{"title_page": "Johnson, Vermont", "text_new": "{{About|the town|the village in the town|Johnson (village), Vermont}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Johnson, Vermont\n|other_name               =\n|native_name              = <!-- for cities whose native name is not in English -->\n|nickname                 =\n|settlement_type          = [[New England town|Town]]\n|motto                    =\n|image_skyline            = Johnson State College Library and \nlearning Center.jpg\n|imagesize                = 250 px\n|image_caption            = [[Northern Vermont University-Johnson]] Library and Buttsex Center\n|image_flag               =\n|flag_size                =\n|image_seal               =\n|seal_size                =\n|image_shield             =\n|shield_size              =\n|image_blank_emblem       =\n|blank_emblem_size        =\n|image_map                = johnson vt highlight.png\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Located in Lamoille County, Vermont\n|image_map1               = Map of USA VT.svg\n|pushpin_map              = USA\n|pushpin_map_caption      = Location in the United States\n|mapsize1                 = 195px\n|map_caption1             = Location of Vermont within the U.S.A.\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Vermont]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Vermont|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Lamoille County, Vermont|Lamoille]]\n|subdivision_type3        =\n|subdivision_name3        =\n|subdivision_type4        =\n|subdivision_name4        =\n|parts_type               = Communities\n|parts                    = [[Johnson (village), Vermont|Johnson]]<br />East Johnson\n|government_footnotes     =\n|government_type          =\n|leader_title             =\n|leader_name              =\n|leader_title1            = <!-- for places with, say, both a mayor and a city manager -->\n|leader_name1             =\n|leader_title2            =\n|leader_name2             =\n|leader_title3            =\n|leader_name3             =\n|leader_title4            =\n|leader_name4             =\n|established_title        = Chartered\n|established_date         = 1792 (Vermont)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vermont-towns.org/Johnson/pagename.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-12-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406171302/http://www.vermont-towns.org/Johnson/pagename.html |archivedate=2012-04-06 }}</ref>\n|area_magnitude           =\n|unit_pref                =  Imperial\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           = 116.8\n|area_land_km2            = 116.8\n|area_water_km2           = >1\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 45.1\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 45.1\n|area_water_sq_mi         = >1\n|area_water_percent       = 0.02\n|population_as_of         = 2010\n|population_footnotes     =\n|population_note          =\n|population_total         = 3446\n|population_density_km2   = 28.0\n|population_density_sq_mi = 72.6\n|population_blank1_title          = Households\n|population_blank1                = 1170\n|population_blank2_title          = Families\n|population_blank2                = 669\n|timezone                 = [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n|utc_offset               = -5\n|timezone_DST             = [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]]\n|utc_offset_DST           = -4\n|coordinates              = {{coord|44|38|38|N|72|40|52|W|region:US-VT|display=inline,title}}\n|coordinates_footnotes    = <ref>{{cite gnis|id=1462129|name=Town of Johnson|accessdate=2009-05-15}}</ref>\n|elevation_footnotes      = <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m              = \n|elevation_ft             = \n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 05656\n|area_code                = [[Area code 802|802]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = \n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 1462129\n|website                  = [http://www.townofjohnson.com/ Johnson Vermont Official Website]\n|footnotes                =\n}}\n<!-- Infobox ends -->\n'''Johnson''' is a [[New England town|town]] in [[Lamoille County, Vermont|Lamoille County]], [[Vermont]], United States. The population was 3,446 at the [[United States Census, 2010|2010 census]].  Johnson is home of [[Northern Vermont University-Johnson]], a part the [[Vermont State Colleges]] system. The [[Vermont Studio Center]] is located in the [[Johnson (village), Vermont|village of Johnson]], a part of the town.\n\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the town has a total area of 45.1&nbsp;square miles (116.8&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>), of which 45.1&nbsp;square&nbsp;miles (116.8&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>) is land and 0.02% is water.\n\n==Town name==\nAccording to Esther Munroe Swift's book \"Vermont Place-names: Footprints of History\" the town of Johnson is named for the American jurist, statesman and educator [[William Samuel Johnson]]. Johnson, Vermont and a part of neighboring [[Cambridge, Vermont|Cambridge]], [[Vermont]] were together known as [[King's College Tract]] being created by a royal charter of British King George III in 1774. The King's College Tract was reserved for the eventual expansion of Kings College in New York, today's [[Columbia University]]. After the Declaration of Independence, Vermont's Council of Censors granted the town to Johnson in 1785.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1790= 93\n|1800= 341\n|1810= 494\n|1820= 778\n|1830= 1079\n|1840= 1410\n|1850= 1381\n|1860= 1526\n|1870= 1558\n|1880= 1495\n|1890= 1462\n|1900= 1391\n|1910= 1526\n|1920= 1478\n|1930= 1378\n|1940= 1420\n|1950= 1527\n|1960= 1478\n|1970= 1927\n|1980= 2581\n|1990= 3156\n|2000= 3274\n|2010= 3446\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=3614\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=January 23, 2020}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html |title=U.S. Decennial Census |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=May 16, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426102944/http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html |archivedate=April 26, 2015 }}</ref>\n}}\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=American FactFinder}}</ref> of 2000, there were 3,274 people, 1,170 households, and 669 families residing in the town. The [[population density]] was 72.6 people per square mile (28.0/km<sup>2</sup>).  There were 1,263 housing units at an average density of 28.0 per square mile (10.8/km<sup>2</sup>).  The racial makeup of the town was 96.58% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.61% [[African American (U.S. Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 0.43% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.67% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.31% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 1.41% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 0.73% of the population.\n\nThere were 1,170 households out of which 30.8% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 41.4% were couples living together and joined in either [[marriage]] or [[Civil Union|civil union]], 10.8% had a female householder with no husband present, and 42.8% were non-families. 28.2% of all households were made up of individuals and 8.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.43 and the average family size was 2.99.\n\nIn the town, the population was spread out with 21.6% under the age of 18, 26.4% from 18 to 24, 25.4% from 25 to 44, 18.2% from 45 to 64, and 8.5% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 26 years. For every 100 females, there were 103.7 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 102.2 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the town was $31,343, and the median income for a family was $38,224. Males had a median income of $28,257 versus $20,610 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the town was $15,014.  About 13.8% of families and 18.9% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 21.6% of those under age 18 and 11.7% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n* Rodgers, Steve. ''Country Towns of Vermont.'' McGraw-Hill: 1998. {{ISBN|1-56626-195-3}}.\n* Strickland, Ron. ''Vermonters: Oral Histories from Down Country to the Northeast Kingdom.'' University Press of New England: 1986. {{ISBN|0-87451-867-9}}.\n* Swift, Esther Monroe. ''Vermont Place Names: Footprints of History.'' The Stephen Greene Press: 1996 {{ISBN|0-8289-0291-7}}.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://townofjohnson.com/ Johnson Vermont Official Town Website]\n* [http://www.johnsonwoolenmills.com/ Johnson Woolen Mills]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061227213731/http://www.jsc.vsc.edu/ Johnson State College]\n* [http://www.vermontstudiocenter.org/ Vermont Studio Center]\n* [http://johnsonconnect.net/ The Johnson Connection: A Business listing site with information about the town.]\n\n{{Lamoille County, Vermont}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Vermont]]\n[[Category:Johnson, Vermont| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Lamoille County, Vermont]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the town|the village in the town|Johnson (village), Vermont}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Johnson, Vermont\n|other_name               =\n|native_name              = <!-- for cities whose native name is not in English -->\n|nickname        