\u0e34\u0e0a\u0e0d\u0e4c |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=leevExpA8ec |website=youtube.com |publisher=GMMTV Records |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\nIn his Twitter interaction with fans, he revealed that his favorite soccer player is [[FC Barcelona|Futbol Club Barcelona]]'s forward, [[Lionel Messi]].<ref>{{cite web |title= #FantalkwithWin|url=https://twitter.com/winmetawin/status/1244627082744713216 |website=twitter.com |publisher=@winmetawin |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\nHe also mentioned that he likes [[durian]].<ref>{{cite web |title= #FantalkwithWin|url=https://twitter.com/winmetawin/status/1244641156874432514 |website=twitter.com |publisher=@winmetawin |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> Their hobbies are Di sports, go to the gym, eat and listen hip hop\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Twitter|winmetawin}}\n* {{Instagram|winmetawin}}\n* {{Weibo | id= 7412472630 | name= Metawin Opas-iamkajorn }}\n* {{IMDb name | nm11456309 | Metawin Opas-Iamkajorn }}\n\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Thai male models]]\n[[Category:21st-century Thai male actors]]\n[[Category:Thai male actors]]\n[[Category:Thai male television actors]]\n[[Category:People from Bangkok]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Thai actor and model}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Metawin Opas-iamkajorn\n| image              = Winmetawin.jpg\n| imagesize          = 250px\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| native_name        = \u0e40\u0e21\u0e18\u0e27\u0e34\u0e19 \u0e42\u0e2d\u0e20\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e40\u0e2d\u0e35\u0e48\u0e22\u0e21\u0e02\u0e08\u0e23\n| native_name_lang   = tha\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1999|02|21}}\n| birth_place        = [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]]\n| alma_mater         = \n| height             = {{height|ft=6|in=0.7}}\n| other_names        = Win\n| occupation         = [[Actor]], [[Model (person)|Model]]\n| years_active       = 2019\u2013present\n| notable_works      = {{plainlist|\n*Tine in ''[[2gether: The Series (Thai TV series)|2gether: The Series]]''\n}}\n| agent              = [[GMMTV]]\n| family             = Mom, DAD, Two older sisters and 1 younger Brother\n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Metawin Opas-iamkajorn''' ({{lang-th|\u0e40\u0e21\u0e18\u0e27\u0e34\u0e19 \u0e42\u0e2d\u0e20\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e40\u0e2d\u0e35\u0e48\u0e22\u0e21\u0e02\u0e08\u0e23}}; also known as '''Win''' ({{lang-th|\u0e27\u0e34\u0e19}}), born February 21, 1999) is a [[Thailand|Thai]] actor and model. He is known for his main role as ''Tine'' in [[GMMTV]]'s ''[[2gether: The Series (Thai TV series)|2gether: The Series]]'' (2020) where he stars as [[Vachirawit Chivaaree]]'s love interest. His fandom name is known as \"Snowball Power\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://instagram.com/winmetawin.official?igshid=vkox4ija2jwt|title=Metawin Opas-iamkajorn's Official Fanclub Instagram Account|last=|first=|date=|website=instagram.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nMetawin was born on February 21, 1999 in [[Bangkok]], Thailand. He completed his secondary education in Panyarat High School where he had the opportunity to become an exchange student in [[Iowa]], [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web |title= #FantalkwithWin|url=https://twitter.com/winmetawin/status/1244628358228365315 |website=twitter.com |publisher=@winmetawin |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> He also passed the [[General Educational Development]] (GED) examination upon his graudation. He is currently taking up Economics (International Program) in [[Thammasat University]].<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0e2a\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e27\u0e31\u0e15\u0e34 \"\u0e27\u0e34\u0e19 \u0e40\u0e21\u0e18\u0e27\u0e34\u0e19\" \u0e2b\u0e23\u0e37\u0e2d \"\u0e44\u0e17\u0e19\u0e4c\" \u0e43\u0e19 \"\u0e40\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e32\u0e30\u0e40\u0e23\u0e32\u0e04\u0e39\u0e48\u0e01\u0e31\u0e19\" |url=https://www.daradaily.com/news/89519/read |website=daradaily.com |publisher=Daradaily |accessdate=20 March 2020 |language=Thai |date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e27\u0e31\u0e15\u0e34 \"\u0e27\u0e34\u0e19 \u0e40\u0e21\u0e18\u0e27\u0e34\u0e19\" \u0e19\u0e31\u0e01\u0e41\u0e2a\u0e14\u0e07\u0e14\u0e32\u0e27\u0e23\u0e38\u0e48\u0e07\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e38\u0e48\u0e21\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e04\u0e27\u0e32\u0e21\u0e2a\u0e39\u0e07 185 \u0e0b\u0e21. \u0e08\u0e32\u0e01\u0e23\u0e31\u0e49\u0e27\u0e18\u0e23\u0e23\u0e21\u0e28\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e15\u0e23\u0e4c\u0e2d\u0e34\u0e19\u0e40\u0e15\u0e2d\u0e23\u0e4c |url=https://www.sanook.com/campus/1399827/ |website=sanook.com |publisher=Sanook |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=Thai |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHis role as ''Tine'' in ''[[2gether: The Series (Thai TV series)|2gether: The Series]]'', where he is being paired with [[Vachirawit Chivaaree]] (Bright), is his first work in the entertainment industry.<ref>{{cite web |title=Biodata Aktor Thailand Win Metawin Opa-iamkajorn |url=https://dianiopiari.com/biodata-aktor-thailand-win-metawin-opas-iamkajorn/ |website=dianiopiari.com |publisher=Diani Opiari |accessdate=20 March 2020 |language=Indonesian |date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\"\u0e27\u0e34\u0e19\" \u0e15\u0e35\u0e1a\u0e17\u0e41\u0e15\u0e01\u0e0b\u0e35\u0e23\u0e35\u0e2a\u0e4c\u0e40\u0e23\u0e37\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e41\u0e23\u0e01 \u0e41\u0e1f\u0e19\u0e46 \u0e40\u0e2d\u0e47\u0e19\u0e14\u0e39\u0e15\u0e34\u0e14\u0e41\u0e2e\u0e0a\u0e41\u0e17\u0e47\u0e01 #\u0e17\u0e35\u0e21\u0e41\u0e21\u0e48\u0e44\u0e17\u0e19\u0e4c \u0e43\u0e19 \"\u0e40\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e32\u0e30\u0e40\u0e23\u0e32\u0e04\u0e39\u0e48\u0e01\u0e31\u0e19\" |url=https://www.sanook.com/movie/96441/ |website=sanook.com |publisher=Sanook |accessdate=20 March 2020 |language=Thai |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, 2020, he reached 1 million followers on [[Instagram]].<ref>{{cite web |title=#\u0e04\u0e31\u0e48\u0e19\u0e01\u0e39 \u0e1e\u0e32\u0e1b\u0e31\u0e07 \"\u0e27\u0e34\u0e19 \u0e40\u0e21\u0e18\u0e27\u0e34\u0e19\" \u0e22\u0e2d\u0e14\u0e1f\u0e2d\u0e25 IG \u0e1e\u0e38\u0e48\u0e07\u0e17\u0e30\u0e25\u0e38\u0e25\u0e49\u0e32\u0e19! |url=https://www.daradaily.com/news/89825/read |website=daradaily.com |publisher=Daradaily |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=Thai |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n! Ref\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | 2020\n| style=\"font-style:italic;\" | [[2gether: The Series (Thai TV series)|2gether: The Series]]\n| Tine\n| Main Role\n| <ref>{{cite web |title=#\u0e04\u0e31\u0e48\u0e19\u0e01\u0e39 \"\u0e40\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e32\u0e30\u0e40\u0e23\u0e32\u0e04\u0e39\u0e48\u0e01\u0e31\u0e19 2gether The Series\" \u0e40\u0e1b\u0e47\u0e19\u0e01\u0e23\u0e30\u0e41\u0e2a \u0e15\u0e31\u0e49\u0e07\u0e41\u0e15\u0e48\u0e17\u0e35\u0e40\u0e0b\u0e2d\u0e23\u0e4c\u0e25\u0e48\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e38\u0e14 \u0e04\u0e31\u0e48\u0e19\u0e01\u0e39 EP1 \u0e23\u0e2d\u0e14\u0e39 \u0e44\u0e1a\u0e23\u0e4c\u0e17\u0e27\u0e34\u0e19 #\u0e2a\u0e32\u0e23\u0e27\u0e31\u0e15\u0e23 #\u0e44\u0e17\u0e19\u0e4c\u0e04\u0e19\u0e0a\u0e34\u0e04 |url=https://medhubnews.com/\u0e14\u0e39\u0e1a\u0e17\u0e04\u0e27\u0e32\u0e21-64752-\u0e04\u0e31\u0e48\u0e19\u0e01\u0e39-\u0e40\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e32\u0e30\u0e40\u0e23\u0e32\u0e04\u0e39\u0e48\u0e01\u0e31\u0e19-2gether-the-series-\u0e40\u0e1b\u0e47\u0e19\u0e01.html |website=medhubnews.com |publisher=Med Hub News |accessdate=21 March 2020 |language=Thai |date=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"font-style:italic;\" | [[School Rangers]]\n| Himself\n| Guest\n| <ref>{{cite web |title=\u0e23\u0e16\u0e42\u0e23\u0e07\u0e40\u0e23\u0e35\u0e22\u0e19 School Rangers [EP.112] \u0e23\u0e23.\u0e40\u0e15\u0e23\u0e35\u0e22\u0e21\u0e2d\u0e38\u0e14\u0e21\u0e28\u0e36\u0e01\u0e29\u0e32\u0e1e\u0e31\u0e12\u0e19\u0e32\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23 \u0e15\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e17\u0e35\u0e48 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x8736B5bkc8 |website=youtube.com |publisher=GMMTV |accessdate=27 March 2020 |language=Thai |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Music Video Appearances===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Song Title\n! Artist\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2020\n| ''Tit Kap (\u0e15\u0e34\u0e14\u0e01\u0e31\u0e1a)'' || [[Natthawut Jenmana]] (Max) || Tine || ''[[2gether: The Series (Thai TV series)|2gether: The Series]]'' opening theme<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0e15\u0e34\u0e14\u0e01\u0e31\u0e1a Ost.\u0e40\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e32\u0e30\u0e40\u0e23\u0e32\u0e04\u0e39\u0e48\u0e01\u0e31\u0e19 2gether The Series - \u0e41\u0e21\u0e47\u0e01\u0e0b\u0e4c \u0e40\u0e08\u0e19\u0e21\u0e32\u0e19\u0e30 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dQaI3VkSCi0 |website=youtube.com |publisher=GMMTV Records |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Khan Ku (\u0e04\u0e31\u0e48\u0e19\u0e01\u0e39) || [[Vachirawit Chivaaree]] (Bright) || Tine || ''[[2gether: The Series (Thai TV series)|2gether: The Series]]'' ending theme<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0e04\u0e31\u0e48\u0e19\u0e01\u0e39 Ost.\u0e40\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e32\u0e30\u0e40\u0e23\u0e32\u0e04\u0e39\u0e48\u0e01\u0e31\u0e19 2gether The Series - \u0e44\u0e1a\u0e23\u0e4c\u0e17 \u0e27\u0e0a\u0e34\u0e23\u0e27\u0e34\u0e0a\u0e0d\u0e4c |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=leevExpA8ec |website=youtube.com |publisher=GMMTV Records |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\nIn his Twitter interaction with fans, he revealed that his favorite soccer player is [[FC Barcelona|Futbol Club Barcelona]]'s forward, [[Lionel Messi]].<ref>{{cite web |title= #FantalkwithWin|url=https://twitter.com/winmetawin/status/1244627082744713216 |website=twitter.com |publisher=@winmetawin |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\nHe also mentioned that he likes [[durian]].<ref>{{cite web |title= #FantalkwithWin|url=https://twitter.com/winmetawin/status/1244641156874432514 |website=twitter.com |publisher=@winmetawin |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> Their hobbies are Di sports, go to the gym, eat and listen hip hop\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Twitter|winmetawin}}\n* {{Instagram|winmetawin}}\n* {{Weibo | id= 7412472630 | name= Metawin Opas-iamkajorn }}\n* {{IMDb name | nm11456309 | Metawin Opas-Iamkajorn }}\n\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Thai male models]]\n[[Category:21st-century Thai male actors]]\n[[Category:Thai male actors]]\n[[Category:Thai male television actors]]\n[[Category:People from Bangkok]]\n", "name_user": "PradaSaetiew", "label": "safe", "comment": "his Vachirawit's last name spelling in English as Chiva-aree, source from his official Instagram @bbrightvc https://www.instagram.com/p/9yMHXeEPL-/?igshid=h5hxparhpcnn", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metawin_Opas-iamkajorn"}
{"title_page": "2013 in Singapore", "text_new": "{{Dynamic list}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Year in Singapore|2013}}\n\nThe following lists events that happened during '''[[2013]] in the [[Singapore|Republic of Singapore]].\n\n== Incumbents ==\n*[[President of Singapore|President]]: [[Tony Tan Keng Yam]]\n*[[Prime Minister of Singapore|Prime Minister]]: [[Lee Hsien Loong]]\n\n==Events==\n===January===\n* 1 January - [[Cheng Lim LRT station]] is opened for service. At the same time, trains on the Sengkang West line will run in both directions too.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sbstransit.com.sg/press/2012-12-21-01.aspx |title=Cheng Lim LRT Station To Open And Sengkang West LRT to Run in Both Directions |website=SBS Transit |access-date=29 August 2019 |date=21 December 2012}}</ref>\n* 2 January - The Personal Data Protection Commission is formed to enforce [[data privacy]] laws.\n* 10 January - The [[North East MRT line]] is disrupted for nearly seven hours between [[HarbourFront MRT station]] to [[Outram Park MRT station]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/1247115/1/.html |title=NEL services fully resumed at 4:35pm: SBS Transit |website=Channel NewsAsia |date=10 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/apps/news/page.aspx?c=2&id=d827b396-5361-4e53-80ff-0ca49164b5cb |title=North East Line Train Service Resumes Full Operation Following Morning Disruption |website=LTA |access-date=6 September 2019 |date=10 January 2013}}</ref>\n* 14 January - [[Halimah Yacob]] is elected [[Speaker of the Parliament of Singapore]], making her the first female speaker in Singapore.<ref>{{cite web |title=PM Lee to nominate Halimah Yacob as next Speaker of Parliament |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/1246664/1/.html |website=CNA |accessdate=25 July 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130111020222/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/1246664/1/.html |archivedate=25 July 2019 |date=8 January 2013}}</ref>\n* 15 January - The [[smoking ban]] is extended to common areas of residential buildings, sheltered linkways and walkways, overhead pedestrian bridges, within 5m of bus stops and outside hospitals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.asiaone.com/print/News/Latest%2BNews/Singapore/Story/A1Story20130112-395047.html |title=Smoking ban to cover 5 more areas |website=Asiaone |accessdate=5 July 2019 |date=14 January 2013}}</ref>\n* 17 January - The [[Land Transport Authority]] announced several new MRT lines to be built, doubling the total MRT network to {{Convert|360|km|miles|abbr=in}} by 2030. They are the [[Jurong Region MRT line]], [[Downtown MRT line]] extension and [[Circle MRT line]] Stage 6 by 2025, [[North East MRT line]] extension to Punggol North and [[Cross Island MRT line]] by 2030, as well as a possible new station on the [[North South MRT line]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Speech%20by%20Mr%20Lui%20Tuck%20Yew%20at%20visit%20to%20DTL1%20Chinatown%20Station%20on%2017%20January%202013/ |title=Speech by Mr Lui Tuck Yew at visit to DTL1 Chinatown Station on 17 January 2013 |website=MOT |accessdate=19 September 2019 |date=17 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/more-new-mrt-lines-to-be-built-by-2030 |title=More new MRT lines to be built by 2030 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=25 May 2019 |date=17 January 2013}}</ref> A section of the Cross Island Line is to run under the [[Central Catchment Nature Reserve]], sparking a controversy with nature groups.\n* 21 January - \n**[[MediaCorp Channel NewsAsia]] begins broadcasting 24 hours daily.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.onscreenasia.com/article/channel-newsasia-relaunches/11424|title=Channel NewsAsia relaunches|date=21 January 2013|accessdate=21 January 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413140620/http://www.onscreenasia.com/article/channel-newsasia-relaunches/11424|archivedate=13 April 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n**1-week [[paternity leave]] is introduced as part of enhancements to the Marriage and Parenthood package, taking effect on 1 May. The leave can also be shared with mums too, and is extended to 2 weeks in 2015. Other measures include a four-week mandatory adoption leave, two days of childcare leave per year for parents of those aged seven to 12 years old, extending maternity protection to an entire pregnancy, and allowing expectant mothers not eligible for leave to claim a cash benefit substitute.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/1-week-government-paid-paternity-leave-now-part-of-parenthood-package-0 |title=1 week Government-paid paternity leave now part of parenthood package |website=The Straits Times  |accessdate=1 July 2019 |date=21 January 2013}}</ref>\n* 22 January - [[Singapore Institute of Technology]]'s campus at [[Nanyang Polytechnic]], known as SIT@NYP, starts construction, which will finish by 2014. The building will house the [[Newcastle University]], [[Trinity College Dublin]] and [[The University of Manchester]].<ref>{{cite web |title=SIT@NYP Groundbreaking Ceremony |url=https://www.singaporetech.edu.sg/digitalnewsroom/sitnyp-groundbreaking-ceremony/ |website=SIT |accessdate=15 September 2019 |date=22 January 2013}}</ref>\n* 26 January - [[Lee Li Lian]], representing the main opposition of [[Workers' Party (Singapore)|Workers' Party]], was elected as Member-of-Parliament (MP) for [[Punggol East Single Member Constituency]] as a result of winning the [[2013 Punggol East by-election]], succeeding the ruling [[People's Action Party]]'s MP [[Michael Palmer (politician)|Michael Palmer]], who earlier vacated his seat on 12 December last year because of an [[extramarital affair]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Au Yong |first1=Jeremy |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/workers-party-wins-punggol-east-by-election-with-5452-of-valid-votes |title=Workers' Party wins Punggol East by-election with 54.52% of valid votes |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=26 March 2020 |date=26 January 2013}}</ref> Lee is sworn into Parliament on 4 February.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ong |first1=Andrea |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/workers-partys-lee-li-lian-sworn-in-as-the-new-mp-for-punggol-east |title=Workers' Party's Lee Li Lian sworn in as the new MP for Punggol East |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=26 March 2020 |date=4 February 2013}}</ref>\n* 29 January - \n**The [[Population White Paper]] (a [[White Paper]] focusing on [[Demographics of Singapore|population]]) is released. The report projects a future population of 6.9 million by 2030, with 3 strategies proposed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cheam |first1=Jessica |title=Singapore's population could hit 6.9m by 2030 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/singapores-population-could-hit-69m-by-2030-0 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=7 July 2019 |date=29 January 2013}}</ref> The report's findings have caused controversy, culminating in a protest on 16 February which attracted 4,000 people.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rare mass rally over Singapore immigration plans |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-21485729 |website=BBC |accessdate=7 July 2019 |date=16 February 2013}}</ref>\n**[[Singapore Institute of Technology]]'s campus at [[Republic Polytechnic]], known as SIT@RP, starts construction, which will finish by 2014. The building will house the [[University of Glasgow]]. It is the tallest SIT building at nine storeys tall.<ref>{{cite web |title=SIT@RP Groundbreaking Ceremony |url=https://www.singaporetech.edu.sg/digitalnewsroom/sitrp-groundbreaking-ceremony/ |website=SIT |accessdate=15 September 2019 |date=29 January 2013}}</ref>\n* 30 January - Thai tycoon [[Charoen Sirivadhanabhakdi]] wins control of [[Fraser and Neave]] (F&N), a [[property]], [[food & beverage]] firm.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/thai-tycoon-wins-control-of-singapores-fraser-and-neave |title=Thai tycoon wins control of Singapore's Fraser and Neave |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=1 July 2019 |date=31 January 2013}}</ref>\n* 31 January - \n**The [[Ministry of National Development (Singapore)|Ministry of National Development]] released a Land Use Plan for land use changes towards 2030. Among them are more new towns, more green spaces, reclamation of land, acquisition of golf courses, moving of defence activities to [[Pulau Tekong]], and two new commercial hubs (the North Coast Innovation Corridor and Southern Waterfront City).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chang |first1=Rachel |title=Plan to grow space for rising population |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/plan-to-grow-space-for-rising-population |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=7 July 2019 |date=31 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Chang |first1=Rachel |title=5,600 hectares more land for bigger population: Land Use Plan |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/5600-hectares-more-land-for-bigger-population-land-use-plan-0 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=7 July 2019 |date=31 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Chin |first1=Daryl |title=Golf courses to make way for growing population |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/golf-courses-to-make-way-for-growing-population-0 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=7 December 2019 |date=31 January 2013}}</ref>\n**[[library@chinatown]] opens in [[Chinatown Point]].\n\n===February=== \n* 1 February - [[MediaCorp]] launches [[Toggle.sg|Toggle]], an [[over-the-top media services|over-the-top service (OTT)]].<ref>{{cite web |title=MediaCorp launches Toggle, its personal entertainment service on multiple devices |url=https://www.mediacorp.sg/en/corporate/mediacorp-in-the-news/media-releases/mediacorp-launches-toggle-its-personal-e-5855908 |website=Mediacorp |accessdate=7 July 2019 |date=1 February 2013}}</ref>\n* 8 February - Parliament convenes a special session to debate the controversial [[Population White Paper]] (a [[White Paper]] focusing on [[Demographics of Singapore|population]]), released earlier in January.\n* 9 February - [[Eng Wah Global|WE Cinemas]] will close both of its cinemas in [[West Mall]] and [[Suntec City]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Boon |first1=Rachael |title=Eng Wah exits Suntec and West Mall |url=https://www.asiaone.com/print/News/Latest%2BNews/Singapore/Story/A1Story20130207-400778.html |accessdate=14 August 2019 |website=The Straits Times |date=9 February 2013}}</ref>\n* 10 February - [[MediaCorp TV]] celebrates its 50-year anniversary since being established in 1963 (before on 16 February). \n* 14 February - Former [[Central Narcotics Bureau]] chief Ng Boon Gay is acquitted from a sex-for-contracts case.<ref>{{cite web |title=Former CNB chief Ng Boon Gay acquitted |url=https://sg.news.yahoo.com/former-cnb-chief-ng-boon-gay-acquitted-072825790.html |accessdate=7 July 2019 |website=Yahoo |date=14 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Lim |first1=Joyce |last2=Tham |first2=Yuen-C |title=Ng Boon Gay verdict: Court finds ex-CNB chief not guilty of corruption |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/ng-boon-gay-verdict-court-finds-ex-cnb-chief-not-guilty-of-corruption |accessdate=21 October 2019 |website=The Straits Times |date=14 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Tham |first1=Yuen-C |title=Ng Boon Gay's \"not guilty\" verdict: Judge says Cecilia Sue's testimony not believable |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/ng-boon-gays-not-guilty-verdict-judge-says-cecilia-sues-testimony-not-believable |accessdate=21 October 2019 |website=The Straits Times |date=14 February 2013}}</ref>\n* 19 February - Singapore and [[Malaysia]] agree to build the [[Penang\u2013Singapore High Speed Rail|high-speed rail link]] between the city-state island republic and mainland towards [[Kuala Lumpur]].<ref>{{cite news |title=PMs agree on high speed rail linking KL, Singapore |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/pms-agree-on-high-speed-rail-linking-kl-singapore |accessdate=4 August 2019 |website=The Straits Times |date=19 February 2013}}</ref>\n* 21 February - [[Uber]] launches its services in Singapore.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hardwarezone.com.sg/tech-news-uber-app-officially-launches-singapore |title=Uber App Officially Launches in Singapore |website=Hardware Zone Singapore |date=21 February 2013 |accessdate=27 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n* 1 March - The [[Sesame Street Spaghetti Space Chase]] is officially opened at [[Universal Studios Singapore]].<ref>{{cite news|title=USS Sesame Street theme park ride to open on March 1 |url=http://www.asiaone.com/print/News/Latest%2BNews/Relax/Story/A1Story20130218-402877.html|accessdate=2 March 2013|newspaper=Asia One|date=18 February 2013}}</ref>\n* 13 March - The [[Ministry of Education (Singapore)|Ministry of Education]] announced that 15 MOE Kindergartens will be set up over the next three years, with the first 5 opening next year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/budget-2013-15-moe-run-kindergartens-to-be-set-up-over-the-next-three-years-0 |title=Budget 2013: 15 MOE-run kindergartens to be set up over the next three years |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=1 July 2019 |date=13 March 2013}}</ref>\n* 14 March - The [[Ministry of Social and Family Development]] announced the setting up of 20 Social Service Offices (SSOs) to help needy Singaporeans.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.msf.gov.sg/media-room/Pages/Social-Service-Offices-to-be-set-up-in-HDB-towns-to-strengthen-delivery-of-social-services-to-needy-Singaporean.aspx |title=Social Service Offices To Be Set Up In HDB Towns To Strengthen Delivery Of Social Services To Needy Singaporeans |website=MSF |accessdate=11 July 2019 |date=14 March 2013}}</ref>\n* 15 March - Singaporeans and PRs will get free museum entry from 18 May to promote Singapore's heritage.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Huang |first1=Lijie |title=Budget 2013: Free museum entry from May for all Singaporeans, PRs |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/budget-2013-free-museum-entry-from-may-for-all-singaporeans-prs-0 |publisher=The Straits Times |accessdate=25 July 2019 |date=15 March 2013}}</ref>\n* 31 March - [[MediaCorp TV Channel 5]] celebrates its 50-year anniversary since being established in 1963 (before on 2 April).\n\n===April===\n* 1 April - \n**The [[Singapore Accountancy Commission]] is formed to regulate the accountancy sector.\n**The [[Early Childhood Development Agency]] is formed to oversee both kindergartens and childcare centres. ECDA is overseen by both the [[Ministry of Education (Singapore)|Ministry of Education]] and [[Ministry of Social and Family Development]], being housed in the latter.<ref>{{cite web |title=Launch of The Early Childhood Development Agency (ECDA) |url=https://www.moe.gov.sg/news/press-releases/launch-of-the-early-childhood-development-agency-ecda |website=MOE |accessdate=20 September 2019 |date=27 March 2013}}</ref>\n**All 57 [[Cold Storage (supermarket)#Shop N Save|Shop N Save]] supermarkets are rebranded to [[Giant Hypermarket|Giant]], except for the [[West Mall]] store, which will become a [[Cold Storage (supermarket)|Cold Storage]] store.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kham |first1=Priscilla |title=Shop n Save supermarket outlets to be converted to Giant stores |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/shop-n-save-supermarket-outlets-to-be-converted-to-giant-stores |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=23 August 2019 |date=1 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n===May===\n* 2 May - Construction works commenced on the [[Tanjong Pagar Centre]], a [[mixed-use]] tower. It will be the [[tallest building in Singapore]] at a height of 290m, more than [[One Raffles Place]], [[Republic Plaza (Singapore)|Republic Plaza]] and [[UOB Plaza One]], standing at 280m (the maximum allowed in Singapore). The building is completed in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/tanjong-pagar-centre-set-to-be-singapores-tallest-building-at-290m |title=Tanjong Pagar Centre set to be Singapore's tallest building at 290m |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=1 July 2019 |date=3 May 2013}}</ref>\n* 15 May - \n**[[City Harvest Church Criminal Breach of Trust Case]]: A 140-day-long trial involving [[Kong Hee]] and five other pastors, who were arrested on June 2012 over alleged misuse of funds, begins.\n**The [[Marina Bay Financial Centre]] is officially opened as a new business hub.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pmo.gov.sg/Newsroom/speech-prime-minister-lee-hsien-loong-official-opening-marina-bay-financial-centre |title=Official Opening of Marina Bay Financial Centre |website=PMO |accessdate=16 July 2019 |date=15 May 2013}}</ref>\n**[[Singapore Kindness Movement]] retires [[Singa the Lion|Singa the Courtesy Lion]] through a resignation letter.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/singa-the-courtesy-lion-i-quit |title=Singa the Courtesy Lion: 'I quit' |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=6 August 2019 |date=15 May 2013}}</ref>\n* 27 May - Filmmaker [[Anthony Chen]] snags a [[Camera d'Or]] for the film [[Ilo Ilo]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.todayonline.com/blogs/ratedg/singapore-film-ilo-ilo-wins-historic-cannes-prize |title=Singapore film Ilo Ilo wins historic Cannes prize |website=Today |accessdate=6 May 2019 |date=27 May 2013}}</ref> The film is eventually shown in cinemas from 29 August.\n* 28 May - Former [[National University of Singapore|NUS]] professor Tey Tsun Hang is found guilty in a sex-for-grades case, and thus sentenced to a 5-month jail term.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Singh |first1=Bryna |last2=Sim |first2=Walter |title=Law professor Tey Tsun Hang 'guilty' on all six counts of corruption in sex-for-grades case |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/law-professor-tey-tsun-hang-guilty-on-all-six-counts-of-corruption-in-sex-for-grades-case |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=7 July 2019 |date=28 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Singh |first1=Bryna |title=Sex for grades case: Former law professor Tey Tsun Hang begins his 5-month jail term |url=https://www.asiaone.com/News/Latest%2BNews/Singapore/Story/A1Story20130626-432536.html |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=7 July 2019 |date=26 June 2013}}</ref> The conviction is subsequently overturned in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lum |first1=Selina |title=Ex-law prof Tey Tsun Hang cleared of corruption by High Court |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/ex-law-prof-tey-tsun-hang-cleared-of-corruption-by-high-court |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=7 July 2019 |date=28 February 2014}}</ref>\n* 29 May - [[2013 dengue outbreak in Singapore]]: A man from [[Hougang]] dies from dengue shock syndrome; the first reported death case relating to dengue in Singapore this year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/dengue-claims-first-life-in-current-epid/692484.html |title=Dengue claims first life in current epidemic |accessdate=9 June 2013 |author=Sara Grosse |date=30 May 2013 |website=Channel NewsAsia}}</ref>\n* 31 May \u2013 Peter Lim Sim Pang, a former [[Singapore Civil Defence Force]] commissioner, is found guilty in a sex-for-contracts scandal involving three women, subsequently sentenced on 13 June to six months in jail.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ex-SCDF chief Peter Lim found guilty of corruption |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/ex-scdf-chief-peter-lim-found-guilty-of-corruption |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=10 August 2019 |date=31 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Sex-for-contracts trial: 6 months' jail for former SCDF chief Peter Lim |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/sex-for-contracts-trial-6-months-jail-for-former-scdf-chief-peter-lim |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=10 August 2019 |date=13 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n===June===\n* 12 June - After a series of financial troubles, the Changi Motorsports Hub project is called off.<ref>{{cite web |title=Changi Motorsports Hub called off |url=https://www.myactivesg.com/read/2013/6/changi-motorsports-hub-called-off |website=Singapore Sports Council |accessdate=26 July 2019 |date=12 June 2013}}</ref>\n* 15 June - [[Jem, Singapore|Jem]] opens its doors.\n* Mid-June: [[2013 Southeast Asian haze]]: Singapore sees its worst haze since [[1997 Southeast Asian haze|1997]]:\n** 17 June: At about 10pm, the 3-hour [[Pollutant Standards Index]] (PSI) levels reading reached an unhealthy range of 155 after air quality plummeted into the \"Unhealthy\" range at 2pm.<ref>{{cite web |title=Worst haze in 16 years, with PSI hitting 155 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/worst-haze-in-16-years-with-psi-hitting-155 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=13 September 2019 |date=18 June 2013}}</ref>\n** 19 June: At 9pm, the 3-hour PSI reaches 290, surpassing the previous record of 226 in [[1997 Southeast Asian haze|1997]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Feng |first1=Zengkun |title=Haze in Singapore hits historical high, PSI at 290 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/haze-in-singapore-hits-historical-high-psi-at-290 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=13 September 2019 |date=19 June 2013}}</ref> At 10pm, the 3-hour PSI reading reaches 321 marking the first time air quality reached \"Hazardous\" levels.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Feng |first1=Zengkun |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/breaking-news/singapore/story/haze-singapore-hits-new-high-psi-321-10pm-20130619 |title=S'pore PSI hits all-time high, PSI at 321 at 10pm |publisher=The Straits Times |date=19 June 2013 |accessdate=19 June 2013}}</ref>\n** 20 June: At about 1pm, the 3-hour PSI reading reaches 371.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/haze-reaches-hazardous/717772.html |title=Haze reaches hazardous level; PSI hits 371 |website=Channel NewsAsia |date=20 June 2013 |accessdate=20 June 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130822084746/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/haze-reaches-hazardous/717772.html |archivedate=22 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Feng |first1=Zengkun |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/haze-update-psi-climbs-to-new-high-of-371-at-1pm-on-thursday |title=Haze update: PSI climbs to new high of 371 at 1pm on Thursday |website=The Straits Times |date=20 June 2013 |accessdate=13 September 2013}}</ref>\n** 21 June - The 3-hour PSI reaches 400 at 11am,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=Pearl |title=Haze update: PSI hits another new high of 400 at 11am on Friday |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/haze-update-psi-hits-another-new-high-of-400-at-11am-on-friday |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=13 September 2019 |date=21 June 2013}}</ref> peaking at 401 at 12pm. This makes it the highest PSI reading in history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/psi-hits-new-all-time/719496.html |title=PSI hits new all-time high of 401 on Friday |website=Channel NewsAsia |date=21 June 2013 |accessdate=21 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624015317/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/psi-hits-new-all-time/719496.html |archivedate=24 June 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Yong |first1=Charissa |title=Haze update: PSI 401 at noon; many pharmacies still out of masks |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/haze-update-psi-401-at-noon-many-pharmacies-still-out-of-masks |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=13 September 2019 |date=21 June 2013}}</ref>\n* 25 June - The third series of Singapore's coins is released.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/new-singapore-third/705544.html |title=New Singapore Third Series coins available at banks from June 25 |website=Channel NewsAsia |date=11 June 2013 |accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref> However, old coins from the 1st and 2nd series remain legal tender.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Singapore Third Series Coins |url=http://www.todayonline.com/videos/singapore-third-series-coins |website=Today |date=21 February 2013 |accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n===July===\n* 27 July - The [[National Environment Agency]] announced that the Tray Return Initiative will be rolled out to all hawker centres in three phases. This comes after a successful trial in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tray Return Initiative To Roll Out To All Hawker Centres |url=https://www.nea.gov.sg/media/news/news/index/tray-return-initiative-to-roll-out-to-all-hawker-centres |website=NEA |accessdate=7 August 2019 |date=27 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n===August===\n* 5 August - [[2013 dengue outbreak in Singapore]]: The number of reported dengue cases reached about 14,000 at the time (including six deaths), surpassing the former record of 14,209 cases from [[2005 dengue outbreak in Singapore|2005]]. This becomes the worst dengue epidemic in Singapore, with a total 22,318 cases (including eight deaths) logged by end-2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/news/asia/354695/singapore-fights-back-against-worsening-dengue-outbreak.html |title=Singapore fights back against worsening dengue outbreak |accessdate=12 June 2013 |date=12 June 2013 |work=Bangkok Post}}</ref>\n* 15 August - [[CleanTech Park|CleanTech One]] is officially opened, boosting the eco industry in Singapore.<ref>{{cite web |title=Opening Ceremony of CleanTech One |url=http://jtc.gov.sg/News/Pages/20130815(SP2).aspx |website=JTC |accessdate=20 August 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140626062708/http://jtc.gov.sg/News/Pages/20130815(SP2).aspx |archivedate=26 June 2014 |date=15 August 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 18 August - Plans are unveiled to build [[Jewel Changi Airport|Project Jewel]] and [[Infrastructure of Singapore Changi Airport|Changi T5]] (including a third runway). In addition, all port activities will be consolidated in Tuas to create a Southern Waterfront City, and [[Paya Lebar Air Base]] will move to Changi East Air Base to free up land and lift height restrictions around the area.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sg.news.yahoo.com/amphtml/paya-lebar-air-base-to-move-to-changi-east-152738932.html |title=NDR 2013: Paya Lebar Air Base to move to Changi East, new plans for Changi Terminal 5 |website=Yahoo |date=18 August 2013 |accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/ndr-2013-paya-lebar-airbase-to-be-moved-to-changi-area-freed-up-for-homes-and-industry |title=NDR 2013: Paya Lebar Airbase to be moved to Changi, area freed up for homes and industry |website=The Straits Times |date=18 August 2013 |accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/terminal-5-will-double-changi-airports-capacity-pm-lee|title=Terminal 5 will double Changi Airport\u2019s capacity: PM Lee|work=TODAYonline|access-date=2018-01-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180117190432/http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/terminal-5-will-double-changi-airports-capacity-pm-lee|archive-date=2018-01-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 19 August - The [[Ministry of Education (Singapore)|Ministry of Education]] announced that 40 places will be reserved in each primary school for those without prior ties to the school. This move aims to increase opportunities for those to study in popular schools and integration.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.moe.gov.sg/news/press-releases/40-places-reserved-to-ensure-open-access-to-all-primary-schools |title=40 Places Reserved to Ensure Open Access to All Primary Schools |website=MOE |date=19 August 2013 |accessdate=9 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 29 August - The [[Housing and Development Board]] (HDB) unveils new housing plans for Bidadari, Tampines North and Punggol Matilda.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/ambitious-plans-for-3-new-hdb-projects |title=Ambitious plans for 3 new HDB projects |website=[[The Straits Times]] |date=30 August 2013 |accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref>\n* 30 August - The [[Ministry of Health (Singapore)|Ministry of Health]] announced [[Health City Novena]], a new health complex in central Singapore. The 17-hectare complex will have 10 buildings connected by bridges and underground links, which will be fully completed by 2030.<ref>{{cite web |title=Official Launch of Health City Novena |url=https://www.moh.gov.sg/news-highlights/details/speech-by-health-minister-gan-kim-yong-at-the-official-launch-of-health-city-novena-30-aug-2013 |website=MOH |accessdate=20 September 2019 |date=30 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/singapores-largest-healthcare-complex-planned-novena-area |title=Singapore's largest healthcare complex planned for Novena area |website=Todayonline |accessdate=25 May 2019 |date=30 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n===September===\n* 2 September - The [[Energy Market Authority]] imposes a $1.5m fine for a gas leak on Jurong Island on 23 April 2012.<ref>{{cite web |title=$1.5 million penalty imposed on PowerGas Ltd for gas leak incident on 23 April 2012 |url=https://www.ema.gov.sg/Gas_Regulatory_Updates.aspx |website=EMA |date=2 September 2013 |accessdate=28 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 5 September - [[Floods in Singapore#2013|Flash floods]] strikes western Singapore due to heavy rain, causing a section of [[AYE]] to close.<ref>{{cite web |title=Flash floods hit several areas in western Singapore |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/flash-floods-several-areas-western-singapore |website=Todayonline |date=5 September 2013 |accessdate=28 July 2019}}</ref> As a result, the [[Public Utilities Board]] announced the building of tidal gates and expansion of the canal to take in more rain.<ref>{{cite web |title=AYE flooding: Tidal gate to be built at expressway-adjacent canal |url=https://sg.news.yahoo.com/-not-acceptable--for-major-expressway-to-close-due-to-flooding--minister-balakrishnan-151937577.html |website=Yahoo |date=5 September 2013 |accessdate=28 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 13 September - The [[Expressway Monitoring and Advisory System]] signs will be upgraded to be more readable with different colours and display real-time traffic information to help motorists make better decisions. The exercise will be completed by 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/lta-replace-all-electronic-signboards-expressways-2017 |title=LTA to upgrade electronic signboards on expressways |website=Today |accessdate=11 July 2019 |date=13 September 2013}}</ref>\n* 18 September - The Tuaspring Desalination Plant is officially opened.<ref>{{cite web |title=Speech by Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong at the official opening of Tuaspring Desalination Plant |url=https://www.pmo.gov.sg/Newsroom/speech-prime-minister-lee-hsien-loong-official-opening-tuaspring-desalination-plant |website=PMO |date=18 September 2013 |accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref>\n* 23 September - The [[Fair Consideration Framework]] is announced in a bid to ensure Singaporeans have fair opportunities for jobs.\n* 30 September - \n**[[MediaCorp Teletext]] ceases transmission due to declining usage. In its heyday, Teletext served as a platform to receive news and information about Singapore.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/teletext-end-service-month |title=Teletext to end service this month |website=Today |access-date=20 September 2019 |date=3 September 2013}}</ref>\n**Dolphin Island opens at the Marine Life Park at [[Resorts World Sentosa]], featuring bottlenose dolphins.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ee |first1=David |title=Resorts World Sentosa's Dolphin Island to open on Sept 30 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/resorts-world-sentosas-dolphin-island-to-open-on-sept-30 |website=The Straits Times |date=19 September 2013 |accessdate=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===October===\n*October to November - [[2013 Singapore cyberattacks]]: Many of the cyberattacks occurred in Singapore, a [[YouTube]] video, made of [[Anonymus Hacker Group]]'s The Messiah threatening the [[Singapore government]]. Affected websites include the [[PAP Community Foundation]], the [[Ang Mo Kio Group Representation Constituency|Ang Mo Kio Town Council]] page (a town council led by the Prime Minister [[Lee Hsien Loong]]), [[Yahoo!]] Singapore, [[Seletar Airport]], [[Prime Minister's Office (Singapore)|Prime Minister's Office]] and [[The Istana]], as well as 13 schools on a single server.\n* 4 October - A penny stock crash occurs on the [[Singapore Exchange]] (SGX), causing a S$8 billion wipeout involving 3 stocks. The [[Monetary Authority of Singapore]], SGX and [[Commercial Affairs Department]] had commenced investigations on that, resulting in 3 arrests.<ref>{{cite web |title=Singapore launches probe into penny stocks crash |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2013/10/24/singapore-launches-probe-into-penny-stocks-crash.html |website=CNBC |date=24 October 2013 |accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=3 arrested over 2013 penny stock crash |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/business/companies-markets/3-arrested-over-penny-stock-crash |website=The Straits Times |date=25 November 2016 |accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref> All have since been slapped with charges with 1 sentenced to jail in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Finance manager in scheme that triggered S$8 billion penny stock crash in 2013 gets jail |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/finance-manager-in-scheme-that-triggered-s-8-billion-penny-stock-11362522 |website=Channel NewsAsia |accessdate=5 May 2019 |date=20 March 2019}}</ref>\n* 7 October - \n**The Land Transport Master Plan 2013 is released, which will include 200&nbsp;km of sheltered walkways, 700&nbsp;km of cycling paths, more ITHs, more trains and buses, an upgraded signalling system and more lifts.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/apps/news/page.aspx?c=2&id=a3ba8ffe-988a-43f7-8881-32d8f9c46416 |title=Launch of Land Transport Master Plan 2013 |website=LTA |accessdate=11 July 2019 |date=7 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/land-transport-masterplan-2013-20-things-you-need-to-know |title=Land Transport Masterplan 2013: 20 things you need to know |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=1 November 2019 |date=7 October 2013}}</ref>\n**Veteran National football player and coach, [[V. Sundramoorthy]] resigns as [[LionsXII]] and [[Singapore national under-23 football team|National U-23]] coach. He is replaced by [[Fandi Ahmad]] on 7 December.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sundram resigns as LionsXII and National U-23 coach |url=http://www.todayonline.com/sports/football/sundram-resigns-lionsxii-and-national-u-23-coach |website=Today |date=7 October 2013 |accessdate=7 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/sport/football-fandi-ahmad/913868.html |title=Football: Fandi Ahmad appointed LionsXII head coach |website=[[Channel NewsAsia]] |accessdate=17 January 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219054345/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/sport/football-fandi-ahmad/913868.html |archivedate=19 December 2013}}</ref>\n* 10 October - [[StarHub]] launches SuperSports Arena (renamed to [[Hub Sports Arena]]) for all households in Singapore to promote Singapore sports.<ref>{{cite web |title=StarHub and Singapore Sports Council Bring More Local Sports Content to Singaporeans |url=https://www.starhub.com/about-us/newsroom/2013/october/starhub-and-singapore-sports-council-bring-more-local-sports-con.html |website=StarHub |accessdate=5 August 2019 |date=8 October 2013}}</ref>\n* 17 October - [[National University of Singapore]]'s U Town is officially opened, encouraging students and professors to learn and live together.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nus.edu.sg/president/pdf/utownopening.pdf |title=Official Opening of University Town |website=NUS |accessdate=22 July 2019 |date=17 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/local-universities-have-wider-national-and-social-mission-beyond-academics-pm-lee |title=Local universities have wider national and social mission beyond academics: PM Lee |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=22 July 2019 |date=17 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Official Opening of University Town |url=https://www.pmo.gov.sg/Newsroom/speech-prime-minister-lee-hsien-loong-official-opening-university-town |website=PMO |accessdate=9 August 2019 |date=17 October 2013}}</ref>\n* 21 October - [[GrabTaxi]] is launched in Singapore, making it the second [[ride-hailing]] service here.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hardwarezone.com.sg/tech-news-grabtaxi-regions-largest-taxi-booking-mobile-app-beta-launches-singapore |title=GrabTaxi, Region's Largest Taxi-booking Mobile App, Beta Launches in Singapore |website=Hardware Zone Singapore |accessdate=27 June 2019 |date=21 October 2013}}</ref>\n* 24 October - The [[Singapore Institute of Technology]] (SIT) announced a slew of its own degree programmes which will start from 2014. This is in preparation of SIT becoming the fifth autonomous university in Singapore, as it currently offers degree programmes with foreign universities.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.singaporetech.edu.sg/digitalnewsroom/sit-to-launch-its-own-applied-degrees-in-2014-to-develop-best-in-class-industry-specialists/ |title=SIT to launch its own applied degrees in 2014 to develop 'best-in-class' industry specialists |website=SIT |date=24 October 2013|accessdate=11 September 2019}}</ref>\n* 25 October - The Disease Outbreak Response System Condition (DORSCON) is revised to consider severity of diseases in addition to the spread of diseases in Singapore. Control measures are made more flexible with four colour alerts instead of five, allowing the framework to be used for both mild and severe diseases.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kok |first1=Xing Hui |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/singapore-revises-outbreak-response-system |title=Singapore revises outbreak response system |website=Today |date=25 October 2013 |accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref>\n* 27 October - The [[Sengkang General Hospital]] and [[Sengkang Community Hospital]] have started construction, first announced in 2011 by the [[Ministry of Health (Singapore)|Ministry of Health]]. These hospitals will be completed by 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=Groundbreaking Ceremony for Sengkang General and Community Hospitals |url=https://www.moh.gov.sg/news-highlights/details/speech-by-mr-gan-kim-yong-minister-for-health-at-the-groundbreaking-ceremony-for-sengkang-general-and-community-hospitals-on-sunday-27-october-2013 |website=MOH |accessdate=20 September 2019 |date=27 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Work begins on new general hospital in Sengkang |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/breaking-news/singapore/story/work-has-begun-new-general-hospital-the-north-one-four-be-built-2030-2 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=4 May 2014 |date=27 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Sengkang General and Community Hospitals and will add 1,400 beds to national healthcare system when completed in 2018 |url=http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/new-sengkang-hospitals-will-boast-1400-beds |website=Today |accessdate=4 May 2014 |date=27 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===November===\n* 8 November - [[Institute of Technical Education|ITE's]] new headquarters and [[ITE College Central]] in Ang Mo Kio is officially opened, marking the completion of the 'One ITE System, Three Colleges' initiative.<ref>{{cite web |title=Review to better match ITE, poly skills to jobs |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/breaking-news/singapore/story/review-polytechnics-and-ites-improve-students-job-and-academic-prospec |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=12 May 2019 |date=8 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Official Opening of ITE Headquarters and ITE College Central |url=https://www.pmo.gov.sg/Newsroom/speech-prime-minister-lee-hsien-loong-official-opening-ite-headquarters-and-ite-college |website=PMO |accessdate=9 August 2019 |date=8 November 2013}}</ref>\n* 12 November - [[2013 Singapore cyberattacks]]: James Raj, the mastermind who is alleged \"The Messiah\", is charged in Singapore court.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/suspected-messiah-hacker-charged-court |title=Suspected 'Messiah' hacker charged in court |website=[[Today (Singapore newspaper)|Today]] |date=12 November 2013}}</ref> He has since been found guilty and sentenced to 56 months jail in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |title='Messiah' hacker jailed for computer misuse, taking drugs |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/messiah-hacker-jailed-56-months |website=Today |date=30 January 2015 |accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref>\n* 14 November - The [[Ministry of Education (Singapore)|Ministry of Education]] announced a trial of Subject-Based Banding in 12 secondary schools from 2014.<ref>{{cite web |title=Greater Flexibility In Secondary School Subject Offering |url=https://www.moe.gov.sg/news/press-releases/greater-flexibility-in--secondary-school-subject-offering |website=MOE |date=14 November 2013 |accessdate=11 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 24 November - [[MediaCorp TV Channel 8]] celebrates its 50-year anniversary since being established on 23 November 1963.\n* 30 November - The first Purple Parade is held to raise awareness of the special needs community.<ref>{{cite web |title=Very special Purple Parade for the special needs community |url=https://www.asiaone.com/health/very-special-purple-parade-special-needs-community |website=Asiaone |date=4 December 2013 |accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===December===\n* 2 December - [[Westgate, Singapore|Westgate Mall]] opened its doors.\n* 3 December - [[Bedok Mall]] opened its doors.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bedok Mall opens its doors with new brands and renowned restaurants |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/bedok-mall-opens-its-doors-with-new-brands-and-renowned-restaurants |website=The Straits Times |date=3 December 2013 |accessdate=27 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 8 December - [[2013 Little India riots]]: A riot broke out on the streets of [[Little India, Singapore|Little India]], with 27 arrests, many injuries and several emergency vehicles overturned. One bus front windscreen was smashed. This was the second riot in post-independence Singapore, after the [[1969 race riots of Singapore|race riots in 1969]].\n* 18 December - A near four-hour disruption of services for [[Circle MRT Line]] for 23 out of 28 stations <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/train-service-disrupted-23-circle-line-stations |title=Train services at 23 Circle Line stations restored after power failure |website=[[Today (Singapore newspaper)]] |accessdate=17 January 2014}}</ref>\n* 22 December - Opening of the [[Downtown MRT Line]] Stage 1, stretching from [[Bugis MRT station]] to [[Bayfront MRT station|Bayfront]] and [[Chinatown MRT station]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Downtown Line Stage 1 to open on Dec 22 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/downtown-line-stage-1-to-open-on-dec-22 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=6 September 2019 |date=7 October 2013}}</ref>\n* 29 December - Opening of the [[Marina Coastal Expressway]] (MCE), Singapore first undersea expressway. The expressway has the most number of lanes in Singapore with five in each direction.<ref>{{cite web |title=Singapore's first undersea road - Marina Coastal Expressway - set to open on Dec 29 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/singapores-first-undersea-road-marina-coastal-expressway-set-to-open-on-dec-29 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=6 September 2019 |date=13 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Deaths==\n*20 April - [[Huang Wenyong]] - Malaysian-born Singaporean [[MediaCorp]] artiste (b. 1952).<ref>{{cite web |title=Veteran MediaCorp actor Huang Wenyong has died |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/veteran-mediacorp-actor-huang-wenyong-has-died |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=29 October 2019 |date=20 April 2013}}</ref>\n*22 April - [[Lee Yong Kiat]] - pioneering physician (b. 1928).<ref>{{cite web |title=Lee Yong Kiat |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_2014-11-24_175615.html |website=NLB |accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n*7 July - [[Cheng Tsang Man]] - founder of [[Prima Group]], Singapore's first flour mill (b. 1916).<ref>{{cite web |title=Cheng Tsang Man |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1192_2010-06-29.html |website=NLB |accessdate=12 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Years in Singapore}}\n{{Asia topic|2013 in}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2013 In Singapore}}\n[[Category:2013 in Singapore]]\n[[Category:2010s in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Years of the 21st century in Singapore]]\n", "text_old": "{{Dynamic list}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Year in Singapore|2013}}\n\nThe following lists events that happened during '''[[2013]] in the [[Singapore|Republic of Singapore]].\n\n== Incumbents ==\n*[[President of Singapore|President]]: [[Tony Tan Keng Yam]]\n*[[Prime Minister of Singapore|Prime Minister]]: [[Lee Hsien Loong]]\n\n==Events==\n===January===\n* 1 January - [[Cheng Lim LRT station]] is opened for service. At the same time, trains on the Sengkang West line will run in both directions too.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sbstransit.com.sg/press/2012-12-21-01.aspx |title=Cheng Lim LRT Station To Open And Sengkang West LRT to Run in Both Directions |website=SBS Transit |access-date=29 August 2019 |date=21 December 2012}}</ref>\n* 2 January - The Personal Data Protection Commission is formed to enforce [[data privacy]] laws.\n* 10 January - The [[North East MRT line]] is disrupted for nearly seven hours between [[HarbourFront MRT station]] to [[Outram Park MRT station]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/1247115/1/.html |title=NEL services fully resumed at 4:35pm: SBS Transit |website=Channel NewsAsia |date=10 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/apps/news/page.aspx?c=2&id=d827b396-5361-4e53-80ff-0ca49164b5cb |title=North East Line Train Service Resumes Full Operation Following Morning Disruption |website=LTA |access-date=6 September 2019 |date=10 January 2013}}</ref>\n* 14 January - [[Halimah Yacob]] is elected [[Speaker of the Parliament of Singapore]], making her the first female speaker in Singapore.<ref>{{cite web |title=PM Lee to nominate Halimah Yacob as next Speaker of Parliament |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/1246664/1/.html |website=CNA |accessdate=25 July 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130111020222/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/1246664/1/.html |archivedate=25 July 2019 |date=8 January 2013}}</ref>\n* 15 January - The [[smoking ban]] is extended to common areas of residential buildings, sheltered linkways and walkways, overhead pedestrian bridges, within 5m of bus stops and outside hospitals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.asiaone.com/print/News/Latest%2BNews/Singapore/Story/A1Story20130112-395047.html |title=Smoking ban to cover 5 more areas |website=Asiaone |accessdate=5 July 2019 |date=14 January 2013}}</ref>\n* 17 January - The [[Land Transport Authority]] announced several new MRT lines to be built, doubling the total MRT network to {{Convert|360|km|miles|abbr=in}} by 2030. They are the [[Jurong Region MRT line]], [[Downtown MRT line]] extension and [[Circle MRT line]] Stage 6 by 2025, [[North East MRT line]] extension to Punggol North and [[Cross Island MRT line]] by 2030, as well as a possible new station on the [[North South MRT line]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Speech%20by%20Mr%20Lui%20Tuck%20Yew%20at%20visit%20to%20DTL1%20Chinatown%20Station%20on%2017%20January%202013/ |title=Speech by Mr Lui Tuck Yew at visit to DTL1 Chinatown Station on 17 January 2013 |website=MOT |accessdate=19 September 2019 |date=17 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/more-new-mrt-lines-to-be-built-by-2030 |title=More new MRT lines to be built by 2030 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=25 May 2019 |date=17 January 2013}}</ref> A section of the Cross Island Line is to run under the [[Central Catchment Nature Reserve]], sparking a controversy with nature groups.\n* 21 January - \n**[[MediaCorp Channel NewsAsia]] begins broadcasting 24 hours daily.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.onscreenasia.com/article/channel-newsasia-relaunches/11424|title=Channel NewsAsia relaunches|date=21 January 2013|accessdate=21 January 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413140620/http://www.onscreenasia.com/article/channel-newsasia-relaunches/11424|archivedate=13 April 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n**1-week [[paternity leave]] is introduced as part of enhancements to the Marriage and Parenthood package, taking effect on 1 May. The leave can also be shared with mums too, and is extended to 2 weeks in 2015. Other measures include a four-week mandatory adoption leave, two days of childcare leave per year for parents of those aged seven to 12 years old, extending maternity protection to an entire pregnancy, and allowing expectant mothers not eligible for leave to claim a cash benefit substitute.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/1-week-government-paid-paternity-leave-now-part-of-parenthood-package-0 |title=1 week Government-paid paternity leave now part of parenthood package |website=The Straits Times  |accessdate=1 July 2019 |date=21 January 2013}}</ref>\n* 22 January - [[Singapore Institute of Technology]]'s campus at [[Nanyang Polytechnic]], known as SIT@NYP, starts construction, which will finish by 2014. The building will house the [[Newcastle University]], [[Trinity College Dublin]] and [[The University of Manchester]].<ref>{{cite web |title=SIT@NYP Groundbreaking Ceremony |url=https://www.singaporetech.edu.sg/digitalnewsroom/sitnyp-groundbreaking-ceremony/ |website=SIT |accessdate=15 September 2019 |date=22 January 2013}}</ref>\n* 26 January - [[Lee Li Lian]], representing the main opposition of [[Workers' Party (Singapore)|Workers' Party]], was elected as Member-of-Parliament (MP) for [[Punggol East Single Member Constituency]] as a result of winning the [[2013 Punggol East by-election]], succeeding the ruling [[People's Action Party]]'s MP [[Michael Palmer (politician)|Michael Palmer]], who earlier vacated his seat on 12 December last year because of an [[extramarital affair]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Au Yong |first1=Jeremy |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/workers-party-wins-punggol-east-by-election-with-5452-of-valid-votes |title=Workers' Party wins Punggol East by-election with 54.52% of valid votes |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=26 March 2020 |date=26 January 2013}}</ref> Lee is sworn into Parliament on 4 February.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ong |first1=Andrea |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/workers-partys-lee-li-lian-sworn-in-as-the-new-mp-for-punggol-east |title=Workers' Party's Lee Li Lian sworn in as the new MP for Punggol East |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=26 March 2020 |date=4 February 2013}}</ref>\n* 29 January - \n**The [[Population White Paper]] (a [[White Paper]] focusing on [[Demographics of Singapore|population]]) is released. The report projects a future population of 6.9 million by 2030, with 3 strategies proposed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cheam |first1=Jessica |title=Singapore's population could hit 6.9m by 2030 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/singapores-population-could-hit-69m-by-2030-0 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=7 July 2019 |date=29 January 2013}}</ref> The report's findings have caused controversy, culminating in a protest on 16 February which attracted 4,000 people.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rare mass rally over Singapore immigration plans |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-21485729 |website=BBC |accessdate=7 July 2019 |date=16 February 2013}}</ref>\n**[[Singapore Institute of Technology]]'s campus at [[Republic Polytechnic]], known as SIT@RP, starts construction, which will finish by 2014. The building will house the [[University of Glasgow]]. It is the tallest SIT building at nine storeys tall.<ref>{{cite web |title=SIT@RP Groundbreaking Ceremony |url=https://www.singaporetech.edu.sg/digitalnewsroom/sitrp-groundbreaking-ceremony/ |website=SIT |accessdate=15 September 2019 |date=29 January 2013}}</ref>\n* 30 January - Thai tycoon [[Charoen Sirivadhanabhakdi]] wins control of [[Fraser and Neave]] (F&N), a [[property]], [[food & beverage]] firm.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/thai-tycoon-wins-control-of-singapores-fraser-and-neave |title=Thai tycoon wins control of Singapore's Fraser and Neave |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=1 July 2019 |date=31 January 2013}}</ref>\n* 31 January - \n**The [[Ministry of National Development (Singapore)|Ministry of National Development]] released a Land Use Plan for land use changes towards 2030. Among them are more new towns, more green spaces, reclamation of land, acquisition of golf courses, moving of defence activities to [[Pulau Tekong]], and two new commercial hubs (the North Coast Innovation Corridor and Southern Waterfront City).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chang |first1=Rachel |title=Plan to grow space for rising population |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/plan-to-grow-space-for-rising-population |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=7 July 2019 |date=31 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Chang |first1=Rachel |title=5,600 hectares more land for bigger population: Land Use Plan |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/5600-hectares-more-land-for-bigger-population-land-use-plan-0 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=7 July 2019 |date=31 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Chin |first1=Daryl |title=Golf courses to make way for growing population |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/golf-courses-to-make-way-for-growing-population-0 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=7 December 2019 |date=31 January 2013}}</ref>\n**[[library@chinatown]] opens in [[Chinatown Point]].\n\n===February=== \n* 1 February - [[MediaCorp]] launches [[Toggle.sg|Toggle]], an [[over-the-top media services|over-the-top service (OTT)]].<ref>{{cite web |title=MediaCorp launches Toggle, its personal entertainment service on multiple devices |url=https://www.mediacorp.sg/en/corporate/mediacorp-in-the-news/media-releases/mediacorp-launches-toggle-its-personal-e-5855908 |website=Mediacorp |accessdate=7 July 2019 |date=1 February 2013}}</ref>\n* 8 February - Parliament convenes a special session to debate the controversial [[Population White Paper]] (a [[White Paper]] focusing on [[Demographics of Singapore|population]]), released earlier in January.\n* 9 February - [[Eng Wah Global|WE Cinemas]] will close both of its cinemas in [[West Mall]] and [[Suntec City]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Boon |first1=Rachael |title=Eng Wah exits Suntec and West Mall |url=https://www.asiaone.com/print/News/Latest%2BNews/Singapore/Story/A1Story20130207-400778.html |accessdate=14 August 2019 |website=The Straits Times |date=9 February 2013}}</ref>\n* 10 February - [[MediaCorp TV]] celebrates its 50-year anniversary since being established in 1963 (before on 16 February). \n* 14 February - Former [[Central Narcotics Bureau]] chief Ng Boon Gay is acquitted from a sex-for-contracts case.<ref>{{cite web |title=Former CNB chief Ng Boon Gay acquitted |url=https://sg.news.yahoo.com/former-cnb-chief-ng-boon-gay-acquitted-072825790.html |accessdate=7 July 2019 |website=Yahoo |date=14 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Lim |first1=Joyce |last2=Tham |first2=Yuen-C |title=Ng Boon Gay verdict: Court finds ex-CNB chief not guilty of corruption |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/ng-boon-gay-verdict-court-finds-ex-cnb-chief-not-guilty-of-corruption |accessdate=21 October 2019 |website=The Straits Times |date=14 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Tham |first1=Yuen-C |title=Ng Boon Gay's \"not guilty\" verdict: Judge says Cecilia Sue's testimony not believable |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/ng-boon-gays-not-guilty-verdict-judge-says-cecilia-sues-testimony-not-believable |accessdate=21 October 2019 |website=The Straits Times |date=14 February 2013}}</ref>\n* 19 February - Singapore and [[Malaysia]] agree to build the [[Penang\u2013Singapore High Speed Rail|high-speed rail link]] between the city-state island republic and mainland towards [[Kuala Lumpur]].<ref>{{cite news |title=PMs agree on high speed rail linking KL, Singapore |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/pms-agree-on-high-speed-rail-linking-kl-singapore |accessdate=4 August 2019 |website=The Straits Times |date=19 February 2013}}</ref>\n* 21 February - [[Uber]] launches its services in Singapore.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hardwarezone.com.sg/tech-news-uber-app-officially-launches-singapore |title=Uber App Officially Launches in Singapore |website=Hardware Zone Singapore |date=21 February 2013 |accessdate=27 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n* 1 March - The [[Sesame Street Spaghetti Space Chase]] is officially opened at [[Universal Studios Singapore]].<ref>{{cite news|title=USS Sesame Street theme park ride to open on March 1 |url=http://www.asiaone.com/print/News/Latest%2BNews/Relax/Story/A1Story20130218-402877.html|accessdate=2 March 2013|newspaper=Asia One|date=18 February 2013}}</ref>\n* 13 March - The [[Ministry of Education (Singapore)|Ministry of Education]] announced that 15 MOE Kindergartens will be set up over the next three years, with the first 5 opening next year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/budget-2013-15-moe-run-kindergartens-to-be-set-up-over-the-next-three-years-0 |title=Budget 2013: 15 MOE-run kindergartens to be set up over the next three years |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=1 July 2019 |date=13 March 2013}}</ref>\n* 14 March - The [[Ministry of Social and Family Development]] announced the setting up of 20 Social Service Offices (SSOs) to help needy Singaporeans.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.msf.gov.sg/media-room/Pages/Social-Service-Offices-to-be-set-up-in-HDB-towns-to-strengthen-delivery-of-social-services-to-needy-Singaporean.aspx |title=Social Service Offices To Be Set Up In HDB Towns To Strengthen Delivery Of Social Services To Needy Singaporeans |website=MSF |accessdate=11 July 2019 |date=14 March 2013}}</ref>\n* 15 March - Singaporeans and PRs will get free museum entry from 18 May to promote Singapore's heritage.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Huang |first1=Lijie |title=Budget 2013: Free museum entry from May for all Singaporeans, PRs |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/budget-2013-free-museum-entry-from-may-for-all-singaporeans-prs-0 |publisher=The Straits Times |accessdate=25 July 2019 |date=15 March 2013}}</ref>\n* 31 March - [[MediaCorp TV Channel 5]] celebrates its 50-year anniversary since being established in 1963 (before on 2 April).\n\n===April===\n* 1 April - \n**The [[Singapore Accountancy Commission]] is formed to regulate the accountancy sector.\n**The [[Early Childhood Development Agency]] is formed to oversee both kindergartens and childcare centres. ECDA is overseen by both the [[Ministry of Education (Singapore)|Ministry of Education]] and [[Ministry of Social and Family Development]], being housed in the latter.<ref>{{cite web |title=Launch of The Early Childhood Development Agency (ECDA) |url=https://www.moe.gov.sg/news/press-releases/launch-of-the-early-childhood-development-agency-ecda |website=MOE |accessdate=20 September 2019 |date=27 March 2013}}</ref>\n**All 57 [[Cold Storage (supermarket)#Shop N Save|Shop N Save]] supermarkets are rebranded to [[Giant Hypermarket|Giant]], except for the [[West Mall]] store, which will become a [[Cold Storage (supermarket)|Cold Storage]] store.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kham |first1=Priscilla |title=Shop n Save supermarket outlets to be converted to Giant stores |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/shop-n-save-supermarket-outlets-to-be-converted-to-giant-stores |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=23 August 2019 |date=1 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n===May===\n* 2 May - Construction works commenced on the [[Tanjong Pagar Centre]], a [[mixed-use]] tower. It will be the [[tallest building in Singapore]] at a height of 290m, more than [[One Raffles Place]], [[Republic Plaza (Singapore)|Republic Plaza]] and [[UOB Plaza One]], standing at 280m (the maximum allowed in Singapore). The building is completed in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/tanjong-pagar-centre-set-to-be-singapores-tallest-building-at-290m |title=Tanjong Pagar Centre set to be Singapore's tallest building at 290m |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=1 July 2019 |date=3 May 2013}}</ref>\n* 15 May - \n**[[City Harvest Church Criminal Breach of Trust Case]]: A 140-day-long trial involving [[Kong Hee]] and five other pastors, who were arrested on June 2012 over alleged misuse of funds, begins.\n**The [[Marina Bay Financial Centre]] is officially opened as a new business hub.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pmo.gov.sg/Newsroom/speech-prime-minister-lee-hsien-loong-official-opening-marina-bay-financial-centre |title=Official Opening of Marina Bay Financial Centre |website=PMO |accessdate=16 July 2019 |date=15 May 2013}}</ref>\n**[[Singapore Kindness Movement]] retires [[Singa the Lion|Singa the Courtesy Lion]] through a resignation letter.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/singa-the-courtesy-lion-i-quit |title=Singa the Courtesy Lion: 'I quit' |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=6 August 2019 |date=15 May 2013}}</ref>\n* 27 May - Filmmaker [[Anthony Chen]] snags a [[Camera d'Or]] for the film [[Ilo Ilo]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.todayonline.com/blogs/ratedg/singapore-film-ilo-ilo-wins-historic-cannes-prize |title=Singapore film Ilo Ilo wins historic Cannes prize |website=Today |accessdate=6 May 2019 |date=27 May 2013}}</ref> The film is eventually shown in cinemas from 29 August.\n* 28 May - Former [[National University of Singapore|NUS]] professor Tey Tsun Hang is found guilty in a sex-for-grades case, and thus sentenced to a 5-month jail term.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Singh |first1=Bryna |last2=Sim |first2=Walter |title=Law professor Tey Tsun Hang 'guilty' on all six counts of corruption in sex-for-grades case |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/law-professor-tey-tsun-hang-guilty-on-all-six-counts-of-corruption-in-sex-for-grades-case |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=7 July 2019 |date=28 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Singh |first1=Bryna |title=Sex for grades case: Former law professor Tey Tsun Hang begins his 5-month jail term |url=https://www.asiaone.com/News/Latest%2BNews/Singapore/Story/A1Story20130626-432536.html |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=7 July 2019 |date=26 June 2013}}</ref> The conviction is subsequently overturned in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lum |first1=Selina |title=Ex-law prof Tey Tsun Hang cleared of corruption by High Court |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/ex-law-prof-tey-tsun-hang-cleared-of-corruption-by-high-court |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=7 July 2019 |date=28 February 2014}}</ref>\n* 29 May - [[2013 dengue outbreak in Singapore]]: A man from [[Hougang]] dies from dengue shock syndrome; the first reported death case relating to dengue in Singapore this year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/dengue-claims-first-life-in-current-epid/692484.html |title=Dengue claims first life in current epidemic |accessdate=9 June 2013 |author=Sara Grosse |date=30 May 2013 |website=Channel NewsAsia}}</ref>\n* 31 May \u2013 Peter Lim Sim Pang, a former [[Singapore Civil Defence Force]] commissioner, is found guilty in a sex-for-contracts scandal involving three women, subsequently sentenced on 13 June to six months in jail.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ex-SCDF chief Peter Lim found guilty of corruption |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/ex-scdf-chief-peter-lim-found-guilty-of-corruption |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=10 August 2019 |date=31 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Sex-for-contracts trial: 6 months' jail for former SCDF chief Peter Lim |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/sex-for-contracts-trial-6-months-jail-for-former-scdf-chief-peter-lim |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=10 August 2019 |date=13 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n===June===\n* 12 June - After a series of financial troubles, the Changi Motorsports Hub project is called off.<ref>{{cite web |title=Changi Motorsports Hub called off |url=https://www.myactivesg.com/read/2013/6/changi-motorsports-hub-called-off |website=Singapore Sports Council |accessdate=26 July 2019 |date=12 June 2013}}</ref>\n* 15 June - [[Jem, Singapore|Jem]] opens its doors.\n* Mid-June: [[2013 Southeast Asian haze]]: Singapore sees its worst haze since [[1997 Southeast Asian haze|1997]]:\n** 17 June: At about 10pm, the 3-hour [[Pollutant Standards Index]] (PSI) levels reading reached an unhealthy range of 155 after air quality plummeted into the \"Unhealthy\" range at 2pm.<ref>{{cite web |title=Worst haze in 16 years, with PSI hitting 155 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/worst-haze-in-16-years-with-psi-hitting-155 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=13 September 2019 |date=18 June 2013}}</ref>\n** 19 June: At 9pm, the 3-hour PSI reaches 290, surpassing the previous record of 226 in [[1997 Southeast Asian haze|1997]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Feng |first1=Zengkun |title=Haze in Singapore hits historical high, PSI at 290 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/haze-in-singapore-hits-historical-high-psi-at-290 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=13 September 2019 |date=19 June 2013}}</ref> At 10pm, the 3-hour PSI reading reaches 321 marking the first time air quality reached \"Hazardous\" levels.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Feng |first1=Zengkun |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/breaking-news/singapore/story/haze-singapore-hits-new-high-psi-321-10pm-20130619 |title=S'pore PSI hits all-time high, PSI at 321 at 10pm |publisher=The Straits Times |date=19 June 2013 |accessdate=19 June 2013}}</ref>\n** 20 June: At about 1pm, the 3-hour PSI reading reaches 371.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/haze-reaches-hazardous/717772.html |title=Haze reaches hazardous level; PSI hits 371 |website=Channel NewsAsia |date=20 June 2013 |accessdate=20 June 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130822084746/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/haze-reaches-hazardous/717772.html |archivedate=22 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Feng |first1=Zengkun |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/haze-update-psi-climbs-to-new-high-of-371-at-1pm-on-thursday |title=Haze update: PSI climbs to new high of 371 at 1pm on Thursday |website=The Straits Times |date=20 June 2013 |accessdate=13 September 2013}}</ref>\n** 21 June - The 3-hour PSI reaches 400 at 11am,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=Pearl |title=Haze update: PSI hits another new high of 400 at 11am on Friday |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/haze-update-psi-hits-another-new-high-of-400-at-11am-on-friday |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=13 September 2019 |date=21 June 2013}}</ref> peaking at 401 at 12pm. This makes it the highest PSI reading in history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/psi-hits-new-all-time/719496.html |title=PSI hits new all-time high of 401 on Friday |website=Channel NewsAsia |date=21 June 2013 |accessdate=21 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624015317/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/psi-hits-new-all-time/719496.html |archivedate=24 June 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Yong |first1=Charissa |title=Haze update: PSI 401 at noon; many pharmacies still out of masks |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/haze-update-psi-401-at-noon-many-pharmacies-still-out-of-masks |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=13 September 2019 |date=21 June 2013}}</ref>\n* 25 June - The third series of Singapore's coins is released.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/new-singapore-third/705544.html |title=New Singapore Third Series coins available at banks from June 25 |website=Channel NewsAsia |date=11 June 2013 |accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref> However, old coins from the 1st and 2nd series remain legal tender.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Singapore Third Series Coins |url=http://www.todayonline.com/videos/singapore-third-series-coins |website=Today |date=21 February 2013 |accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n===July===\n* 27 July - The [[National Environment Agency]] announced that the Tray Return Initiative will be rolled out to all hawker centres in three phases. This comes after a successful trial in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tray Return Initiative To Roll Out To All Hawker Centres |url=https://www.nea.gov.sg/media/news/news/index/tray-return-initiative-to-roll-out-to-all-hawker-centres |website=NEA |accessdate=7 August 2019 |date=27 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n===August===\n* 5 August - [[2013 dengue outbreak in Singapore]]: The number of reported dengue cases reached about 14,000 at the time (including six deaths), surpassing the former record of 14,209 cases from [[2005 dengue outbreak in Singapore|2005]]. This becomes the worst dengue epidemic in Singapore, with a total 22,318 cases (including eight deaths) logged by end-2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/news/asia/354695/singapore-fights-back-against-worsening-dengue-outbreak.html |title=Singapore fights back against worsening dengue outbreak |accessdate=12 June 2013 |date=12 June 2013 |work=Bangkok Post}}</ref>\n* 15 August - [[CleanTech Park|CleanTech One]] is officially opened, boosting the eco industry in Singapore.<ref>{{cite web |title=Opening Ceremony of CleanTech One |url=http://jtc.gov.sg/News/Pages/20130815(SP2).aspx |website=JTC |accessdate=20 August 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140626062708/http://jtc.gov.sg/News/Pages/20130815(SP2).aspx |archivedate=26 June 2014 |date=15 August 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 18 August - Plans are unveiled to build [[Jewel Changi Airport|Project Jewel]] and [[Infrastructure of Singapore Changi Airport|Changi T5]] (including a third runway). In addition, all port activities will be consolidated in Tuas to create a Southern Waterfront City, and [[Paya Lebar Air Base]] will be moved to Changi East Airbase to free up land and lift height restrictions around the area.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sg.news.yahoo.com/amphtml/paya-lebar-air-base-to-move-to-changi-east-152738932.html |title=NDR 2013: Paya Lebar Air Base to move to Changi East, new plans for Changi Terminal 5 |website=Yahoo |date=18 August 2013 |accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/ndr-2013-paya-lebar-airbase-to-be-moved-to-changi-area-freed-up-for-homes-and-industry |title=NDR 2013: Paya Lebar Airbase to be moved to Changi, area freed up for homes and industry |website=The Straits Times |date=18 August 2013 |accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/terminal-5-will-double-changi-airports-capacity-pm-lee|title=Terminal 5 will double Changi Airport\u2019s capacity: PM Lee|work=TODAYonline|access-date=2018-01-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180117190432/http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/terminal-5-will-double-changi-airports-capacity-pm-lee|archive-date=2018-01-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 19 August - The [[Ministry of Education (Singapore)|Ministry of Education]] announced that 40 places will be reserved in each primary school for those without prior ties to the school. This move aims to increase opportunities for those to study in popular schools and integration.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.moe.gov.sg/news/press-releases/40-places-reserved-to-ensure-open-access-to-all-primary-schools |title=40 Places Reserved to Ensure Open Access to All Primary Schools |website=MOE |date=19 August 2013 |accessdate=9 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 29 August - The [[Housing and Development Board]] (HDB) unveils new housing plans for Bidadari, Tampines North and Punggol Matilda.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/ambitious-plans-for-3-new-hdb-projects |title=Ambitious plans for 3 new HDB projects |website=[[The Straits Times]] |date=30 August 2013 |accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref>\n* 30 August - The [[Ministry of Health (Singapore)|Ministry of Health]] announced [[Health City Novena]], a new health complex in central Singapore. The 17-hectare complex will have 10 buildings connected by bridges and underground links, which will be fully completed by 2030.<ref>{{cite web |title=Official Launch of Health City Novena |url=https://www.moh.gov.sg/news-highlights/details/speech-by-health-minister-gan-kim-yong-at-the-official-launch-of-health-city-novena-30-aug-2013 |website=MOH |accessdate=20 September 2019 |date=30 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/singapores-largest-healthcare-complex-planned-novena-area |title=Singapore's largest healthcare complex planned for Novena area |website=Todayonline |accessdate=25 May 2019 |date=30 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n===September===\n* 2 September - The [[Energy Market Authority]] imposes a $1.5m fine for a gas leak on Jurong Island on 23 April 2012.<ref>{{cite web |title=$1.5 million penalty imposed on PowerGas Ltd for gas leak incident on 23 April 2012 |url=https://www.ema.gov.sg/Gas_Regulatory_Updates.aspx |website=EMA |date=2 September 2013 |accessdate=28 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 5 September - [[Floods in Singapore#2013|Flash floods]] strikes western Singapore due to heavy rain, causing a section of [[AYE]] to close.<ref>{{cite web |title=Flash floods hit several areas in western Singapore |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/flash-floods-several-areas-western-singapore |website=Todayonline |date=5 September 2013 |accessdate=28 July 2019}}</ref> As a result, the [[Public Utilities Board]] announced the building of tidal gates and expansion of the canal to take in more rain.<ref>{{cite web |title=AYE flooding: Tidal gate to be built at expressway-adjacent canal |url=https://sg.news.yahoo.com/-not-acceptable--for-major-expressway-to-close-due-to-flooding--minister-balakrishnan-151937577.html |website=Yahoo |date=5 September 2013 |accessdate=28 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 13 September - The [[Expressway Monitoring and Advisory System]] signs will be upgraded to be more readable with different colours and display real-time traffic information to help motorists make better decisions. The exercise will be completed by 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/lta-replace-all-electronic-signboards-expressways-2017 |title=LTA to upgrade electronic signboards on expressways |website=Today |accessdate=11 July 2019 |date=13 September 2013}}</ref>\n* 18 September - The Tuaspring Desalination Plant is officially opened.<ref>{{cite web |title=Speech by Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong at the official opening of Tuaspring Desalination Plant |url=https://www.pmo.gov.sg/Newsroom/speech-prime-minister-lee-hsien-loong-official-opening-tuaspring-desalination-plant |website=PMO |date=18 September 2013 |accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref>\n* 23 September - The [[Fair Consideration Framework]] is announced in a bid to ensure Singaporeans have fair opportunities for jobs.\n* 30 September - \n**[[MediaCorp Teletext]] ceases transmission due to declining usage. In its heyday, Teletext served as a platform to receive news and information about Singapore.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/teletext-end-service-month |title=Teletext to end service this month |website=Today |access-date=20 September 2019 |date=3 September 2013}}</ref>\n**Dolphin Island opens at the Marine Life Park at [[Resorts World Sentosa]], featuring bottlenose dolphins.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ee |first1=David |title=Resorts World Sentosa's Dolphin Island to open on Sept 30 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/resorts-world-sentosas-dolphin-island-to-open-on-sept-30 |website=The Straits Times |date=19 September 2013 |accessdate=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===October===\n*October to November - [[2013 Singapore cyberattacks]]: Many of the cyberattacks occurred in Singapore, a [[YouTube]] video, made of [[Anonymus Hacker Group]]'s The Messiah threatening the [[Singapore government]]. Affected websites include the [[PAP Community Foundation]], the [[Ang Mo Kio Group Representation Constituency|Ang Mo Kio Town Council]] page (a town council led by the Prime Minister [[Lee Hsien Loong]]), [[Yahoo!]] Singapore, [[Seletar Airport]], [[Prime Minister's Office (Singapore)|Prime Minister's Office]] and [[The Istana]], as well as 13 schools on a single server.\n* 4 October - A penny stock crash occurs on the [[Singapore Exchange]] (SGX), causing a S$8 billion wipeout involving 3 stocks. The [[Monetary Authority of Singapore]], SGX and [[Commercial Affairs Department]] had commenced investigations on that, resulting in 3 arrests.<ref>{{cite web |title=Singapore launches probe into penny stocks crash |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2013/10/24/singapore-launches-probe-into-penny-stocks-crash.html |website=CNBC |date=24 October 2013 |accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=3 arrested over 2013 penny stock crash |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/business/companies-markets/3-arrested-over-penny-stock-crash |website=The Straits Times |date=25 November 2016 |accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref> All have since been slapped with charges with 1 sentenced to jail in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Finance manager in scheme that triggered S$8 billion penny stock crash in 2013 gets jail |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/finance-manager-in-scheme-that-triggered-s-8-billion-penny-stock-11362522 |website=Channel NewsAsia |accessdate=5 May 2019 |date=20 March 2019}}</ref>\n* 7 October - \n**The Land Transport Master Plan 2013 is released, which will include 200&nbsp;km of sheltered walkways, 700&nbsp;km of cycling paths, more ITHs, more trains and buses, an upgraded signalling system and more lifts.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/apps/news/page.aspx?c=2&id=a3ba8ffe-988a-43f7-8881-32d8f9c46416 |title=Launch of Land Transport Master Plan 2013 |website=LTA |accessdate=11 July 2019 |date=7 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/land-transport-masterplan-2013-20-things-you-need-to-know |title=Land Transport Masterplan 2013: 20 things you need to know |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=1 November 2019 |date=7 October 2013}}</ref>\n**Veteran National football player and coach, [[V. Sundramoorthy]] resigns as [[LionsXII]] and [[Singapore national under-23 football team|National U-23]] coach. He is replaced by [[Fandi Ahmad]] on 7 December.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sundram resigns as LionsXII and National U-23 coach |url=http://www.todayonline.com/sports/football/sundram-resigns-lionsxii-and-national-u-23-coach |website=Today |date=7 October 2013 |accessdate=7 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/sport/football-fandi-ahmad/913868.html |title=Football: Fandi Ahmad appointed LionsXII head coach |website=[[Channel NewsAsia]] |accessdate=17 January 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219054345/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/sport/football-fandi-ahmad/913868.html |archivedate=19 December 2013}}</ref>\n* 10 October - [[StarHub]] launches SuperSports Arena (renamed to [[Hub Sports Arena]]) for all households in Singapore to promote Singapore sports.<ref>{{cite web |title=StarHub and Singapore Sports Council Bring More Local Sports Content to Singaporeans |url=https://www.starhub.com/about-us/newsroom/2013/october/starhub-and-singapore-sports-council-bring-more-local-sports-con.html |website=StarHub |accessdate=5 August 2019 |date=8 October 2013}}</ref>\n* 17 October - [[National University of Singapore]]'s U Town is officially opened, encouraging students and professors to learn and live together.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nus.edu.sg/president/pdf/utownopening.pdf |title=Official Opening of University Town |website=NUS |accessdate=22 July 2019 |date=17 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/local-universities-have-wider-national-and-social-mission-beyond-academics-pm-lee |title=Local universities have wider national and social mission beyond academics: PM Lee |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=22 July 2019 |date=17 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Official Opening of University Town |url=https://www.pmo.gov.sg/Newsroom/speech-prime-minister-lee-hsien-loong-official-opening-university-town |website=PMO |accessdate=9 August 2019 |date=17 October 2013}}</ref>\n* 21 October - [[GrabTaxi]] is launched in Singapore, making it the second [[ride-hailing]] service here.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hardwarezone.com.sg/tech-news-grabtaxi-regions-largest-taxi-booking-mobile-app-beta-launches-singapore |title=GrabTaxi, Region's Largest Taxi-booking Mobile App, Beta Launches in Singapore |website=Hardware Zone Singapore |accessdate=27 June 2019 |date=21 October 2013}}</ref>\n* 24 October - The [[Singapore Institute of Technology]] (SIT) announced a slew of its own degree programmes which will start from 2014. This is in preparation of SIT becoming the fifth autonomous university in Singapore, as it currently offers degree programmes with foreign universities.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.singaporetech.edu.sg/digitalnewsroom/sit-to-launch-its-own-applied-degrees-in-2014-to-develop-best-in-class-industry-specialists/ |title=SIT to launch its own applied degrees in 2014 to develop 'best-in-class' industry specialists |website=SIT |date=24 October 2013|accessdate=11 September 2019}}</ref>\n* 25 October - The Disease Outbreak Response System Condition (DORSCON) is revised to consider severity of diseases in addition to the spread of diseases in Singapore. Control measures are made more flexible with four colour alerts instead of five, allowing the framework to be used for both mild and severe diseases.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kok |first1=Xing Hui |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/singapore-revises-outbreak-response-system |title=Singapore revises outbreak response system |website=Today |date=25 October 2013 |accessdate=8 February 2020}}</ref>\n* 27 October - The [[Sengkang General Hospital]] and [[Sengkang Community Hospital]] have started construction, first announced in 2011 by the [[Ministry of Health (Singapore)|Ministry of Health]]. These hospitals will be completed by 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=Groundbreaking Ceremony for Sengkang General and Community Hospitals |url=https://www.moh.gov.sg/news-highlights/details/speech-by-mr-gan-kim-yong-minister-for-health-at-the-groundbreaking-ceremony-for-sengkang-general-and-community-hospitals-on-sunday-27-october-2013 |website=MOH |accessdate=20 September 2019 |date=27 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Work begins on new general hospital in Sengkang |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/breaking-news/singapore/story/work-has-begun-new-general-hospital-the-north-one-four-be-built-2030-2 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=4 May 2014 |date=27 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Sengkang General and Community Hospitals and will add 1,400 beds to national healthcare system when completed in 2018 |url=http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/new-sengkang-hospitals-will-boast-1400-beds |website=Today |accessdate=4 May 2014 |date=27 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===November===\n* 8 November - [[Institute of Technical Education|ITE's]] new headquarters and [[ITE College Central]] in Ang Mo Kio is officially opened, marking the completion of the 'One ITE System, Three Colleges' initiative.<ref>{{cite web |title=Review to better match ITE, poly skills to jobs |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/breaking-news/singapore/story/review-polytechnics-and-ites-improve-students-job-and-academic-prospec |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=12 May 2019 |date=8 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Official Opening of ITE Headquarters and ITE College Central |url=https://www.pmo.gov.sg/Newsroom/speech-prime-minister-lee-hsien-loong-official-opening-ite-headquarters-and-ite-college |website=PMO |accessdate=9 August 2019 |date=8 November 2013}}</ref>\n* 12 November - [[2013 Singapore cyberattacks]]: James Raj, the mastermind who is alleged \"The Messiah\", is charged in Singapore court.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/suspected-messiah-hacker-charged-court |title=Suspected 'Messiah' hacker charged in court |website=[[Today (Singapore newspaper)|Today]] |date=12 November 2013}}</ref> He has since been found guilty and sentenced to 56 months jail in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |title='Messiah' hacker jailed for computer misuse, taking drugs |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/messiah-hacker-jailed-56-months |website=Today |date=30 January 2015 |accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref>\n* 14 November - The [[Ministry of Education (Singapore)|Ministry of Education]] announced a trial of Subject-Based Banding in 12 secondary schools from 2014.<ref>{{cite web |title=Greater Flexibility In Secondary School Subject Offering |url=https://www.moe.gov.sg/news/press-releases/greater-flexibility-in--secondary-school-subject-offering |website=MOE |date=14 November 2013 |accessdate=11 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 24 November - [[MediaCorp TV Channel 8]] celebrates its 50-year anniversary since being established on 23 November 1963.\n* 30 November - The first Purple Parade is held to raise awareness of the special needs community.<ref>{{cite web |title=Very special Purple Parade for the special needs community |url=https://www.asiaone.com/health/very-special-purple-parade-special-needs-community |website=Asiaone |date=4 December 2013 |accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===December===\n* 2 December - [[Westgate, Singapore|Westgate Mall]] opened its doors.\n* 3 December - [[Bedok Mall]] opened its doors.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bedok Mall opens its doors with new brands and renowned restaurants |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/bedok-mall-opens-its-doors-with-new-brands-and-renowned-restaurants |website=The Straits Times |date=3 December 2013 |accessdate=27 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 8 December - [[2013 Little India riots]]: A riot broke out on the streets of [[Little India, Singapore|Little India]], with 27 arrests, many injuries and several emergency vehicles overturned. One bus front windscreen was smashed. This was the second riot in post-independence Singapore, after the [[1969 race riots of Singapore|race riots in 1969]].\n* 18 December - A near four-hour disruption of services for [[Circle MRT Line]] for 23 out of 28 stations <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/train-service-disrupted-23-circle-line-stations |title=Train services at 23 Circle Line stations restored after power failure |website=[[Today (Singapore newspaper)]] |accessdate=17 January 2014}}</ref>\n* 22 December - Opening of the [[Downtown MRT Line]] Stage 1, stretching from [[Bugis MRT station]] to [[Bayfront MRT station|Bayfront]] and [[Chinatown MRT station]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Downtown Line Stage 1 to open on Dec 22 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/downtown-line-stage-1-to-open-on-dec-22 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=6 September 2019 |date=7 October 2013}}</ref>\n* 29 December - Opening of the [[Marina Coastal Expressway]] (MCE), Singapore first undersea expressway. The expressway has the most number of lanes in Singapore with five in each direction.<ref>{{cite web |title=Singapore's first undersea road - Marina Coastal Expressway - set to open on Dec 29 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/singapores-first-undersea-road-marina-coastal-expressway-set-to-open-on-dec-29 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=6 September 2019 |date=13 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Deaths==\n*20 April - [[Huang Wenyong]] - Malaysian-born Singaporean [[MediaCorp]] artiste (b. 1952).<ref>{{cite web |title=Veteran MediaCorp actor Huang Wenyong has died |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/veteran-mediacorp-actor-huang-wenyong-has-died |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=29 October 2019 |date=20 April 2013}}</ref>\n*22 April - [[Lee Yong Kiat]] - pioneering physician (b. 1928).<ref>{{cite web |title=Lee Yong Kiat |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_2014-11-24_175615.html |website=NLB |accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n*7 July - [[Cheng Tsang Man]] - founder of [[Prima Group]], Singapore's first flour mill (b. 1916).<ref>{{cite web |title=Cheng Tsang Man |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1192_2010-06-29.html |website=NLB |accessdate=12 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Years in Singapore}}\n{{Asia topic|2013 in}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2013 In Singapore}}\n[[Category:2013 in Singapore]]\n[[Category:2010s in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Years of the 21st century in Singapore]]\n", "name_user": "TheGreatSG'rean", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAugust", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2013_in_Singapore"}
{"title_page": "La Jolla", "text_new": "{{Other uses|La Jolla (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!--See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields that may be available-->\n<!--See the Table at Infobox settlement for all fields and descriptions of usage-->\n<!-- Basic info ---------------->\n|name=La Jolla<!-- at least one of the first two fields must be filled in -->\n|official_name=\n|other_name=\n|native_name=<!-- if different from the English name -->\n|nickname=\"Jewel City\"\n|settlement_type=[[List of communities and neighborhoods of San Diego|Community of San Diego]] <!-- e.g. Town, Village, City, etc.-->\n|total_type=<!-- to set a non-standard label for total area and population rows -->\n|motto=\n<!-- images and maps ----------->\n|image_skyline=La Jolla, San Diego California photo D Ramey Logan.jpg\n|imagesize=\n|image_caption=Aerial photo of part of La Jolla\n|image_flag=\n|flag_size=\n|seal_size=\n|image_shield=\n|shield_size=\n|image_blank_emblem=\n|blank_emblem_type=\n|blank_emblem_size=\n|image_map=\n|mapsize=\n|map_caption=\n|pushpin_map=California\n|pushpin_label_position=\n|pushpin_map_caption=Location within California\n|pushpin_mapsize=\n|pushpin_label_position1=\n|pushpin_mapsize1=\n<!-- Location ------------------>\n|subdivision_type       = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|United States}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1      = {{flag|California}}\n|subdivision_type2      = [[County (United States)|County]]\n|subdivision_name2      = {{flagicon image|Flag of San Diego County, California.png}} [[San Diego County, California|San Diego]]\n|subdivision_type3      = [[List of municipalities in California|City]]\n|subdivision_name3      = {{flagicon image|Flag of San Diego, California.svg}} [[San Diego]]\n<!-- Smaller parts (e.g. boroughs of a city) and seat of government -->\n|seat_type=\n|seat=\n|parts_type=\n|parts_style=<!--=list (for list), coll (for collapsed list), para (for paragraph format)\n Default is list if up to 5 items, coll if more than 5-->\n|parts=<!-- parts text, or header for parts list -->\n|p1=\n|p2=<!-- etc. up to p50: for separate parts to be listed-->\n<!-- Politics ----------------->\n|government_footnotes=\n|government_type=\n|leader_title=\n|leader_name=\n|leader_title1=\n|leader_name1=\n|leader_title2=\n|leader_name2=\n|leader_title3=\n|leader_name3=\n|established_date=\n<!-- Area --------------------->\n|area_magnitude=\n|unit_pref=\n|area_footnotes=\n|area_total_sq_mi=\n|area_land_sq_mi=\n|area_water_sq_mi=\n|area_water_percent=\n<!-- Elevation -------------------------->\n|elevation_footnotes=<!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m=\n|elevation_ft=\n|elevation_max_m=\n|elevation_max_ft=\n|elevation_min_m=\n|elevation_min_ft=\n<!-- Population ----------------------->\n|population_as_of=2010\n|population_footnotes=<ref name=\"2010population\"/>\n|population_note=\n|population_total=46,781\n|population_density_sq_mi=\n<!-- General information --------------->\n|timezone=\n|utc_offset=\n|timezone_DST=\n|utc_offset_DST=\n|coordinates            = {{coord|32|50|24|N|117|16|37|W|display=inline}}\n|postal_code_type=[[ZIP Code]]\n|postal_code=92037-92039, 92092, 92093\n|area_code=[[Area code 858|858]]\n|website=[http://www.sandiego.gov/planning/community/profiles/lajolla/ sandiego.gov/lajolla]\n|footnotes=\n}}\n\n'''La Jolla''' ({{IPAc-en|l|\u0259|_|\u02c8|h|\u0254\u026a|\u0259}} {{respell|l\u0259|_|HOY|\u0259}}, {{IPA-es|la \u02c8xo\u029da|am}}) is a hilly, seaside community within the city of [[San Diego, California]], occupying {{convert|7|mi|km}} of curving coastline along the [[Pacific Ocean]] within the northern city limits. The population reported in the 2010 census was 46,781.<ref name=\"2010population\">{{cite web |title=Profile of General Population and Housing Characteristics: 2010 |work=2010 Demographic Profile Data |url=https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?src=CF |access-date=2017-03-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721034521/http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=DEC_10_PL_GCTPL2.ST13&prodType=table |archive-date=2011-07-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{efn|The 2004 estimated population was 42,808.<ref name=\"population\">{{cite web | title=Population and Housing Estimates, Zip Code 92037 |work=2004 Estimates |url=http://cart.sandag.org/profiles/est/zip92037est.pdf |access-date=2006-10-15 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060718182113/http://cart.sandag.org/profiles/est/zip92037est.pdf <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2006-07-18}}</ref>}}\n\nLa Jolla is surrounded on three sides by ocean bluffs and beaches<ref name=\"SanDiego.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sandiego.org/article_set/Visitors/8/113 |title=SanDiego.org |publisher=SanDiego.org |date= |access-date=2010-06-30}}</ref> and is located {{convert|12|mi|km}} north of [[Downtown San Diego]] and {{convert|45|mi|km}} south of [[Orange County, California|Orange County]].<ref>{{cite web|author=US |url=http://www.mapquest.com/maps?city=La+Jolla&state=CA&country=US&latitude=32.847198&longitude=-117.2733&geocode=CITY |title=Mapquest |publisher=Mapquest |date= |access-date=2010-06-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sandiego.gov |title=San Diego City |publisher=Sandiego.gov |date= |access-date=2010-06-30}}</ref> The climate is mild, with an average daily temperature of {{convert|70.5|F|C}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sandiego.org/nav/Visitors/VisitorInformation/Weather |title=SanDiego.org |publisher=SanDiego.org |date= |access-date=2010-06-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100620152024/http://www.sandiego.org/nav/Visitors/VisitorInformation/Weather |archive-date=2010-06-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weather.com |title=Weather.com |publisher=Weather.com |date=2009-06-17 |access-date=2010-06-30}}</ref>\n\nLa Jolla is home to many educational institutions and a variety of businesses in the areas of lodging, dining, shopping, software, finance, real estate, bioengineering, medical practice and scientific research.<ref name=\"SanDiego.org\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.discoversd.com/california/san-diego/ca/la-jolla-shopping.html |title=DiscoverSD |publisher=DiscoverSD |date= |access-date=2010-06-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100529151444/http://www.discoversd.com/california/san-diego/ca/la-jolla-shopping.html |archivedate=2010-05-29 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lajollabythesea.com/members/index.php?cid=4 |title=La Jolla, CA Official Website |publisher=Lajollabythesea.com |date= |access-date=2010-06-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100629042747/http://www.lajollabythesea.com/members/index.php?cid=4 |archive-date=2010-06-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The [[University of California, San Diego]] (UCSD) is located in La Jolla, as are the [[Salk Institute for Biological Studies|Salk Institute]], [[Scripps Institution of Oceanography]] (part of UCSD), [[Scripps Research Institute]], and the headquarters of [[National University (California)|National University]] (though its academic campuses are elsewhere).\n\n==History==\n===Origin of the name===\n[[File:La Jolla, San Diego, California (1908).jpg|thumb|left|La Jolla, 1908]]\nLocal Native Americans, the [[Kumeyaay]], called this location ''{{lang|dih|mat kulaaxuuy}}'' ({{IPA-all|mat k\u0259la\u02d0xu\u02d0j|IPA}}), {{abbr|lit.|literally}} \"land of holes\" (''{{lang|dih|mat}}'' = \"land\").<ref>Langdon 1970</ref> The topographic feature that gave rise to the name \"holes\" is uncertain; it probably refers to sea-level caves located on the north-facing bluffs, which are visible from [[La Jolla Shores]]. It is suggested{{citation needed|reason=By whom?|date=April 2015}} that the Kumeyaay name for the area was transcribed by the Spanish settlers as ''{{lang|es|La Jolla}}''. An alternative, [[false etymology|pseudo-etymological]] suggestion for the origin of the name is that it is an alternate spelling of the Spanish phrase ''{{lang|es|la [[wikt:joya#Spanish|joya]]}}'', which means \"the jewel\". Despite being disputed by scholars, this derivation of the name has been widely cited in popular culture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lajollaplayhouse.org/plan-your-visit/about-la-jolla/history-of-la-jolla |title=History of La Jolla |author= |date= |publisher=La Jolla Playhouse, via Wayback Machine |access-date=September 30, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111103082914/http://www.lajollaplayhouse.org/plan-your-visit/about-la-jolla/history-of-la-jolla |archivedate=November 3, 2011 }}</ref> This supposed origin gave rise to the nickname \"Jewel City\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Ray |first=Nancy |title=One of La Jolla's Best-Kept Secrets Is Fun Ride |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1985-08-31/local/me-24176_1_trolley-riders |date=August 31, 1985 |access-date=June 22, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006190418/http://articles.latimes.com/1985-08-31/local/me-24176_1_trolley-riders |archivedate=October 6, 2014 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Early history===\n{{See also|List of San Diego Historical Landmarks in La Jolla}}\n[[File:Red Roost, Red Rest, La Jolla.JPG|thumb|\"Red Roost\" and \"Red Rest\", two bungalow cottages built in 1894 on the road above [[La Jolla Cove]]. In recent years the cottages have been covered in [[tarpaulin]]s.]]\n[[File:\"Red Roost\" La Jolla, California.JPG|thumb|The side view of \"Red Roost\", a bungalow cottage built in 1894, one of two that still exist on the road above La Jolla Cove]]\n\nDuring the Mexican period of San Diego's history, La Jolla was mapped as ''[[pueblo]]'' land and contained about 60 lots. When California became a state in 1850, the La Jolla area was incorporated as part of the chartered City of San Diego. In 1870, Charles Dean acquired several of the pueblo lots and subdivided them into an area that became known as La Jolla Park. Dean was unable to develop the land and left San Diego in 1881. A [[Real estate bubble|real estate boom]] in the 1880s led speculators Frank T. Botsford and George W. Heald to further develop the sparsely settled area.\n\nIn the 1890s, the San Diego, Pacific Beach, and La Jolla Railway was built, connecting La Jolla to the rest of San Diego. La Jolla became known as a resort area. To attract visitors to the beach, the railway built facilities such as a bath house and a dance pavilion. Visitors were housed in small cottages and bungalows above La Jolla Cove, as well as a temporary [[tent city]] erected every summer. Two of the cottages that were built in 1894 still exist: the \"Red Roost\" and the \"Red Rest\", also known as the \"Neptune and Cove Tea Room\"; the two cottages have been vacant since the 1980s, and are covered in tarpaulins. The La Jolla Park Hotel opened in 1893. The Hotel Cabrillo was built in 1908 by \"Squire\" James A. Wilson and was later incorporated into the La Valencia Hotel.<ref name=\"Hollins\">{{cite journal|last=Hollins|first=Jeremy|title=Village Memories: A Photo Essay on La Jolla's Past|journal=Journal of San Diego History|pages=295\u2013305|url=http://www.sandiegohistory.org/journal/v54-4/pdf/v54-4Hollins.pdf}}</ref>\n\nBy 1900, La Jolla comprised 100 buildings and 350 residents. The first reading room (library) was built in 1898.<ref name = \"Hollins\" /> A volunteer fire brigade was organized in 1907; the city of San Diego established a regular fire house in 1914. Livery stable owner Nathan Rannells served successively as La Jolla's volunteer fire captain, first police officer (the only San Diego police officer north of [[Mission Valley]]), and first postmaster.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rannells|first=Nathan L.|date=October 1958|title=La Jolla No. 1|journal=Journal of San Diego History|volume=4|issue=4|url=http://www.sandiegohistory.org/journal/58october/lajolla.htm}}</ref>\n\nLa Jolla Elementary School began educating local children in 1896.<ref name=\"SDUSD\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sandiegounified.org/schools/la-jolla-elementary/about-la-jolla-elementary|title=About La Jolla Elementary|work=San Diego Unified School District|accessdate=28 October 2017}}</ref> [[The Bishop's School (La Jolla)|The Bishop's School]] opened in 1909. [[La Jolla High School]] was established in 1922. Between 1951 and 1963, other elementary schools (Bird Rock, Decatur, Scripps, and Torrey Pines) were established in the area to ease overcrowding.<ref name = SDUSD/> The La Jolla Beach and Yacht Club (later the [[La Jolla Beach and Tennis Club]]) was built in 1927.<ref name = \"Hollins\" />\n\n===Ellen Browning Scripps===\n[[File:La Jolla Recreational Center.jpg|thumb|La Jolla Recreational Center]]\nIn 1896 journalist and publisher [[Ellen Browning Scripps]] settled in La Jolla, where she lived for the last 35 years of her life. She was wealthy in her own right from her investments and writing, and she inherited a large sum from her brother George H. Scripps in 1900. She devoted herself to philanthropic endeavors, particularly those benefiting her adopted home of La Jolla. She commissioned many of La Jolla's most notable buildings, usually designed by [[Irving Gill]] or his nephew and partner [[Louis John Gill]]. Many of these buildings are now on the  [[National Register of Historic Places listings in San Diego County, California|National Register of Historic Places]] or are listed as historic by the city of San Diego; these include the [[La Jolla Woman's Club]] (1914), the [[La Jolla Recreational Center]] (1915), the earliest buildings of [[The Bishop's School (La Jolla)|The Bishop's School]], and the [[Old Scripps Building]] at the [[Scripps Institution of Oceanography]], as well as her own residence, built in 1915 and now housing the [[Museum of Contemporary Art San Diego]]. Her donations also launched the [[Scripps Health|Scripps Memorial Hospital]] in 1924 (originally located on Prospect Street in La Jolla until it moved to its present site in 1964), the Scripps Metabolic Clinic (now the [[Scripps Research Institute]]), and the [[Children's Pool Beach|Children's Pool]]. Ellen Browning Scripps also founded [[Scripps College]], a women's college,  in 1926.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scrippscollege.edu/about/ellen-browning-scripps|title=About Scripps College - History|website=www.scrippscollege.edu}}</ref> Scripps College is located in [[Claremont, California|Claremont]] in Los Angeles County (not to be confused with [[Clairemont, San Diego|Clairemont]], a community of [[San Diego]]).\n\n===Scripps Institution of Oceanography===\n[[File:SIOpier.jpg|right|thumb|Scripps Institution of Oceanography pier]]\nThe [[Scripps Institution of Oceanography]], one of the nation's oldest oceanographic institutes, was founded in 1903 by [[William Emerson Ritter]], chair of the zoology department at the [[University of California, Berkeley]], with financial support from Scripps and her brother [[E. W. Scripps]]. At first the institution operated out of a boathouse in [[Coronado, California|Coronado]]. In 1905 they purchased a {{convert|170|acre|ha|adj=on}} site in La Jolla where the Institution still stands today. The first laboratory buildings there opened in 1907. The institution became part of the [[University of California]] in 1912. Ultimately it became the nucleus for the establishment of the University of California San Diego.\n\n===Camp Matthews===\nFrom 1917 through 1964 the [[United States Marine Corps]] maintained a military base in La Jolla. The base was used for marksmanship training and was known as [[Camp Calvin B. Matthews]]. During and after [[World War II]] the population of La Jolla grew, causing residential development to draw close to the base, so that it became less and less suitable as a firing range because of risk to the adjacent civilian population.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.militarymuseum.org/SDMarines.html#18 |title=A Brief History of the U.S. Marine Corps in San Diego |last=Denger |first=Mark J. |work=The California State Military Museum |access-date=21 May 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130424141525/http://www.militarymuseum.org/SDMarines.html |archivedate=24 April 2013 |df= }}</ref> Meanwhile, the site was being eyed as a location for a proposed new campus of the University of California. In 1962 Camp Matthews was declared surplus by the Marine Corps. The base formally closed in 1964, and that same year the first class of undergraduates enrolled in the University of California San Diego.\n\n===University of California, San Diego===\nLocal civic leaders had long toyed with the idea of a [[University of California, San Diego|San Diego campus]] of the [[University of California]], and the quest became more definite following World War II. The Scripps Institution of Oceanography, under its director [[Roger Revelle]], had become an important defense contractor, and local aerospace companies like [[Convair]] were pressing for local training for their scientists and engineers. The state legislature proposed the idea in 1955, and the Regents of the University formally approved it in 1960.<ref name=\"Shragge\">{{cite journal|last=Shragge|first=Abraham J.|date=Fall 2001|title=Growing Up Together: The University of California's One Hundred-Year Partnership with the San Diego Region|journal=Journal of San Diego History|volume=47|issue=4|url=http://www.sandiegohistory.org/journal/2001-4/ucsd.htm}}</ref> During the planning stage of the university's establishment, it was briefly known as the \"University of California, La Jolla\", but the name was changed to \"University of California, San Diego\" before its founding in 1960.<ref name=\"timeline\">{{cite web|url=http://ucsd.edu/timeline/|title=Timeline|work=University of California San Diego|access-date=23 May 2013}}</ref> The founding chancellor was [[Herbert York]], named in 1961, and the second chancellor was [[John Semple Galbraith]], named in 1964. The university was designed to have a \"college\" system; there are now six colleges. The first college was established in 1965 and was named [[Revelle College]] after [[Roger Revelle]], who is regarded as the \"father\" of the university.<ref name = \"timeline\" /> A [[UC San Diego School of Medicine|medical school]] was established in 1968. The landmark [[Geisel Library]] with its [[Brutalist architecture]] opened in 1970.\n\n===Antisemitism===\nThe Camp Matthews site for the University was selected with some hesitation; one of the concerns was \"whether La Jollans in particular would lay aside old prejudices in order to welcome a culturally, ethnically, and religiously diverse professoriate into their midst\".<ref name = \"Shragge\" /> La Jolla had a history of restrictive housing policies, often specified in deeds and ownership documents. In La Jolla Shores and La Jolla Hermosa, only people with pure [[Europe]]an ancestry could own property; this excluded [[Judaism|Jews]], who were not considered [[White people|white]]. Such \"[[Covenant (law)|restrictive covenants]]\" were once fairly common throughout the United States; the 1948 Supreme Court case ''[[Shelley v. Kraemer]]'' ruled them to be unenforceable, and Congress outlawed them twenty years later via the Fair Housing Act (Title VII of the [[Civil Rights Act of 1968]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://portal.hud.gov/hudportal/HUD?src=/program_offices/fair_housing_equal_opp/progdesc/title8|title=Title VIII: Fair Housing and Equal Opportunity|work=U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development|access-date=11 February 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150708050943/http://portal.hud.gov/hudportal/HUD?src=%2Fprogram_offices%2Ffair_housing_equal_opp%2Fprogdesc%2Ftitle8|archivedate=8 July 2015|df=}}</ref> However, realtors and property owners in La Jolla continued to use more subtle ways of preventing or discouraging Jews from owning property there.<ref name=\"Garson\">For example, when the world-famous mathematician and philosopher [[Jacob Bronowski]] came to the [[Salk Institute for Biological Studies|Salk Institute]] in 1963, he wanted to build a home on La Jolla Farms Road for his family. For his required character references, his family produced letters from members of [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]], in {{cite web|author=Garson, Sue |url=http://www.sdjewishjournal.com/stories/jewishnewsstory.html |title=The End of Covenant |publisher=The San Diego Jewish Journal |year=2003 |access-date=2010-06-30 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080723060708/http://www.sdjewishjournal.com/stories/jewishnewsstory.html |archivedate=July 23, 2008 |url-status=unfit }}</ref> Revelle stated the issue bluntly: \"You can't have a university without having Jewish professors. The Real Estate Broker's Association and their supporters in La Jolla had to make up their minds whether they wanted a university or an anti-Semitic covenant. You couldn't have both.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Carless, Will |url=http://www.lajollalight.com/printer/article.asp?c=223555 |title=A specter from our past: Longtime residents will always remember the stain left on the Jewel by an era of housing discrimination |publisher=LaJollaLight.com |date=2005-04-07 |access-date=2010-06-30 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100913084414/http://www.lajollalight.com/printer/article.asp?c=223555 |archivedate=2010-09-13 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> The issue was overcome; La Jolla now boasts a thriving Jewish population,<ref>{{cite web|author=Stratthaus, Mary Ellen |url=http://www.fairhousingforall.org/sites/default/files/files/Stratthaus.pdf |title=Flaw in the Jewel: Housing Discrimination Against Jews in La Jolla, California |publisher=American Jewish Historical Society |year=1996 |access-date=2010-06-30 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5quH6gLRG?url=http://www.fairhousingforall.org/sites/default/files/files/Stratthaus.pdf |archivedate=2010-07-01 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> and there are four synagogues in La Jolla.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://goo.gl/maps/ktHHu |title=Synagogues in La Jolla |author=Google.com |date= |publisher=Google Maps |access-date=May 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Mount Soledad cross===\n[[File:Mount Soledad Cross WF.jpg|thumb|upright 0.7|The [[Christian cross]] on [[Mount Soledad]]]]\n{{Main|Mount Soledad Cross}}\n[[Mount Soledad]] is an {{convert|822|ft|m|adj=mid|-tall}} hill on the eastern edge of La Jolla and one of the highest points in San Diego. A large [[Christian cross]] was placed at the top in 1913 as a prominent landmark. It has been replaced twice, most recently in 1954 with a {{convert|29|ft|m|adj=mid|-tall}} cross ({{convert|43|ft|m}} tall including the base). Originally known as the \"Mount Soledad Easter Cross\", its presence on publicly owned land was challenged in the 1980s as a violation of the [[separation of church and state]]. Since then the cross has had a war memorial built around it and was renamed \"Mount Soledad Veterans War Memorial\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/US/01/04/california.cross/|title=Appeals court says cross on federal land is unconstitutional|date=January 5, 2011|work=CNN|access-date=23 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe issue has been in almost continual litigation ever since, with the city attempting to sell or give away the land under the cross. By an act of Congress, the federal government took possession of it under [[Eminent domain in the United States|eminent domain]] in 2006. The [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]] declared the cross unconstitutional in 2011, and the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] declined to hear an appeal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2012/jun/25/mount-soledad-case/|title=Supreme Court won't hear Mt. Soledad cross case|date=June 25, 2012|work=San Diego Union Tribune|access-date=23 May 2013}}</ref> In December 2013, U.S. District Judge Larry Burns ordered that the cross be removed within 90 days, but stayed the order pending a forthcoming appeal by the government.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fox5sandiego.com/2013/12/12/federal-judge-orders-mt-soledad-cross-must-come-down/#axzz2nJUI07xd|title=Federal judge says Mt. Soledad cross must come down|last=Wolski|first=Kristi|date=December 12, 2013|work=Fox 5 San Diego|access-date=14 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2013/dec/12/mount-solidad-cross-constitution-removal/|title=Judge: Mt. Soledad cross must come down|last=Davis|first=Kristina|date=December 12, 2013|work=San Diego Union Tribune|access-date=14 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn July 20, 2015, a group called the Mt. Soledad Memorial Association reported that it had bought the land under the cross from the [[U.S. Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] for $1.4 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2015/jul/20/mt-soledad-cross-stand-veterans-group-buys-land-de/|title=Mt. Soledad cross to stand as veterans group buys land from Defense Department|first=The Washington Times|last=http://www.washingtontimes.com|publisher=}}</ref> On September 7, 2016, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals issued a one-page ruling, ordering dismissal of the case and an end to all current appeals, stating that the case was now moot because the cross was no longer on government land. Both sides agreed that this decision puts a final end to the case.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/2016/sep/08/soledad-final/|title=Soledad cross case concludes, leaving memorial in place|last=Moran|first=Greg|date=September 8, 2016|work=San Diego Union-Tribune|access-date=9 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Arts===\nLa Jolla became an [[art colony]] in 1894 when Anna Held (also known as Anna Held Heinrich) established the Green Dragon Colony. This was a cluster of twelve cottages designed by [[Irving Gill]], who had moved to San Diego only a year earlier and later became San Diego's best-known architect.<ref name=\"Stern\">{{cite journal|last=Stern|first=Jean|title=Artists in La Jolla, 1890&ndash;1950|journal=Journal of San Diego History|pages=281\u2013287|url=http://www.sandiegohistory.org/journal/v54-4/pdf/v54-4Stern.pdf}}</ref>\n\nThe [[La Jolla Playhouse]] was founded in 1947 by [[Gregory Peck]], [[Dorothy McGuire]], and [[Mel Ferrer]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lajollaplayhouse.org/about-the-playhouse/playhouse-highlights |title=Playhouse Highlights |publisher=La Jolla Playhouse |access-date=May 23, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111115204055/http://www.lajollaplayhouse.org/about-the-playhouse/playhouse-highlights |archive-date=November 15, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It became inactive in 1959, but was revived in 1983 on the University of California campus under the leadership of [[Des McAnuff]]. It now incorporates three theaters: the [[Mandell Weiss Theatre]] (1983), the Mandell Weiss Forum (1991) and the Potiker Theater (2005).\n\nThe [[Museum of Contemporary Art San Diego]] was founded in 1941 in La Jolla, in the former home of Ellen Browning Scripps (designed by Irving J. Gill). The museum has undergone several renovations and expansions, and is working on plans to triple its size.<ref>{{cite news|first=David |last=Ng |date=March 17, 2014 |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/culture/la-et-cm-museum-contemporary-art-san-diego-architect-expansion-20140317,0,6886253.story |title=Museum of Contemporary Art San Diego picks architect for expansion |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |access-date=June 22, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117090544/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/culture/la-et-cm-museum-contemporary-art-san-diego-architect-expansion-20140317-story.html |archivedate=November 17, 2015 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lajollalight.com/news/2015/jul/28/permit-reviewers-approve-mcasd-plans/|title=La Jolla's permit reviewers approve museum expansion|last=Sherman|first=Pat|date=July 28, 2015|work=La Jolla Light|access-date=28 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[La Jolla Music Society]] was founded in 1941 as the Musical Arts Society of La Jolla by [[Nikolai Sokoloff]], former conductor of the [[Cleveland Orchestra]]. It presented the premieres of commissioned works in the auditorium of La Jolla High School before presenting their concerts in the Sherwood Auditorium of the Museum of Contemporary Art San Diego. Since April 2019, the [[Conrad Prebys Performing Arts Center]] is the permanent home of La Jolla Music Society and hosts world-class performances presented by LJMS as well as other San Diego arts presenters.  Additionally, The Conrad will see a wide range of conferences, corporate meetings, and private events.\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Lajollahighsmith104670u.jpg|thumb|right|View looking north from above the Children's Pool]]\n[[File:La Holla 020.jpg|thumb|right|View from Horseshoe]]\n[[File:Pdphoto lajolla 6 bg 060504.jpg|thumb|upright|Wipeout Beach]]\n\n===Demarcation===\nThe community's border starts at [[Pacific Beach, San Diego|Pacific Beach]] to the south and extends along the Pacific Ocean shoreline north to include [[Torrey Pines State Natural Reserve]] ending at [[Del Mar, California]]. La Jolla encompasses the neighborhoods<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ruthmillsteam.com/lajollamap.html |title=map of La Jolla neighborhoods |publisher=Ruthmillsteam.com |date= |access-date=2010-06-30}}</ref> of Bird Rock, [[Windansea Beach]], the commercial center known as the [[Village of La Jolla]], [[La Jolla Shores]], La Jolla Farms, Muirlands, [[Torrey Pines, San Diego|Torrey Pines]], and [[Mount Soledad]] to name a few.\n\nThe City of San Diego defines the community's eastern boundary as Gilman Drive and the [[Interstate 5 in California|Interstate 5 freeway]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sandiego.gov/planning/community/profiles/lajolla/index.shtml |title=San Diego City Department |publisher=Sandiego.gov |date= |access-date=2010-06-30}}</ref> and the northern boundary as UCSD.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sandiego.gov/neighborhoodmaps/northern.shtml |title=Northern Neighborhood &#124; Neighborhood Maps |publisher=Sandiego.gov |date= |access-date=2010-06-30}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Postal Service]] defines a somewhat larger area, assigning the community the 92037 [[ZIP Code]], recognizing it as a historically and geographically distinct area. This unique ZIP code allows addresses to read La Jolla, CA, and is the only community within the City of San Diego so recognized. Additionally, it is in the 919xx/920xx sequence used for suburban and rural ZIP Codes in San Diego County, rather than the 921xx sequence used for the remainder of the City of San Diego proper. These conditions sometimes lead to the erroneous impression that La Jolla is a separate city, rather than a part of San Diego. The 92037 ZIP code extends the northeasterly boundary to Genesee Avenue and the northerly boundary to [[Del Mar, California]]. The UCSD campus, although it is part of La Jolla, has ZIP Codes 92092 and 92093.\n\nDespite the city and postal service definitions, La Jolla does not have universally accepted boundaries. In the 1980s, the trustees of Scripps Hospital voted to move the campus from downtown La Jolla to [[University City, San Diego|University City]], east of Interstate 5 and not within the traditional boundaries of La Jolla. The governing documents of the hospital required it to be located in La Jolla, however. A court ruled that \"La Jolla\" exists merely as a \"state of mind\" and thus allowed the relocation of the hospital.<ref>Morgan, Neil. [https://books.google.com/books?id=0f8DAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA116&dq=%22la+jolla%22+%22state+of+mind%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi-xKiA_IHSAhVGzGMKHWPeAe4Q6AEIMTAC#v=onepage&q=%22la%20jolla%22%20%22state%20of%20mind%22&f=false \"The Building Block of Philanthropy\"]. San Diego Magazine. May 2005. p.116.</ref> Several businesses and housing developments east of Interstate 5 use \"La Jolla\" in their names despite being geographically located in the [[University City, San Diego|University City]] neighborhood of San Diego which incorporates everything east of Interstate 5.\n\n===Geology===\nLa Jolla is an area of mixed geology, including sandy beaches and rocky shorelines. The area is occasionally susceptible to flooding and ocean storms, as occurred in January and December 2010.<ref>{{cite web|last=Schwab |first=Dave |url=http://www.lajollalight.com/2010/01/21/flooding-closes-gym-on-la-jollas-pearl-street/ |title=Flooding closes gym on La Jolla's Pearl Street |publisher=La Jolla Light |date=January 20, 2010 |access-date=June 22, 2014 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20140623051741/http://www.lajollalight.com/2010/01/21/flooding-closes-gym-on-la-jollas-pearl-street/ |archivedate=June 23, 2014 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\n[[Mount Soledad]] is covered with the narrow roads that follow its contours and hundreds of homes overlooking the ocean on its slopes. It is the home of the large concrete [[Mount Soledad cross controversy|Mount Soledad Easter Cross]] built in 1954, later designated a Korean War Memorial, that became the center of a controversy over the display of religious symbols on government property.\n\nThe most compelling geographical highlight of La Jolla is its ocean front, with alternating rugged and sandy coastline that serves as habitat for many wild seal congregations. Popular beaches and coastal access points, listed from north to south, include:\n*[[Torrey Pines State Natural Reserve]]\n*[[Black's Beach]] (a ''de facto'' [[nude beach]])\n*Scripps, near [[Scripps Institution of Oceanography]]\n*[[La Jolla Shores]]\n*[[La Jolla Beach and Tennis Club]]\n*[[La Jolla Cove]]\n*Boomers Beach\n*[[Shell Beach, La Jolla|Shell Beach]]\n*[[Children's Pool Beach]]\n*Wipeout Beach\n*Horseshoes\n*Marine Street\n*[[Windansea Beach]]\n*Bird Rock\n\n==Demographics==\nAccording to United States Census Bureau figures, the [[Race and ethnicity in the United States Census|ethnic/racial makeup]] of La Jolla is 82.5% White, 0.8% Black, 0.2% American Indian, 11.2% Asian, 0.1% Pacific Islander, 2.0% some other race, and 3.1% two or more races.  Latinos, who may be of any race, form 7.2% of La Jolla's population.\n\nLa Jolla had the highest home prices in the nation in 2008<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/lifestyle/content/sep2008/bw2008098_534409.htm|title=Business Week, September 9, 2008|publisher=}}</ref> and 2009,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/2009/sep/24/la-jolla-called-most-expensive-housing-market-us-a/|title=La Jolla called most expensive housing market in U.S. again|first=Roger|last=Showley|publisher=}}</ref> according to a survey by [[Coldwell Banker]]. The survey compares the cost of a standardized four-bedroom home in communities across the country. The average price for such a home in La Jolla was reported as US$1.842 million in 2008 and US$2.125 million in 2009.\n{{wide image|LaJollaSkyline.jpg|1000px|alt=View of La Jolla|<center>View of La Jolla</center>}}\n\n==Neighborhoods==\n* '''La Jolla Farms'''&nbsp;\u2014 This northern La Jolla neighborhood is just west of UCSD. It includes the [[Torrey Pines Gliderport]], the [[Salk Institute for Biological Studies|Salk Institute]], and a group of expensive homes on the cliffs above [[Black's Beach]] (one of which is the [[Audrey Geisel University House]]).\n* '''[[La Jolla Shores]]'''&nbsp;\u2014 The residential area and the [[Scripps Institution of Oceanography]] campus along La Jolla Shores Beach and east up the hillside.  Also includes a small business district of shops and restaurants along Avenida de la Playa.\n* '''La Jolla Heights'''&nbsp;\u2014 The homes on the hills overlooking '''La Jolla Shores'''. No businesses.\n* '''Hidden Valley'''&nbsp;\u2014 Lower portion of [[Mount Soledad]] on the northern slopes. No businesses.\n* '''Country Club'''&nbsp;\u2014 Lower Mt. Soledad on the northwest side, including the La Jolla Country Club golf course.\n* '''[[Village of La Jolla|Village]]'''&nbsp;\u2014 Also called '''Village of La Jolla''' (not to be confused with '''La Jolla Village''') the \"downtown\" business district area, including most of La Jolla's shops and restaurants, and the immediately surrounding higher density and single family residential areas.\n* '''Beach-Barber Tract'''&nbsp;\u2014 The coastal section from [[Windansea Beach]] to the Village. A few shops and restaurants along La Jolla Boulevard.\n* '''Lower Hermosa'''&nbsp;\u2014 Coastal strip south of '''Beach-Barber Tract'''. No businesses.\n* '''[[Bird Rock, San Diego|Bird Rock]]'''&nbsp;\u2014 Southern coastal La Jolla, and the very lowest slopes of Mt. Soledad in the area. Notable for shops and restaurants along La Jolla Boulevard, five traffic roundabouts on La Jolla Boulevard, coastal bluffs, and surfing areas just two blocks off the main drag.\n* '''Muirlands'''&nbsp;\u2014 Relatively large area on western middle slope of Mt. Soledad. No businesses.\n* '''La Jolla Mesa''' &nbsp;\u2014 A strip on the lower southern side of Mt. Soledad, bordering [[Pacific Beach, San Diego|Pacific Beach]]. No businesses.\n* '''La Jolla Alta'''&nbsp;\u2014 A master-planned development east of '''La Jolla Mesa'''. No businesses.\n* '''Soledad South'''&nbsp;\u2014  Southeastern slopes of Mt. Soledad, all the way up to the top, east of '''La Jolla Alta'''.\n* '''Muirlands West'''&nbsp;\u2014 The small neighborhood between '''Muirlands''' to the south, and '''Country Club''' to the north. No businesses.\n* '''Upper Hermosa'''&nbsp;\u2014  Southwestern La Jolla, north of '''Bird Rock''' and east of La Jolla Blvd.\n* '''[[La Jolla Village, San Diego|La Jolla Village]]'''&nbsp;\u2014 Not to be confused with the '''Village''' (of La Jolla). In northeast La Jolla, east of '''La Jolla Heights''', west of [[Interstate 5 in California|I-5]] and south of UCSD. The neighborhood's namesake is the [[La Jolla Village Square]] shopping and residential mall, which includes two movie theaters.\n\n==Community groups==\nThe La Jolla Community Planning Association<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lajollacpa.org/ |title=La Jolla Community Planning Association |publisher=Lajollacpa.org |date= |access-date=2010-06-30}}</ref> advises the city council, Planning Commission, City Planning Department as well as other governmental agency as appropriate in the initial preparation, adoption of, implementation of, or amendment to the General or Community Plan as it pertains to the La Jolla area as well as review specific development proposals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sandiego.gov/planning/community/profiles/lajolla/ |title=La Jolla Community Profile |publisher=Sandiego.gov |date= |access-date=2010-06-30}}</ref> The nonprofit La Jolla Town Council<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lajollatowncouncil.org/ |title=La Jolla Town Council |publisher=La Jolla Town Council |date= |access-date=2010-06-30}}</ref> represents the interests of La Jolla businesses and residents that belong to the Council. The Bird Rock Community Council<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.birdrock.org/ |title=Bird Rock Community Council |publisher=Birdrock.org |date= |access-date=2010-06-30}}</ref> serves the Bird Rock neighborhood, while the La Jolla Shores Association<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lajollaguide.com/ljsa/ |title=La Jolla Shores Association |publisher=Lajollaguide.com |date= |access-date=2010-06-30}}</ref> serves the La Jolla Shores neighborhood. La Jolla Village Merchants Association, Inc. is a non-profit organization formed in February 2011 to manage the La Jolla Village Business Improvement District for the City of San Diego.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.LaJollabytheSea.com|title=Home|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nCommunity organizations include Independent La Jolla,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independentlajolla.org/ |title=Independent La Jolla |publisher=Independent La Jolla |date= |access-date=2010-06-30}}</ref> a membership-based citizens group seeking to secede from the city of San Diego. Service clubs in La Jolla include [[Kiwanis]], [[Rotary International|Rotary]], [[La Jolla Woman's Club]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Triqqer Code House |url=http://www.lajollawomansclub.com/ |title=La Jolla Women's Club |publisher=Lajollawomansclub.com |date= |access-date=2010-06-30}}</ref> and the Social Service League of La Jolla,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.darlingtonhouse.com/ |title=Social Service League of La Jolla |publisher=Darlingtonhouse.com |date= |access-date=2010-06-30}}</ref> to name a few.\n\n==Attractions and activities==\n[[File:Torrey Pines Golf Course clubhouse.jpg|thumb|[[Torrey Pines Golf Course]]]]\n[[File:La Jolla Museum of Contemporary Art.jpg|right|thumb|Museum of Contemporary Art - La Jolla]]<!-- |200px -->\n\nLa Jolla is the location of [[Torrey Pines Golf Course]], the site each January or February of a [[PGA Tour]] event formerly known as the Buick Invitational and since 2010, called the [[Farmers Insurance Open]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.farmersinsuranceopen.com/ |title=Farmers Insurance Open website |publisher=Farmersinsuranceopen.com |date= |access-date=2010-06-30}}</ref> Torrey Pines also hosted the 2008 [[U.S. Open (golf)|U.S. Open]], and will host the 2021 [[U.S. Open (golf)|U.S. Open.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usopen.com/u-s--open-future-sites.html#!1|title=U.S. Open Future Sites|last=|first=|date=|website=US Open|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 25, 2019}}</ref> Nearby are the [[de facto]] [[nude beach]], [[Black's Beach]], and the [[Torrey Pines Gliderport]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Sherman |first=Pat |url=http://www.lajollalight.com/2014/04/22/la-jolla-native-chronicles-gliderport%E2%80%99s-rich-history-in-new-book/ |title=La Jolla native chronicles Gliderport's rich history in new book |newspaper=La Jolla Light |date=April 22, 2014 |access-date=June 22, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812015843/http://www.lajollalight.com/2014/04/22/la-jolla-native-chronicles-gliderport%e2%80%99s-rich-history-in-new-book/ |archivedate=August 12, 2014 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nDowntown La Jolla is noted for jewelry stores, boutiques, upmarket restaurants and hotels. Prospect Street and Girard Avenue are also shopping and dining districts.<ref>{{Cite news|title=La Jolla |work=[[Where (magazine)|Where]] |url=http://wherela.com/sd/tours/la-jolla/ |access-date=June 22, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140617212633/http://wherela.com/sd/tours/la-jolla/ |archivedate=June 17, 2014 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> The Museum of Contemporary Art, founded in 1941, is located just above the waterfront in what was originally the 1915 residence of philanthropist [[Ellen Browning Scripps]]. The museum has a permanent collection with more than 3,500 post-1950 American and European works, including paintings, works on paper, sculptures, photographic art, design objects and video works.<ref name=Schaelchlin /> The museum was renamed [[Museum of Contemporary Art San Diego]] in 1990 to recognize its regional significance.\n\nBeaches and ocean access include [[Windansea Beach]], [[La Jolla Shores]], [[La Jolla Cove]] and [[Children's Pool Beach]]. For many years, La Jolla has been the host of a rough water swim at La Jolla Cove.<ref>[http://www.ljrws.com/site3.aspx La Jolla Rough Water Swim] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090826225958/http://www.ljrws.com/site3.aspx |date=2009-08-26 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the La Jolla Community Foundation commissioned various artists to contribute to the scenery of the town, through various [[mural]]s. Some of the artists that are featured in the series are [[John Baldessari]], [[Julian Opie]], and [[Kim MacConnel]]. There are 11 murals in the series, all of which will be on display for two years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lajollabluebook.com/blog/murals-of-la-jolla/|title=Murals of La Jolla - La Jolla Blue Book Blog|date=18 May 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Landmarks===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* Bed & Breakfast Inn at La Jolla\n* Grande Colonial Hotel\n* Harry's Coffee Shop\n* [[KGTV Tower]]\n* [[La Jolla Beach and Tennis Club]]\n* [[La Jolla Recreational Center]]\n* [[La Jolla Woman's Club]]\n* La Valencia (Cabrillo) Hotel\n* [[Mount Soledad cross controversy|Mt. Soledad Memorial]]\n* [[Museum of Contemporary Art San Diego]] ([[Ellen Browning Scripps]] residence)\n* [[The Bishop's School (La Jolla)|The Bishop's School]]\n* The 12 Green Dragon Buildings\n* [[University of California San Diego]]\n* [[Birch Aquarium at Scripps]]\n* [[Scripps Institution of Oceanography]]\n* Wisteria Cottage, home of the [[La Jolla Historical Society]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Geisel library.jpg|right|thumb|UCSD's distinctive [[Geisel Library]], named after Theodor Seuss Geisel (\"[[Dr. Seuss]]\") and featured in UCSD's logo]]\n\n===Higher education===\nThe [[University of California San Diego]] is the center of higher education in La Jolla. The campus' name was briefly UC La Jolla during the planning stage of the university's development. UCSD includes the [[Scripps Institution of Oceanography]] and the [[San Diego Supercomputer Center]].\n\n[[National University (California)|National University]] is also headquartered in La Jolla, with several academic campuses located throughout the county and the state. Among the several research institutes near UCSD and in the nearby Torrey Pines Science Park are [[Scripps Research Institute]], the [[Sanford Burnham Prebys Medical Discovery Institute]] (formerly called the La Jolla Cancer Research Foundation), [[La Jolla Institute for Allergy and Immunology]] (LJI), and the [[Salk Institute for Biological Studies]].\n\n===Other schools===\nLa Jolla is served by the [[San Diego Unified School District]]. Public schools include [[La Jolla High School]], La Jolla Elementary,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ljes.org/|title=Friends of La Jolla Elementary School|website=www.ljes.org}}</ref>  Muirlands Middle School,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sandiegounified.org/schools/muirlands|title=Muirlands {{!}} San Diego Unified School District|website=www.sandiegounified.org|access-date=2016-03-12}}</ref> Torrey Pines Elementary,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torreypineselementary.org/|title=Torrey Pines Elementary School - Home|website=www.torreypineselementary.org}}</ref> and Bird Rock Elementary,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sandi.net/birdrock/|title=Bird Rock - San Diego Unified School District|website=www.sandi.net}}</ref> as well as [[Preuss School]], a public [[charter school]]. The community's [[University-preparatory school|prep schools]] are [[The Bishop's School (La Jolla)|The Bishop's School]], The Children's School,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcslj.org/|title=The Children's School La Jolla: Progressive Private School in San Diego -|website=www.tcslj.org}}</ref> [[Delphi Schools|Delphi Academy]], Stella Maris Academy,<ref>[http://www.stellamarisacademy.org/ Stella Maris Academy], All Hallows Academy</ref> The Gillispie School, and the Evans School. [[La Jolla Country Day School]] is located in the nearby community of [[University City, San Diego|University City]].\n\n==Religious institutions==\n{{Div col|colwidth=22em}}\nChristian:\n* All Hallows Catholic Church<ref name=Schaelchlin>Schaelchlin, Patricia. ''La Jolla: The Story of a Community 1897-1987'', Friends of the La Jolla Library, San Diego, 1988</ref>\n* [[Assemblies of God|Assembly of God]]<ref name=Schaelchlin />\n* [[Christian Science]] Church<ref name=Schaelchlin />\n* [[Congregational church|Congregational Church]] (the first church built; burned down in 1915 and re-built in 1916 at 1216 Cave Street)<ref name=Schaelchlin />\n* Barabbas Road Church<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whoisbarabbas.com/|title=Barabbas Road Church in San Diego, Pacific Beach, La Jolla, CA|website=Barabbas Road Church in San Diego, CA}}</ref>\n* First Baptist Church\n* La Jolla Christian Fellowship\n* La Jolla Lutheran Church<ref name=Schaelchlin />\n* La Jolla Presbyterian Church<ref name=Schaelchlin />\n* La Jolla Religious [[Quakers|Society of Friends]]<ref name=Schaelchlin />\n* La Jolla [[United Methodist Church]]<ref name=Schaelchlin />\n* Mary, Star of the Sea Catholic church<ref name=Schaelchlin />\n* Prince Chapel by the Sea ([[African Methodist Episcopal Church]]) <ref name=Schaelchlin />\n* St. James by-the-Sea Episcopal<ref name=Schaelchlin />\n* St. John Church of God in Christ<ref name=Schaelchlin />\n* Torrey Pines Christian Church<ref name=Schaelchlin />\n* University Lutheran Church<ref name=Schaelchlin />\n\nJewish:\n* Congregation Beth El<ref name=Schaelchlin />\n* Congregation Adat Yeshurun<ref name=Schaelchlin />\n* [[Chabad]] Jewish Center of La Jolla\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Business and media==\nLa Jolla (under the fictionalized name \"Esmerelda\") is the setting for [[Raymond Chandler]]'s final\n[[Philip Marlowe]] novel, [[Playback (novel)|''Playback'']], published in 1958. Chandler\nlived in La Jolla for the previous decade. La Jolla's [[Hotel del Charro]] becomes \"Rancho\nDescansado\" in the novel.  A number of landmarks described can still be found today.\n<ref>Raymond Chandler, ''Playback'', Houghton Mifflin, 1958</ref>\n<ref>OriginallyPB (pseudonym),\n[http://thewebsters.us/2015/01/16/raymond-chandlers-esmeralda/ \"Raymond Chandler's Esmerelda\"],\nAnother Side of History (blog), January 16, 2015</ref>\n\nLa Jolla was home to the comic book publisher [[WildStorm|WildStorm Productions]], from its founding by [[Jim Lee]] in 1993, until its closing in 2012 when [[DC Comics]], which had purchased the publisher as an imprint in 1998, absorbed the company and moved the office to Burbank, California.<ref>Wells, Aaron. [http://www.lajollalight.com/2008/07/25/wild-wild-comic-art/ \"Wild, wild comic art\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006234740/http://www.lajollalight.com/2008/07/25/wild-wild-comic-art/ |date=2011-10-06 }}, ''La Jolla Light'', July 25, 2008</ref><ref>Iyoho, Charles. [http://lajolla.patch.com/articles/is-superman-fleeing-la-jolla#c \"Are Superheroes Fleeing La Jolla?\"], La Jolla Patch, October 18, 2010</ref><ref>Phegley, Kiel. [http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=28446 \"WildStorm & Zuda Imprints Close Amidst DC Changes\"], [[Comic Book Resources]], September 21, 2010</ref><ref>[http://www.comicsbeat.com/2010/09/21/a-day-of-change-bye-bye-wildstorm-so-long-zuda/ \"A day of change: bye bye, WildStorm; so long, Zuda\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110816103846/http://www.comicsbeat.com/2010/09/21/a-day-of-change-bye-bye-wildstorm-so-long-zuda/ |date=2011-08-16 }}, The Beat, September 21, 2010</ref>\n\nLa Jolla is the setting for the 2011 season of ''[[The Real World: San Diego (2011)|The Real World: San Diego]]'', the twenty-sixth season of the long-running [[MTV]] reality television series.<ref name=\"RealityBlurred\">{{cite news|url=http://www.realityblurred.com/realitytv/archives/the_real_world_26/2011_Jun_07_san_diego|title=Real World returning to San Diego for its 26th season|last=Dehnart|first=Andy|authorlink=Andy Dehnart|publisher=RealityBlured.com|date=June 7, 2011|access-date=June 7, 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://www.movewithtitan.com/mtvs-real-world-will-screen-from-pacific-beach-california-according-to-san-diego-movers \"MTV\u2019s ''Real World'' will screen from La Jolla, California according to San Diego Movers\"], Titan Movers, May 27, 2011</ref>\n\nLa Jolla is the base for the [[Sundt Memorial Foundation]], a national organization aimed at discouraging youth from getting involved in drugs.\n\nLa Jolla is mentioned in the [[The Beach Boys|Beach Boys']] 1963 song [[Surfin' U.S.A. (song)|Surfin' U.S.A.]] and in [[The Network|The Network's]] 2003 song [[Money Money 2020|Spike]].\n\nIn [[The Big Lebowski]] (1998), [[The Big Lebowski|Walter Sobchak]] eulogizes his friend thus: \"''Donny was a good bowler, and a good man. He was one of us. He was a man who loved the outdoors... and bowling, and as a surfer he explored the beaches of Southern California, from La Jolla to [[Leo Carrillo State Park|Leo Carrillo]] and... up to... [[Pismo State Beach|Pismo]].''\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikiquote.org/wiki/The_Big_Lebowski|title=The Big Lebowski - Wikiquote|website=en.wikiquote.org|language=en|access-date=2019-01-08}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Netflix]] [[sitcom]] ''[[Grace and Frankie]]'' is set in La Jolla, although exteriors are filmed in other parts of California.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://houseandhome.com/gallery/inside-stunning-homes-netflixs-grace-frankie/|title=Inside The Stunning Homes Of Netflix's Grace & Frankie|website=houseandhome.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-03}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n{{Main|List of people from La Jolla}}\nLa Jolla has been the home to many notable people, including prominent scientists, business people, artists, writers, surfers and performers.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|California}}\n* [[List of San Diego Historical Landmarks in La Jolla]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite book |last=Langdon |first=Margaret |year=1970 |title=A grammar of Diegueno: the Mesa Grande dialect |location=Berkeley |publisher=University of California Press |isbn= }}\n*{{Cite book |last=Schaelchlin |first=Patricia |year=1988 |title=La Jolla: The Story of a Community 1897-1987 |location=La Jolla |publisher=Friends of the La Jolla Library |isbn= }}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|La Jolla, San Diego|<br />La Jolla, San Diego}}\n{{wikivoyage|San_Diego/La_Jolla|La Jolla}}\n* [http://lajollatowncouncil.org La Jolla Town Council]\n* [http://www.lajollahistory.org La Jolla Historical Society]\n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20130601061923/http://www.lajollahistory.org/historic-la-jolla/la-jolla-history-timeline/ Local hi