{"title_page": "Golden Dragon Splendour", "text_new": "{{Infobox UK Bus\n | background       = \n | name             = Golden Dragon Splendour\n | image            = AW5816 at ZBAA T3 (20191105132010).jpg\n | imagesize        = 270px\n | caption          = A Golden Dragon Splendour in [[China]]\n | manufacturer     = [[Golden Dragon (company)|Golden Dragon]]\n | factory          =  \n | production       =  2015 \u2013 present\n | replaced         = \n | capacity         = \n | operator         = \n | length           = \n | width            = \n | height           = \n | floortype        = step entrance \n | doors            = 1/2 door \n | weight           = \n | chassis          = \n | engine           = 6.7L Cummins ISDe<br>6.5L Yuchai YC6J<br>7.2L Yuchai YC6A<br>7.8L Yuchai YC6G\n | powerout         = \n | transmission     = 6-speed manual<br>6-speed automatic ([[ZF Friedrichshafen AG|ZF]])\n | options          = Various customer options\n}}\n\nThe '''Golden Dragon Splendour''' is a mini [[coach (bus)|integral coach]] built by [[Golden Dragon (company)|Golden Dragon]]. It was introduced in 2015 and is available ranges from 8.9-meters to 9.5-meters. Engine options including the 6.7L [[Cummins]] ISDe, 6.5L Yuchai YC6J, 7.2L Yuchai YC6A and 7.8L Yuchai YC6G.\n\n==Philippine version==\nA version of the Golden Dragon Splendour with a longer height and is produced in the [[Philippines]] at the facility of Trans-Oriental Motor Builders, Inc. in [[Naic, Cavite|Naic]], [[Cavite]]. It is powered by the 7.8L Yuchai YC6G engine that offers 240 PS at 2,200 rpm and 940 Nm of torque from 1,400 - 1,600 rpm, and 270 PS at 2,200 rpm and 1,080 Nm of torque from 1,400 - 1,600 rpm. The sole transmission choice is a 6-speed manual.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Buses}}\n*[http://www.goldendragonbus.com/car/view/11149.html Product official website]\n\n[[Category:Coaches (bus)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox UK Bus\n | background       = \n | name             = Golden Dragon Splendour\n | image            = AW5816 at ZBAA T3 (20191105132010).jpg\n | imagesize        = 270px\n | caption          = A Golden Dragon Splendour in [[China]]\n | manufacturer     = [[Golden Dragon (company)|Golden Dragon]]\n | factory          =  \n | production       =  2015 \u2013 present\n | replaced         = \n | capacity         = \n | operator         = \n | length           = \n | width            = \n | height           = \n | floortype        = step entrance \n | doors            = 1/2 door \n | weight           = \n | chassis          = \n | engine           = 6.7L Cummins ISDe<br>6.5L Yuchai YC6J<br>7.2L Yuchai YC6A<br>7.8L Yuchai YC6G\n | powerout         = \n | transmission     = 6-speed manual<br>6-speed automatic ([[ZF Friedrichshafen AG|ZF]])\n | options          = Various customer options\n}}\n\nThe '''Golden Dragon Splendour''' is a mini [[coach (bus)|integral coach]] built by [[Golden Dragon (company)|Golden Dragon]]. It was introduced in 2015 and is available ranges from 8.9-meters to 9.5-meters. Engine options including the 6.7L [[Cummins]] ISDe, 6.5L Yuchai YC6J, 7.2L Yuchai YC6A and 7.8L Yuchai YC6G.\n\n==Philippine version==\nA version of the Golden Dragon Splendour with a longer height and is produced in the [[Philippines]] at the facility of Trans-Oriental Motor Builders, Inc. in [[Naic, Cavite|Naic]], [[Cavite]]. It is powered by the 7.8L Yuchai YC6G engine that offers 240 PS at 2,200 rpm and 940 Nm of torque from 1,400 - 1,600 rpm, and 270 PS at 2,200 rpm and 1,080 Nm of torque from 1,400 - 1,600 rpm. The sole transmission choice is a 6-speed manual.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Buses}}\n*[http://www.goldendragonbus.com/car/view/11149.html Product official website]\n\n[[Category:Coaches (bus)]]\n", "name_user": "Rheysterjohndelera1", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_Dragon_Splendour"}
{"title_page": "Forth Bridge", "text_new": "{{short description|Cantilever railway bridge over the Firth of Forth in the east of Scotland}}\n{{distinguish|Fourth Bridge}}\n{{about|the railway bridge|the road bridge|Forth Road Bridge|other uses}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox bridge\n|bridge_name= Forth Bridge\n|image={{Css Image Crop|Image = Scotland-2016-Aerial-Edinburgh-Forth Bridge.jpg|bSize = 380|cWidth = 300|cHeight = 120|oTop = 30|oLeft = 38|Location = center}}\n|owner = [[Network Rail]]\n|carries =Rail traffic\n|crosses =[[Firth of Forth]]\n|locale =[[Edinburgh]], [[Inchgarvie]] and [[Fife]], Scotland\n|maint =[[Balfour Beatty]] under contract to Network Rail\n|designer = Sir [[Sir John Fowler, 1st Baronet|John Fowler]] and<br>Sir [[Benjamin Baker (engineer)|Benjamin Baker]]\n|design =[[Cantilever bridge]]\n|mainspan =Two of {{convert|1700|ft}}<ref name=nr>{{cite web|title=Forth Bridge|url=http://www.networkrail.co.uk/VirtualArchive/forth-bridge/|website=NetworkRail|publisher=Network Rail|accessdate=3 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150704235928/http://www.networkrail.co.uk/VirtualArchive/forth-bridge/|archive-date=4 July 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|length = {{convert|8094|ft}}<ref name=nr/>\n|width ={{convert|120|ft|abbr=on}} at piers<ref name=nr/><br />{{convert|32|ft|abbr=on}} at centre<ref name=nr/>\n|height ={{convert|361|ft|abbr=on}} above high water<ref name=nr/>\n|below ={{convert|150|ft|abbr=on}} to high water<ref name=nr/>\n|traffic =190\u2013200 trains per day\n|begin =1882\n|complete =December 1889\n|open=4 March 1890\n|coordinates = {{coord|56.0004|-3.3886|region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n|map_type = UK Scotland\n|extra =  {{Designation list\n  | embed                   = yes\n  | designation1            = World Heritage Site\n  | designation1_offname    = The Forth Bridge\n  | designation1_type       = cultural\n  | designation1_criteria   = i, iv\n  | designation1_date       = 2015\n  | delisted1_date          =\n  | designation1_number     = [https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1485 1485]\n  | designation2            = Category A Listed Building\n  | designation2_offname    = Forth Bridge\n  | designation2_type       =\n  | designation2_criteria   =\n  | designation2_date       = 18 June 1973\n  | delisted2_date          =\n  | designation2_number     = [http://portal.historicenvironment.scot/designation/LB40370 LB40370]\n}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Forth Bridge'''<ref name=\"bridgeName\">{{cite web|title=The Forth Bridge|url=http://www.forth-bridges.co.uk/forth-bridge.html|website=forth-bridges.co.uk|publisher=Forth Bridges Forum|accessdate=26 March 2017|date=2015|quote=Opened in 1890, The Forth Bridge is recognised the world over as the most famous of cantilever designs.}}</ref> is a [[cantilever bridge|cantilever]] [[rail transport|railway]] bridge across the [[Firth of Forth]] in the east of [[Scotland]], {{convert|9|mi|abbr=off}} west of central [[Edinburgh]]. It is considered as a symbol of Scotland (having been voted Scotland's greatest man-made wonder in 2016), and is a [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]]. It was designed by the English engineers [[Sir John Fowler, 1st Baronet|Sir John Fowler]] and [[Benjamin Baker (engineer)|Sir Benjamin Baker]]. It is sometimes referred to as the '''Forth Rail Bridge''' (to distinguish it from the adjacent [[Forth Road Bridge]]), although this has never been its official name.\n\nConstruction of the bridge began in 1882 and it was opened on 4 March 1890 by the [[Duke of Rothesay]], the future [[Edward VII]]. The bridge carries the [[Edinburgh\u2013Aberdeen line]] across the Forth between the villages of [[South Queensferry]] and [[North Queensferry]] and has a total length of {{convert|2467|m|order=flip}}. When it opened it had the [[list of longest cantilever bridge spans|longest single cantilever bridge span]] in the world, until 1919 when the [[Quebec Bridge]] in [[Canada]] was completed. It continues to be the world's second-longest single cantilever span, with a span of {{convert|521|m|order=flip}}.\n\nThe bridge and its associated railway infrastructure are owned by [[Network Rail]].\n\n==Background==\n[[File:The guts of the Forth Bridge - geograph.org.uk - 1318782.jpg|thumb|View of the structure]]\n\n===Earlier proposals===\n{{Main|History of the Forth Crossing}}\n\nBefore the construction of the bridge, [[Ferry|ferries]] were used to cross the Firth.<ref name=m58>{{harvnb|McKean|2006|p=58}}</ref> In 1806, a pair of tunnels, one for each direction, was proposed, and in 1818 [[James Anderson (civil engineer)|James Anderson]] produced a design for a three-span suspension bridge close to the site of the present one.<ref name=2006p2>{{harvnb|Harding|Gerard|Ryall|2006|p=2}}</ref> Calling for approximately {{convert|2500|t}} of iron, Wilhelm Westhofen said of it \"and this quantity [of iron] distributed over the length would have given it a very light and slender appearance, so light indeed that on a dull day it would hardly have been visible, and after a heavy gale probably no longer to be seen on a clear day either\".<ref name=w1>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=1}}</ref>\n\nFor the railway age, [[Thomas Bouch]] designed for the [[Edinburgh and Northern Railway]] a [[roll-on/roll-off]] [[Train ferry|ferry]] between [[Granton, Edinburgh|Granton]] and [[Burntisland]] that opened in 1850, which proved so successful that another was ordered for the Tay.<ref name=\"m58-59\">{{harvnb|McKean|2006|pp=58\u201359}}</ref> In late 1863, a joint project between the [[North British Railway]] and [[Edinburgh and Glasgow Railway]], which would merge in 1865, appointed Stephenson and Toner to design a bridge for the Forth, but the commission was given to Bouch around six months later.<ref name=m62>{{harvnb|McKean|2006|p=62}}</ref>\n\nIt had proven difficult to engineer a [[suspension bridge]] that was able to carry railway traffic, and Thomas Bouch, engineer to the [[North British Railway]] (NBR) and [[Edinburgh and Glasgow Railway]], was in 1863\u20131864 working on a [[Single-track railway|single-track]] [[girder bridge]] crossing the Forth near [[Charlestown, Fife|Charlestown]], where the river is around {{convert|2|mi|km}} wide, but mostly relatively shallow.<ref name=m62/><ref name=\"rp24-27\">{{harvnb|Paxton|1990|pp=24\u201327}}</ref> The promoters, however, were concerned about the ability to set foundations in the silty river bottom, as borings had gone as deep as {{convert|231|ft}} into the mud without finding any rock, but Bouch conducted experiments to demonstrate that it was possible for the silt to support considerable weight.<ref name=rp29>{{harvnb|Paxton|1990|p=29}}</ref> Experiments in late 1864 with weighted caissons achieved a pressure of {{convert|5|t/sqft|LT/sqft ST/sqft|abbr=on}} on the silt, encouraging Bouch to continue with the design.<ref name=rp29/> In August 1865, Richard Hodgson, chairman of the NBR, proposed that the company invest {{GBP|18000}} to try a different kind of foundation, as the weighted caissons had not been successful.<ref name=\"m73-74\">{{harvnb|McKean|2006|pp=73\u201374}}</ref> Bouch proposed using a large pine platform underneath the piers, {{convert|80|x|60|x|7|ft|m}} (the original design called for a {{convert|114|x|80|x|9|ft|m}} platform of green beech) weighed down with {{convert|10000|t}} of [[pig iron]] which would sink the wooden platform to the level of the silt.<ref name=rp29/> The platform was launched on 14 June 1866 after some difficulty in getting it to move down the greased planks it rested on, and then moored in the harbour for six weeks pending completion.<ref name=rp29/><ref name=m77>{{harvnb|McKean|2006|p=77}}</ref> The bridge project was aborted just before the platform was sunk as the NBR expected to lose \"through traffic\" following the amalgamation of the [[Caledonian Railway]] and the [[Scottish North Eastern Railway]].<ref name=rp29/> In September 1866, a committee of shareholders investigating rumours of financial difficulties found that accounts had been falsified, and the chairman and the entire board had resigned by November.<ref name=m78>{{harvnb|McKean|2006|p=78}}</ref> By mid-1867 the NBR was nearly bankrupt, and all work on the Forth and Tay bridges was stopped.<ref name=m81>{{harvnb|McKean|2006|p=81}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Forth Bridge (1890) Figs. 2 and 3, Page 4.png|thumb|upright=1.5<!--image represents multiple low aspect diagrams-->|Bouch's proposed bridge (top) along with other proposals on the same principle]]\n\nThe North British Railway took over the ferry at Queensferry in 1867, and completed a rail link from [[Ratho]] in 1868, establishing a contiguous link with Fife.<ref name=rp32>{{harvnb|Paxton|1990|p=32}}</ref> Interest in bridging the Forth increased again, and Bouch proposed a stiffened steel suspension bridge on roughly the line of the present rail bridge in 1871, and after careful verification, work started in 1878 on a pier at [[Inchgarvie]].<ref name=rp32/>\n\nAfter the [[Tay Bridge disaster|Tay Bridge collapsed]] in 1879, confidence in Bouch dried up and the work stopped.<ref name=rp32/> The public inquiry into the disaster, chaired by [[Henry Cadogan Rothery]], found the Tay Bridge to be \"badly designed, badly constructed and badly maintained\", with Bouch being \"mainly to blame\" for the defects in construction and maintenance and \"entirely responsible\" for the defects in design.<ref>{{harvnb|Summerhayes|2010|p=7}}</ref>\n\nAfter the disaster, which occurred in high winds for which Bouch had not properly accounted, the [[Board of Trade]] imposed a lateral wind allowance of {{convert|56|lb/sqft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"rp41-44\">{{harvnb|Paxton|1990|p=41}}</ref> Bouch's 1871 design had taken a much lower figure of {{convert|10|lb/sqft|abbr=on}} on the advice of the [[Astronomer Royal]], although contemporary analysis showed it would probably have stood, but the engineers making the analysis stated that \"we do not commit ourselves to an opinion that it is the best possible\" [design].<ref name=\"rp44-45\">{{harvnb|Paxton|1990|pp=44\u201345}}</ref> Bouch's design was formally abandoned on 13 January 1881, and [[Sir John Fowler, 1st Baronet|Sir John Fowler]], [[William Henry Barlow|W. H. Barlow]] and T. E. Harrison, consulting engineers to the project, were invited to give proposals for a bridge.<ref name=\"rp47-49\">{{harvnb|Paxton|1990|pp=47\u201349}}</ref><ref name=\"bridgeDesigners\">{{cite web|url=http://www.forth-bridges.co.uk/forth-bridge/history.html|title=History of the Forth Bridge|date=2015|website=forth-bridges.co.uk|publisher=Forth Bridges Forum|quote=the momentum for a crossing had grown and a new design, by John Fowler and Benjamin Baker, was submitted to the Forth Bridge Company in May 1881, with construction authorised by Parliament in July 1882.|accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Design==\n[[File:Forth Bridge (1890) Fig. 4, Page 5.png|thumb|upright=1.5<!--width for low aspect image-->|The original (above) and final (below) designs of the Forth Bridge]]\n\n===Dimensions===\nThe bridge spans the Forth between the villages of [[South Queensferry]] and [[North Queensferry]] and has a total length of {{convert|2467|m|order=flip}}<ref name=\"nr\" /> with the double track elevated {{convert|150|ft|m|2}} above the water level at high tide. It consists of two main spans of {{convert|1700|ft|m|2|}}, two side spans of {{convert|207.3|m|order=flip|abbr=on}}, and 15 approach spans of {{convert|51.2|m|ft|order=flip|abbr=on}}.<ref name=nr/><ref name=\"facts\">\"[http://www.forthbridges.org.uk/railbridgefacts.htm Forth Rail Bridge Facts & Figures] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121223015457/http://www.forthbridges.org.uk/railbridgefacts.htm |date=23 December 2012 }}\". Forth Bridges Visitors Centre Trust. Retrieved 21 April 2006.</ref> Each main span consists of two {{convert|207.3|m|ft|order=flip|abbr=on}} [[cantilever]] arms supporting a central {{convert|106.7|m|ft|order=flip}} span truss. The weight of the bridge superstructure was {{convert|50513|LT}}, including the 6.5&nbsp;million [[rivet]]s used.<ref name=\"facts\"/> The bridge also used {{convert|18122|m3|order=flip}} of [[granite]].<ref name=Gazetteer>{{cite web |url=http://www.scottish-places.info/features/featurefirst1053.html |title=Overview of Forth Bridge |work=The Gazetteer for Scotland |accessdate=21 April 2006}}</ref>\n\nThe three great four-tower cantilever structures are {{convert|361|ft|m|2}} tall,<ref name=nr/> each tower resting on a separate [[granite]] pier. These were constructed using {{convert|70|ft|m|abbr=on}} diameter [[caisson (engineering)|caissons]]; those for the north cantilever and two on the small uninhabited island of [[Inchgarvie]] acted as [[cofferdam]]s, while the remaining two on Inchgarvie and those for the south cantilever, where the river bed was {{convert|91|ft|m|abbr=on}} below high-water level, used compressed air to keep water out of the working chamber at the base.<ref name=\"Descriptionand1890\">{{cite news |title=Description and History of the Bridge |issue=32950 |page=13 |newspaper=The Times|location=London |date=4 March 1890 }}</ref>\n\n{{comparison_of_notable_bridges.svg}}\n\n===Engineering principles===\n[[File:Cantilever bridge human model.jpg|thumb|right|Illustration of the cantilever principle]]\nThe bridge is built on the principle of the [[cantilever bridge]], where a [[cantilever]] beam supports a light central girder, a principle that has been used for thousands of years in the construction of bridges.<ref name=w4>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=4}}</ref> In order to illustrate the use of tension and compression in the bridge, a demonstration in 1887 had the Japanese engineer [[Kaichi Watanabe]] supported between Fowler and Baker sitting in chairs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.universitystory.gla.ac.uk/biography/?id=WH17361&type=P |title=Kaichi Watanabe |publisher=University of Glasgow |accessdate=26 December 2014}}</ref> Fowler and Baker represent the cantilevers, with their arms in tension and the sticks under compression, and the bricks the cantilever end piers which are weighted with cast iron.<ref name=w6>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=6}}</ref>\n\n===Materials===\nThe bridge was the first major structure in Britain to be constructed of steel;<ref>{{harvnb|Blanc|McEvoy|Plank|2003|p=16}}</ref> its French contemporary, the [[Eiffel Tower]], was built of [[wrought iron]].<ref name=\"Hanser2006\">{{cite book |author=Hanser, David A. |title=Architecture of France |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zojzUU976h0C&pg=PA66 |year=2006 |publisher=Greenwood |isbn=978-0-313-31902-0 |page=66}}</ref>\nLarge amounts of steel became available after the invention of the [[Bessemer process]], patented in 1856.<ref>{{cite book |last=Wagner |first=Donald |title=Science and Civilisation in China: Vol. 5, Part 11: Ferrous Metallurgy |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FAud8CE5stsC&pg=PA361 |year=2008 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-87566-0 |page=361}}</ref><!-- The British [[Board of Trade]] had limited the use of steel in [[structural engineering]], as the produced steel was of unpredictable strength due to the production process. This limit was lifted in 1877 after the development of the [[Open hearth furnace|Siemens-Martin open-hearth process]] in 1875{{fact}}, which yielded steel of consistent quality.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}--> In 1859, the Board of Trade imposed a limit of {{convert|5|LTf/in2|N/mm2|2|abbr=on|lk=on|order=flip}} for the maximum design stress in railway bridges; this was revised as technology progressed.<ref name=\"historic-construction\">{{cite book|last1=D'Ayala |first1=Dina |last2=Fodde |first2=Enrico |title=Structural Analysis of Historic Construction: Preserving Safety and Significance, Two Volume Set: Proceedings of the VI International Conference on Structural Analysis of Historic Construction, SAHC08, 2\u20134 July 2008, Bath, United Kingdom |publisher=CRC Press |isbn=978-1-4398-2822-9 |page=209 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TVnRBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA209 |accessdate=30 April 2017|date=2 June 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe original design required {{convert|42000|t}} for the cantilevers only, of which {{convert|12000|t}} was to come from Siemens' steel works in [[Landore]], [[Wales]] and the remainder from the Steel Company of Scotland's works near Glasgow.<ref name=\"w36-37\">{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|pp=36\u201337}}</ref> When modifications to the design necessitated a further {{convert|16000|t}}, about half of this was supplied by the Steel Company of Scotland Ltd. and half by Dalzell's Iron and Steel Works in Motherwell.<ref name=w37>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=37}}</ref> About {{convert|4200|t}} of rivets came from the Clyde Rivet Company of Glasgow.<ref name=w37/> Around three or four thousand tons of steel was scrapped, some of which was used for temporary purposes, resulting in the discrepancy between the quantity delivered and the quantity erected.<ref name=w37/>\n\n===Approaches===\n[[File:Forth bridges 2005-06-17 06.jpg|thumb|The southern approach to the Forth Bridge, designed by [[James Carswell]]]]\nAfter [[Dalmeny railway station]], the track curves very slightly to the east before coming to the southern approach viaduct.<ref name=gmap>{{Google maps |url=https://www.google.co.uk/maps/@55.9996898,-3.3863626,14z |title=Forth Bridge |accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref> After the railway crosses the bridge, it passes through [[North Queensferry railway station]], before curving to the west, and then back to the east over the [[Jamestown Viaduct]].<ref name=gmap/>\n\nThe approaches were built under separate contract and were to the design of the engineer [[James Carswell]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scottisharchitects.org.uk/architect_full.php?id=100260 |title=James Carswell |website=Dictionary of Scottish Architects |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref> The supports of the approach viaducts are [[Entasis|tapered]] to prevent the impression of the columns widening as they approach the top, and an evaluation of the aesthetics of the Bridge in 2007, by A D Magee of the [[University of Bath]], identified that order was present throughout, and this included in the approach viaducts. Magee points out that the masonry was carefully planned, and has neat block work even in areas not immediately visible from the ground.<ref name=\"magee\" />{{rp|6}}\n\n==Construction==\n[[File:Forth Bridge - General view from back of Newhalls Inn, South Queensferry.jpg|left|thumb|The bridge under construction, viewed from South Queensferry]]\nThe Bill for the construction of the bridge was passed on 19 May 1882 after an eight-day enquiry, the only objections being from rival railway companies.<ref name=rp67>{{harvnb|Paxton|1990|p=67}}</ref> On 21 December, the contract was let to Sir Thomas Tancred, Mr. T. H. Falkiner and Mr. Joseph Philips, civil engineers and contractor, and [[Sir William Arrol & Co.]].<ref name=\"rp67-68\">{{harvnb|Paxton|1990|pp=67\u201368}}</ref> Arrol was a [[self-made man]], who had been apprenticed to a blacksmith at the age of thirteen before going on to have a highly successful business.<ref name=\"rp68-70\">{{harvnb|Paxton|1990|pp=68\u201370}}</ref> Tancred was a professional engineer who had worked with Arrol before, but he would leave the partnership during the course of construction.<ref name=rp70>{{harvnb|Paxton|1990|p=70}}</ref>\n\nThe steel was produced by Frederick and William Siemens (England) and Pierre and Emile Martin (France). Following advances in furnace design by the Siemens brothers and improvements by the Martin brothers, the process of manufacture enabled high quality steel to be produced very quickly.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.railway-technology.com/projects/forth-rail-bridge-firth-scotland/ |title=Forth Rail Bridge, Firth of Forth |work=Railway Technology |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://kids.britannica.com/comptons/article-202991/iron-and-steel-industry |title=iron and steel industry |publisher=Britannica |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.industrialmetalcastings.com/foundries_open_hearth.html|title=Open Hearth Furnace|website=www.industrialmetalcastings.com|access-date=30 April 2017|publisher=Industrialmetalcastings.com|date=2010}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Preparations===\n[[File:George Washington Wilson.jpg|thumb|The bridge under construction]]\nThe new works took possession of offices and stores erected by Arrol in connection with Bouch's bridge; these were expanded considerably over time.<ref name=w12>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=12}}</ref> Reginald Middleton took an accurate survey to establish the exact position of the bridge and allow the permanent construction work to commence.<ref name=\"w12-13\">{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|pp=12\u201313}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Triangulation & measurements at the Forth bridge |publisher=worldcat.org |oclc = 123250114}}</ref>\n\nThe old coastguard station at the Fife end had to be removed to make way for the north-east pier.<ref name=w13>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=13}}</ref> The rocky shore was levelled to a height of {{convert|7|ft}} above high water to make way for plant and materials, and huts and other facilities for workmen were set up further inland.<ref name=w13/>\n\nThe preparations at South Queensferry were much more substantial, and required the steep hillside to be terraced.<ref name=w13/> Wooden huts and shops for the workmen were put up, as well as more substantial brick houses for the foremen and tenements for leading hands and gangers.<ref name=w13/> Drill roads and workshops were built, as well as a [[Lofting|drawing loft]] {{convert|200|by|60|ft}} to allow full size drawings and templates to be laid out.<ref name=w13/> A cable was also laid across the Forth to allow telephone communication between the centres at South Queensferry, Inchgarvie, and North Queensferry, and girders from the collapsed [[Tay Rail Bridge|Tay Bridge]] were laid across the railway to the west in order to allow access to the ground there.<ref name=w13/> Near the shore a [[sawmill]] and cement store were erected, and a substantial jetty around {{convert|2100|ft}} long was started early in 1883, and extended as necessary, and [[Siding (rail)|sidings]] were built to bring railway vehicles among the shops, and cranes set up to allow the loading and movement of material delivered by rail.<ref name=w13/>\n\nIn April 1883, construction of a landing stage at [[Inchgarvie]] commenced.<ref name=w13/> Extant buildings, including fortifications built in the 15th century, were roofed over to increase the available space, and the rock at the west of the island was cut down to a level {{convert|7|ft}} above high water, and a seawall was built to protect against large waves.<ref name=w13/> In 1884 a [[compulsory purchase]] order was obtained for the island, as it was found that previously available area enclosed by the four piers of the bridge was insufficient for the storage of materials.<ref name=w13/> Iron staging reinforced wood in heavily used areas was put up over the island, eventually covering around {{convert|10000|sqyd}} and using over {{convert|1000|t}} of iron.<ref name=w14>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=14}}</ref>\n\n===Movement of materials===\n\nThe bridge uses {{convert|55000|t}} of [[steel]] and {{convert|140000|cuyd}} of masonry.<ref name=w14/> Many materials, including [[granite]] from [[Aberdeen]], [[Arbroath]] rubble, sand, timber, and sometimes coke and coal, could be taken straight to the centre where they were required.<ref name=w14/> Steel was delivered by train and prepared at the yard at [[South Queensferry]], painted with boiled [[linseed oil]], and was then taken to where it was needed by barge.<ref name=w14/> The cement used was [[Portland cement]] manufactured on the [[Medway]].<ref name=w17/> It required to be stored before it was able to be used, and up to {{convert|1200|t}} of [[cement]] could be kept in a barge, formerly called the ''[[Hougoumont (ship)|Hougoumont]]'' that was moored off South Queensferry.<ref name=w17>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=17}}</ref>\n\nFor a time a paddle steamer was hired for the movement of workers, but after a time it was replaced with one capable of carrying 450 men, and the barges were also used for people carrying.<ref name=w14/> Special trains were run from Edinburgh and Dunfermline, and a steamer ran to [[Leith]] in the summer.<ref name=w14/>\n\n===Circular piers===\n[[File:Forth Bridge (1890) Fig. 53, Page 30.png|thumb|right|upright|A completed caisson on Inchgarvie with the granite pier]]\nThe three towers of the cantilever are each seated on four circular piers. Since the foundations were required to be constructed at or below sea level, they were excavated with the assistance of [[caisson (engineering)|caissons]] and [[cofferdam]]s.<ref name=w17/> Caissons were used at locations that were either always under water, even at [[low tide]], or where the foundations were to be built on [[mud]] and [[clay]]. Cofferdams were used where rock was nearer to the surface, and it was possible to work in low tide.<ref name=\"magee\">{{cite conference |url=http://www.bath.ac.uk/ace/uploads/StudentProjects/Bridgeconference2007/conference/mainpage/Magee_Forth_Bridge.pdf |title=A Critical Analysis of the Forth Bridge |first=A D |last=Magee |author= |author-link= |date=27 April 2007 |conference=Bridge Engineering 2 Conference 2007 |conference-url=http://www.bath.ac.uk/ace/uploads/StudentProjects/Bridgeconference2007/index.html |volume=8  |publisher=University of Bath |access-date=30 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nSix caissons were excavated by the pneumatic process, by the French contractor L. Coisea.<ref name=w22>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=22}}</ref><ref name=w71/> This process used a positive air pressure inside a sealed caisson to allow dry working conditions at depths of up to {{convert|89|ft}}.<ref name=w71>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=71}}</ref><ref name=w27>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=27}}</ref>\n\nThese caissons were constructed and assembled in Glasgow by the Arrol Brothers, namesakes of but unconnected to W. Arrol, before being dismantled and transported to South Queensferry.<ref name=w22/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.glasgowwestaddress.co.uk/1888_Book/Arrol_Brothers.htm |title=Arrol Brothers |publisher=glasgowwestaddress.co.uk |accessdate=26 December 2014}}</ref> The caissons were then built up to a large extent before being floated to their final resting-places.<ref name=w23>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=23}}</ref> The first caisson, for the south-west pier at South Queensferry was launched on 26 May 1884, and the last caisson was launched on 29 May 1885 for the south-west pier at Inchgarvie.<ref name=w23/> When the caissons had been launched and moored, they were extended upwards with a temporary portion in order to keep water out and allow the granite pier to be built when in place.<ref name=w23/>\n\nAbove the foundations each of which is different to suit the different sites, is a tapered circular granite pier with a diameter of {{convert|55|ft}} at the bottom and a height of {{convert|36|ft}}.<ref name=w31>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=31}}</ref>\n\n====Inchgarvie====\nThe rock on which the two northern piers at Inchgarvie are located is submerged at high water, and of the other two piers, the site of eastern one is about half submerged and the western one three-quarters submerged.<ref name=w18>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=18}}</ref> This meant work initially had to be done at low tide.<ref name=w18/>\n\nThe southern piers on Inchgarvie are sited on solid rock with a slope of around 1 in 5, so the rock was prepared with concrete and sandbags to make a landing-spot for the caissons.<ref name=w26/><ref name=w20>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=20}}</ref> Excavation was carried out by [[drilling and blasting]], but no blasting was done within {{convert|1.5|ft|abbr=on}} of the caissons, and the remaining rock was quarried to within {{convert|6|in|abbr=on}}.<ref name=w18/>\n\n====North Queensferry====\nOnce the positions of the piers had been established, the first task at the Fife end was to level the site of the northernmost piers, a bedrock of whinstone rising to a level of {{convert|10|to|20|ft}} above high water, to a height of {{convert|7|ft}} above high water.<ref name=w17/> The south piers at North Queensferry are sited on rock sloping into the sea, and the site was prepared by [[diamond drilling]] holes for explosive charges and blasting the rock.<ref name=w18/>\n\n====South Queensferry====\n[[File:Forth Bridge (1890) Fig. 46, Page 26.png|thumb|left|The tilted caisson]]\n[[File:Forth Bridge (1890) Fig. 51, Page 28.png|thumb|left|The mode of sinking the South Queensferry caissons]]\n\nThe four South Queensferry caissons were all sunk by the pneumatic method, and are identical in design except for differences in height.<ref name=w22/> A '''T''' shaped jetty was built at the site of the South Queensferry piers, to allow one caisson to be attached to each corner, and when launched the caissons were attached to the jetty and permitted to rise and fall with the tide.<ref name=w23/><ref name=w21>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=21}}</ref> Excavation beneath the caissons was generally only carried out at high tide when the caisson was supported by buoyancy, and then when the tide fell the air pressure was reduced in order to allow the caisson to sink down, and digging would begin anew.<ref name=w27/>\n\nThe north-west caisson was towed into place in December 1884, but an exceptionally low tide on New Year's Day 1885 caused the caisson to sink into the mud of the river bed and adopt a slight tilt.<ref name=w26>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=26}}</ref> When the tide rose, it flooded over the lower edge, filling the caisson with water, and when the tide fell but the water did not drain from the caisson, its top-heaviness caused to tilt further.<ref name=w26/> Plates were bolted on by divers to raise the edge of the caisson above water level, and the caisson was reinforced with wooden struts as water was pumped out, but pumping took place too quickly and the water pressure tore a hole between {{convert|25|and|30|ft}} long.<ref name=w26/> It was decided to construct a \"barrel\" of large timbers inside the caisson to reinforce it, and it was ten months before the caisson could be pumped out and dug free.<ref name=w26/> The caisson was refloated on 19 October 1885, and then moved into position and sunk with suitable modifications.<ref name=w26/>\n\n===Approach viaducts===\nThe approach viaducts to the north and south had to be carried at {{convert|130|ft|6|in}} above the level of high water, and it was decided to build them at a lower level and then raise them in tandem with the construction of the masonry piers.<ref name=w32>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=32}}</ref> The two viaducts have fifteen spans between them, each one {{convert|168|ft}} long and weighing slightly over {{convert|200|t}}.<ref name=w32/> Two spans are attached together to make a continuous [[girder]], with an [[expansion joint]] between each pair of spans.<ref name=w32/> Due to the slope of the hill under the viaducts, the girders were assembled at different heights, and only joined when they had reached the same level.<ref name=w33>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=33}}</ref> Lifting was done using large [[hydraulic ram]]s, and took place in increments of around {{convert|3|ft|6|in}} every four days.<ref name=w33/>\n\n===Building the cantilevers===\nThe tubular members were constructed in the No. 2 workshop further up the hill at South Queensferry.<ref name=w38>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=38}}</ref> To bend plates into the required shape, they were first heated in a gas furnace, and then pressed into the correct curve.<ref name=w38/> The curved plates were then assembled on a [[mandrel]], and holes drilled for rivets, before they were marked individually and moved to the correct location to be added to the structure.<ref name=w38/> Lattice members and other parts were also assembled at South Queensferry, using cranes and highly efficient hydraulic rivetters.<ref name=w39>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=39}}</ref>\n<!--\n====Bedplates====\nAbove the twelve circular granite piers are the bedplates, some of which are constructed in such a way as to allow limited movement.<w39>\n\nThe bridge is bolted to the piers by holding-down bolts around {{convert|2.5|in}} thick and {{convert|25|ft}} long, with 48 bolts in each of the twelve piers.<w32> The bolts are angled slightly\n-->\n\n===Opening===\nThe bridge was completed in December 1889, and load testing of the completed bridge was carried out on 21 January 1890. Two trains, each consisting of three heavy locomotives and 50 wagons loaded with coal, totalling 1,880 tons in weight, were driven slowly from South Queensferry to the middle of the north cantilever, stopping frequently to measure the deflection of the bridge. This represented more than twice the design load of the bridge: the deflection under load was as expected.<ref name=\"Descriptionand1890\" /> A few days previously there had been a violent storm, producing the highest wind pressure recorded to date at Inchgarvie, and the deflection of the cantilevers had been less than 25&nbsp;mm (1&nbsp;in). The first complete crossing took place on 24 February, when a train consisting of two carriages carrying the chairmen of the various railway companies involved made several crossings. The bridge was opened on 4 March 1890 by the Duke of Rothesay, later King [[Edward VII of the United Kingdom|Edward VII]], who drove home the last rivet, which was gold plated and suitably inscribed.<ref name=Gazetteer/> The key for the official opening was made by Edinburgh silversmith John Finlayson Bain, commemorated in a plaque on the bridge. When it opened it had the [[list of longest cantilever bridge spans|longest single cantilever bridge span]] in the world,<ref name=\"UNESCO\">{{cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1485|title=The Forth Bridge|date=2015|publisher=UNESCO|quote=This railway bridge, crossing the Forth estuary in Scotland, had the world's longest spans (541&nbsp;m) when it opened in 1890. It remains one of the greatest cantilever trussed bridges and continues to carry passengers and freight.|last1=Centre|first1=UNESCO World Heritage|accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref> until 1919 when the [[Quebec Bridge]] in [[Canada]] was completed.<ref name=\"quebecBridge\">{{cite web|url=http://www.travelandleisure.com/slideshows/worlds-longest-bridges/14|title=Longest Cantilever Bridge Span: The Quebec Bridge, Quebec|date=2017|website=travelandleisure.com|publisher=Travel + Leisure|quote=Finally, in December 1919, the 94-foot-wide, 1,800-foot-long central span was jacked 150 feet into place, and it has remained the record-holder ever since.|accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref> It continues to be the world's second-longest single cantilever span, with a span of {{convert|521|m|order=flip}}.<ref name=\"spanLengths\">{{cite web|url=http://www.forth-bridges.co.uk/forth-bridge/facts-figures-rail.html|title=Key facts about the Forth Bridge|date=2015|website=forth-bridges.co.uk|publisher=Forth Bridges Forum|quote=The two main spans of 521m were for 28 years the longest and second longest bridge spans in the world|accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n{{main|Forth Bridge approach railways}}\nTo make the fullest use of the bridge, [[Forth Bridge approach railways|several new railway connections]] were built, bringing main line routes to the bridge. The construction of some of these lines was only completed on 2 June 1890, delaying the implementation of a full express train service over the bridge until that date. Even then, there was considerable congestion at Edinburgh Waverley station with remarshalling of the portions of the new, more intensive train service.<ref>''Aberdeen Weekly Journal'', 4 June 1890</ref>\n\n===Accidents and deaths===\nAt its peak, approximately 4,600 workers were employed in the bridge's construction. Wilhelm Westhofen recorded in 1890 that 57 lives were lost. In 2005 the Forth Bridge Memorial Committee was set up to erect a monument to those lost, and a team of local historians set out to name all those who died.<ref name=b82>{{harvnb|Wills|2009|p=82}}</ref> As of 2009, 73 deaths have been connected with the construction of the bridge and its immediate aftermath.<ref name=b86>{{harvnb|Wills|2009|p=86}}</ref> It is thought that the figure of 57 deaths excluded those who died working on the approaches to the bridge, as those parts were completed by a subcontractor, as well as those who died after the Sick and Accident Club stopped.<ref name=b86/> Of the 73 recorded deaths, 38 were as a result of falling, 9 of being crushed, 9 drowned, 8 struck by a falling object, 3 died in a fire in a [[bothy]], 1 of [[Decompression sickness|caisson disease]], and the cause of five deaths is unknown.<ref name=b90>{{harvnb|Wills|2009|p=90}}</ref>\n\nThe Sick and Accident Club was founded in 1883, and membership was compulsory for all contractors' employees.<ref name=rp136/> It would provide medical treatment to men and sometimes their families, and pay them if they were unable to work.<ref name=rp136/> The club also paid for funerals within certain limits, and would provide grants to the widows of men killed or the wives of those permanently disabled.<ref name=rp136>{{harvnb|Paxton|1990|p=136}}</ref> Eight men were saved from drowning by rowing boats positioned in the river under the working areas.<ref name=w14/>\n\n==Later history==\n\n===Race to the North===\nBefore the opening of the Forth Bridge, the railway journey from London to [[Aberdeen]] had taken about 13 hours running from {{stnlnk|Euston}} and using the [[London and North Western Railway]] and [[Caledonian Railway]] on a [[West Coast Main Line|west coast route]]. With competition opened up along the [[East Coast Main Line|east coast route]] from the [[Great Northern Railway (Great Britain)|Great Northern]], [[North Eastern Railway (UK)|North Eastern]] and [[North British Railway|North British]] railways and starting from [[London King's Cross railway station|King's Cross]], unofficial racing took place between the two consortia, reducing the journey time to about 8\u00bd hours on the overnight runs. This reached a climax in 1895 with sensational daily press reports about the \"[[Race to the North]]\". When race fever subsided the journey times became around 10\u00bd hours.<ref>{{harvnb|Nock|1958|pp=64,66}}</ref>\n\n===World wars===\n\n[[File:Are these \"just a few splashes\", Mr. Churchill?.jpg|thumb|A German photograph allegedly taken during the raid]]\nIn the [[First World War]] British sailors would time their departures or returns to the base at [[Rosyth]] by asking when they would pass under the bridge.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/stream/northseadiary00kingiala/northseadiary00kingiala_djvu.txt |title=A North Sea diary, 1914\u20131918 |author=King-Hall, Stephen |publisher=Newnes |date= |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref> <!--This practice continued at least up to the 1990s. In both wars the anchorage at Rosyth extended eastwards beyond the bridge.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}--> The first German air attack on Britain in the [[Second World War]] took place over the Forth Bridge, six weeks into the war, on 16 October 1939. Although known as the \"Forth Bridge Raid\", the bridge was not the target and not damaged. In all, 12 German [[Junkers Ju 88]] bombers led by two reconnaissance [[Heinkel He 111]]s from Westerland on the island of [[Sylt]], {{convert|460|mi|nmi km}} away, reached the Scottish coast in four waves of three.<ref>W. Simpson, ''Spitfires Over Scotland'', G C Books Ltd., 2010 {{ISBN|978-1-872350-44-8}}, p. 84</ref> The target of the attack was shipping from the [[Rosyth Dockyard|Rosyth naval base]] in the Forth, close to the bridge. The Germans were hoping to find {{HMS|Hood|51|6}}, the largest [[capital ship]] in the Royal Navy. ''[[Luftwaffe]]'' rules of engagement restricted action to targets on water and not in the dockyard. Although {{HMS|Repulse|1916|6}} was in Rosyth, the attack was concentrated on the cruisers {{HMS|Edinburgh|16|2}} and {{HMS|Southampton|83|2}}, the carrier {{HMS|Furious|47|2}} and the destroyer [[HMS Jervis|''Jervis'']].<ref>W. Simpson, ''Spitfires Over Scotland'', p. 92</ref> The destroyer ''Mohawk'' and the cruisers, ''Southampton'' and ''Edinburgh'' were damaged. Sixteen Royal Navy crew died and 44 were wounded, although this information was not made public at the time.<ref name=\"LTS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.educationscotland.gov.uk/scotlandshistory/20thand21stcenturies/worldwarii/airattack/index.asp|title=Air attack in the Firth of Forth|website=educationscotland.org.uk|publisher=[[Learning and Teaching Scotland]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150406135906/http://www.educationscotland.gov.uk/scotlandshistory/20thand21stcenturies/worldwarII/airattack/index.asp|archive-date=6 April 2015|url-status=dead|accessdate=25 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Spitfire]]s from [[No. 603 Squadron RAF|603 \"City of Edinburgh\" Squadron]] RAF intercepted the raiders and during the attack shot down the first German aircraft downed over Britain in the war.<ref name=\"LTS\" /> One bomber came down in the water off [[Port Seton]] on the East Lothian coast and another off [[Crail]] on the coast of Fife. After the War it was learned that a third bomber had come down in the Netherlands as a result of damage inflicted during the raid. Later in the month, a reconnaissance Heinkel 111 crashed near [[Humbie]] in [[East Lothian]] and photographs of this crashed plane were, and still are, used erroneously to illustrate the raid of 16 October, thus sowing confusion as to whether a third aircraft had been brought down.<ref>W. Simpson, ''Spitfires Over Scotland'', p. 108</ref> Members of the bomber crew at Port Seton were rescued and made prisoners-of-war. Two bodies were recovered from the Crail wreckage and after a full military funeral with firing party, were interred in [[Portobello, Edinburgh|Portobello]] cemetery, Edinburgh. The body of the gunner was never found.<ref>W. Simpson, ''Spitfires Over Scotland'', pp. 100, 109</ref> A wartime propaganda film, ''Squadron 992'', made by the [[GPO Film Unit]] after the raid, recreated it and conveyed the false impression that the main target was the bridge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/1364857/index.html |title=BFI Screenonline: Squadron 992 (1940) |website=Screen Online |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Ownership===\n[[File:Forth Bridge RJD 129.jpg|right|thumb|upright|A 1913 [[Railway Clearing House]] Junction Diagram showing the Forth Bridge Railway (red) and neighbouring lines of the [[North British Railway]] (blue)]]\nBefore the opening of the bridge, the [[North British Railway]] (NBR) had lines on both sides of the Firth of Forth between which trains could not pass except by running at least as far west as {{stnlnk|Alloa}} and using the lines of a rival company. The only alternative route between Edinburgh and Fife involved the ferry at Queensferry, which was purchased by the NBR in 1867. Accordingly, the NBR sponsored the Forth Bridge project which would give them a direct link independent of the [[Caledonian Railway]].<ref name=Awdry132>{{cite book |last=Awdry |first=Christopher |authorlink=Christopher Awdry |title=Encyclopaedia of British Railway Companies |year=1990 |publisher=Guild Publishing |location=London |id=CN 8983 |page=132 |ref=harv }}</ref> A conference at York in 1881 set up the Forth Bridge Railway Committee, to which the NBR contributed 35% of the cost. The remaining money came from three English railways, which ran trains from London over NBR tracks. The [[Midland Railway]], which connected to the NBR at {{stnlnk|Carlisle}} and which owned the route to [[St Pancras railway station|London (St Pancras)]], contributed 30% and the remainder came equally from the [[North Eastern Railway (UK)|North Eastern Railway]] and the [[Great Northern Railway (Great Britain)|Great Northern Railway]], which between them owned the route between {{stnlnk|Berwick-upon-Tweed}} and [[London King's Cross railway station|London (King's Cross)]], via {{stnlnk|Doncaster}}. This body undertook to construct and maintain the bridge.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Thomas |first1=John |last2=Turnock |first2=David |editor1-last=Thomas |editor1-first=David St John |editor1-link=David St John Thomas |editor2-last=Patmore |editor2-first=J. Allan |title=A Regional History of the Railways of Great Britain: Volume XV&nbsp;\u2014 North of Scotland |year=1989 |publisher=[[David St John Thomas]] |location=Newton Abbot |isbn=0-946537-03-8 |page=71 |ref=harv }}</ref>\n\nIn 1882 the NBR were given powers to purchase the bridge, which it never exercised.<ref name=Awdry132 /> At the time of the [[1923 Grouping]], the bridge was still jointly owned by the same four railways,<ref>{{cite book |last=Conolly |first=W. Philip |title=British Railways Pre-Grouping Atlas and Gazetteer |edition=5th |date=January 1976 |publisher=[[Ian Allan Publishing|Ian Allan]] |location=Shepperton |isbn=0-7110-0320-3 |id=EX/0176 |page=49 |ref=harv }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Whitehouse |first1=Patrick |last2=Thomas |first2=David St John |authorlink2=David St John Thomas |title=LNER 150: The London and North Eastern Railway&nbsp;\u2013 A Century and a Half of Progress |year=1989 |publisher=[[David & Charles]] |location=Newton Abbot |isbn=0-7153-9332-4 |id=01LN01 |page=21 |ref=harv }}</ref> and so it became jointly owned by these companies' successors, the [[London Midland and Scottish Railway]] (30%) and the [[London and North Eastern Railway]] (70%).<ref>{{cite book |last=Hughes |first=Geoffrey |title=LNER |year=1987 |origyear=1986 |publisher=Guild Publishing/Book Club Associates |location=London |id=CN 1455 |pages=33\u201334 |ref=harv }}</ref> The Forth Bridge Railway Company was named in the [[Transport Act 1947]] as one of the bodies to be nationalised and so became part of [[British Railways]] on 1 January 1948.<ref>{{cite book |title=Transport Act 1947 (10 & 11 Geo. 6 ch. 49) |chapter-url=http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/documents/HMG_Act1947.pdf |date=6 August 1947 |author=His Majesty's Government |publisher=His Majesty's Stationery Office |location=London |chapter=Third Schedule |page=145 |accessdate=1 July 2011 |ref=ref1011Geo6c49 }}</ref> Under the Act, Forth Bridge shareholders would receive \u00a3109 of British Transport stock for each \u00a3100 of Forth Bridge Debenture stock; and \u00a3104-17-6d (\u00a3104.87\u00bd) of British Transport stock for each \u00a3100 of Forth Bridge Ordinary stock.<ref>[[#ref1011Geo6c49|Transport Act 1947]], fourth schedule, p. 148</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Bonavia |first=Michael R. |title=British Rail: The First 25 Years |year=1981 |publisher=[[David & Charles]] |location=Newton Abbot |isbn=0-7153-8002-8 |page=10 |ref=harv }}</ref>\n\nAs of April 2017, the bridge and its associated railway infrastructure are owned by [[Network Rail|Network Rail Infrastructure Limited]].<ref name=\"networkRail\">{{cite web|url=https://www.networkrail.co.uk/running-the-railway/our-routes/scotland/|title=Scotland \u2013 Network Rail|date=2017|website=www.networkrail.co.uk|publisher=Network Rail|quote=Network Rail Scotland looks after Scotland's railway infrastructure, including the world-famous Forth Bridge that connects passengers in Fife, north of Edinburgh, with Edinburgh and the Borders.|accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Operation==\n[[File:The Forth Bridge seen from Dalmeny Station.JPG|thumb|left|upright|The approach to the bridge from [[Dalmeny Station]]]]\n[[File:InsideTheForthRailBridge 19990822P0001.jpg|thumb|right|Inside the Forth Bridge as seen from a [[ScotRail (National Express)|ScotRail]] [[British Rail Class 158|class 158]]]]\n\n===Traffic===\nThe bridge has a speed limit of {{convert|50|mph}} for high-speed trains and [[diesel multiple unit]]s, {{convert|40|mph}} for ordinary passenger trains and {{convert|30|mph}} for freight trains.<ref name=bm11>{{harvnb|Harding|Gerard|Ryall|2006|p=11}}</ref><ref name=rp91>{{harvnb|Paxton|1990|p=91}}</ref> The [[route availability]] code is RA8, but freight trains above a certain size must not pass each other on the bridge.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.transportscotland.gov.uk/report/j8512a-05.htm |title=Forth Bridge and Associated Rail Network |publisher=Transport Scotland |accessdate=20 July 2014}}</ref> Up to 190\u2013200&nbsp;trains per day crossed the bridge in 2006.<ref>\"[http://www.forthbridges.org.uk/railbridgemain.htm The Forth Bridge] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080222183156/http://www.forthbridges.org.uk/railbridgemain.htm |date=22 February 2008 }}\". Forth Bridges Visitors Centre Trust. Retrieved 21 April 2006.</ref>\n\n===Maintenance===\n<!--The Forth Bridge needs constant maintenance and the ancillary works for the bridge include not only a maintenance workshop and yard but a railway \"colony\" of some fifty houses at [[Dalmeny railway station|Dalmeny Station]]. The track on the bridge is of \"[[waybeam]]\" construction: 12&nbsp;inch square baulks of timber 6 metres long are bolted into steel troughs in the bridge deck and the rails are fixed on top of these sleepers. Prior to 1992 the rails on the bridge were of a unique \"Forth Bridge\" section.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}-->\n\n{{Anchor|painting}}\"Painting the Forth Bridge\" is a colloquial expression for a never-ending task, coined on the erroneous belief that at one time in the history of the bridge repainting was required and commenced immediately upon completion of the previous repaint.<ref name=\"dict\">{{cite web |title=be like painting the Forth Bridge |url=http://idioms.thefreedictionary.com/be+like+painting+the+Forth+Bridge |publisher=theFreeDictionary.com |accessdate=23 November 2010}}</ref> Such a practice never existed, as weathered areas were given more attention, but there was a permanent maintenance crew.<ref name=rai15/> In 2011, the bridge was covered in a new coating designed to last for 25 years, bringing an end to having painters as a regular part of the maintenance crew. Colin Hardie, of [[Balfour Beatty Construction]], was reported as saying,<ref name=\"paintingEnd\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-edinburgh-east-fife-14789036|title=Forth Bridge painting 'is coming to an end'|date=5 September 2011 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |quote=The Forth Rail Bridge will be free of scaffolding and painters from 9 December|accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/jan/26/world/la-fg-scotland-bridge-20120127|title=Scotland can stop painting its Forth Rail Bridge|last=Chu|first=Henry|date=26 January 2012|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=13 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=For the first time in the bridge's history there will be no painters required on the bridge. Job done&nbsp;... |sign=Colin Hardie|source=[[BBC News]] article, 5 September 2011}}\n\n===Restoration===\nFloodlighting was installed in 1991, and the track was renewed between 1992 and 1995.<ref name=rai15>{{harvnb|Glen|Bowman|Andrew|2012|p=15}}</ref> The bridge was costing [[British Rail]] \u00a31&nbsp;million a year to maintain, and they announced that the schedule of painting would be interrupted to save money, and the following year, upon privatisation, [[Railtrack]] took over.<ref name=rai15/> A \u00a340&nbsp;million package of works commenced in 1998, and in 2002 the responsibility of the bridge was passed to [[Network Rail]].<ref name=rai15/>\n\nWork started in 2002 to repaint the bridge fully for the first time in its history, in a \u00a3130&nbsp;million contract awarded to [[Balfour Beatty]].<ref name=rai16>{{harvnb|Glen|Bowman|Andrew|2012|p=16.}}</ref><ref name=mos>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/men-of-steel-the-men-who-maintain-the-forth-rail-bridge-1-1976605 |title=Men of Steel: The men who maintain the Forth Rail Bridge |work=The Scotsman |date=22 November 2011}}</ref> Up to {{convert|4000|t}} of scaffolding was on the bridge at any time, and computer modelling was used to analyse the additional wind load on the structure.<ref name=rai18>{{harvnb|Glen|Bowman|Andrew|2012|p=18}}</ref> The bridge was encapsulated in a climate controlled membrane to give the proper conditions for the application of the paint.<ref name=rai19>{{harvnb|Glen|Bowman|Andrew|2012|p=19}}</ref> All previous layers of paint were removed using [[copper slag]] fired at up to {{convert|200|mph}}, exposing the steel and allowing repairs to be made.<ref name=rai19/><ref name=\"NCE\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nce.co.uk/painting-of-forth-bridge-to-end/754462.article |title=Painting of Forth bridge to end |last=McKenna |first=John |date=19 February 2008 |work=New Civil Engineer |accessdate=16 January 2010}}</ref> The paint, developed specifically for the bridge by [[Leigh Paints]], consisted of a system of three coats derived from that used in the North Sea oil industry;<ref name=rai19/> a total of {{convert|240000|l}} was applied to {{convert|255000|m2}} of the structure, and it is not expected to need repainting for at least 20 years.<ref name=mos/><ref name=rai19/> The top coat can be reapplied indefinitely, minimising future maintenance work.<ref name=rai20>{{harvnb|Glen|Bowman|Andrew|2012|p=20}}</ref>\n\n{{wide image|Forth rail bridge head-on-panorama josh-von-staudach.jpg|1320px|align-cap=center|Panoramic view of the Forth Bridge undergoing maintenance work in 2007}}\n\nIn a report produced by JE Jacobs, [[Grant Thornton]] and [[Faber Maunsell]] in 2007 which reviewed the alternative options for a second road crossing, it was stated that \"Network Rail has estimated the life of the bridge to be in excess of 100 years. However, this is dependant {{sic}} upon NR's inspection and refurbishment works programme for the bridge being carried out year on year\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.transport.gov.scot/report/j8512a-05.htm#43 |title=Forth Replacement Crossing \u2013 Report 1 \u2013 Assessment of Transport Network |publisher=Transport Scotland |archive-url=https://www.webarchive.org.uk/wayback/archive/20170106202624/http://www.transport.gov.scot/report/j8512a-05.htm#43 |archive-date=6 January 2017 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== In culture ==\n[[File:ForthRivet.JPG|thumb|Original [[rivet]] from the Forth Bridge]]\n\n===In the media===\nThe Forth Bridge has been featured in [[television program]]mes and films, including ''[[Carry On Regardless]]'', [[Alfred Hitchcock]]'s 1935 film ''[[The 39 Steps (1935 film)|The 39 Steps]]'', and its [[The 39 Steps (1959 film)|1959 remake]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lner.info/article/filmtv/filmtv.shtml|title=The LNER in Books, Film, and TV|accessdate=18 January 2014}}</ref> [[A.G. Barr]] used the bridge in posters advertising its soft drink [[Irn-Bru]], with the slogan: \"Made in Scotland, from [[girder]]s\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edinburgh-inspiringcapital.com/about/blog/forth_bridge_repaint.aspx|title=A Glow in the Dark Forth Bridge? Easy For Boats to Spot at Least!|accessdate=18 January 2014|archive-url=https://archive.is/20140118134624/http://www.edinburgh-inspiringcapital.com/about/blog/forth_bridge_repaint.aspx|archive-date=18 January 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2005, the [[BBC]] lit the Bridge in red for [[Comic Relief]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dunfermlineonline.net/news/index.php?ID=149&CATEGORY2=|title=Dunfermline.info The Historic City|accessdate=18 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824001731/http://dunfermlineonline.net/news/index.php?ID=149&CATEGORY2=|archive-date=24 August 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Also in 2005, [[Channel 4]] documentary ''[[Jump Britain]]'' showed [[S\u00e9bastien Foucan]], a French [[Free running|freerunner]], crawling along one of the highest points of the bridge without a harness.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bufvc.ac.uk/dvdfind/index.php/title/av38090|title=Jump Britain \u00b7 British Universities Film & Video Council|accessdate=18 January 2014}}</ref> The first episode of the UK television series ''Britain's Greatest Bridges'' featured the Forth Bridge and was aired on [[Spike (UK)|Spike UK]] on 12 January 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.channel5.com/show/britains-greatest-bridges/|title=Britain's Greatest Bridges|work=Channel 5|access-date=26 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== In general culture ===\nThe location of the Forth Bridge has seen it featured in other cultural forms. In the build up to the [[Millennium celebrations]] a countdown clock sponsored by the [[Royal Bank of Scotland]] was attached to the top of the Bridge in 1998.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/transport/forth-road-bridge-50th-year-ad-banner-plan-slammed-1-3054573|title=Forth Road Bridge 50th year ad banner plan slammed \u2013 The Scotsman|work=[[The Scotsman]]|accessdate=18 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.forth-bridges.co.uk/forth-bridge/history/growth-milestones.html|title=Growth and milestones|website=forth-bridges.co.uk|publisher=Forth Bridges Forum|access-date=29 April 2017}}</ref> [[Iain Banks]] wrote the novel ''[[The Bridge (novel)|The Bridge]]'', which is mainly set on a fictionalised version of the bridge, which links \"The City\" (Edinburgh) and \"The Kingdom\" ([[Fife]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arts.gla.ac.uk/scotlit/asls/Laverock-Iain_Banks.html|title=The Worlds of Iain Banks|last=MacGillivray|first=Alan|date=30 September 2013|website=arts.gla.ac.uk|publisher=The Association for Scottish Literary Studies|accessdate=18 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503134235/http://www.arts.gla.ac.uk/ScotLit/ASLS/Laverock-Iain_Banks.html|archive-date=3 May 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In [[Alan Turing]]'s most famous paper about [[artificial intelligence]], one of the challenges put to the subject of an imagined [[Turing test]] is \"Please write me a sonnet on the subject of the Forth Bridge.\" The test subject in Turing's paper answers, \"Count me out on this one. I never could write poetry.\"<ref>{{Turing 1950}}</ref> The bridge is included in the video game ''[[Grand Theft Auto: San Andreas]]'' by Edinburgh-based developer [[Rockstar North]]. Renamed the Kincaid Bridge, it serves as the main railway bridge of the fictional city of [[San Fierro]], and appears alongside a virtual Forth Road Bridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/gaming/grand-theft-auto-tour-of-scotland-as-councillors-of-hawick-disgusted-by-use-of-name-for-gta-vs-drug-district-8830390.html|title=Grand Theft Auto tour of Scotland as councillors of Hawick 'disgusted' by use of name for GTA V's drug district|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=18 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bison Skeleton.svg|thumb|[[D'Arcy Thompson]] used a figure of a [[bison]] skeleton when comparing it to the structural form of the Forth Bridge.<ref name=\"D'ArcyThompson\"/>]]\n\nIn his 1917 book ''[[On Growth and Form]]'', the mathematical biologist [[D'Arcy Thompson]] compares the structural form of the Forth Bridge with the cantilevered [[skeleton]] of an [[ox]], the piers corresponding to legs, the cantilevers to the [[vertebral column]]:<ref name=\"D'ArcyThompson\">{{cite book |last1=Thompson |first1=D'Arcy |authorlink1=D'Arcy Wentworth Thompson |editor1-last=Bonner |editor1-first=John Tyler |editor1-link=John Tyler Bonner |title=On Growth and Form |date=1961 |origyear=1917 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=0-521-09390-2 |pages=243\u2013246 |edition=Abridged}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|In a typical cantilever bridge, such as the Forth Bridge, a certain simplification is introduced. For each pier carries, in this case, its own double-armed cantilever, linked by a short connecting girder to the next, but so jointed to it that no weight is transmitted from one cantilever to another. The bridge in short is ''cut'' into separate sections, practically independent of one another&nbsp;... In the horse or the ox, it is obvious that the two piers of the bridge, that is to say the fore-legs and the hind-legs, do not bear (as they do in the Forth Bridge) separate and independent loads, but the whole system forms a continuous structure.<ref name=\"D'ArcyThompson\"/>}}\n\n===As heritage===\nNetwork Rail plans to add a visitor centre to the bridge, which would include a viewing platform on top of the North Queensferry side, or a bridge climbing experience to the South Queensferry side.<ref name=fs>{{cite web |title=The Forth Bridge Experience: An executive summary of its feasibility|publisher=Network Rail Infrastructure Limited|website=forthbridgeexperience.com|date=23 August 2013 |url=http://www.forthbridgeexperience.com/media/498/Network-Rail-Forth-Bridge-Feasibility-Study-LR.pdf |accessdate=20 July 2014}}</ref> In December 2014 it was announced Arup had been awarded the design contract for the project.<ref>{{cite web |title=Design For \u00a315m Forth Bridge Visitor Won by Arup |url=http://www.obas.com/blog/design-for-15m-forth-bridge-visitor-centre-won-by-arup/ | publisher=obas.com |date=15 December 2012}}</ref>\nUNESCO inscribed the bridge as a [[UNESCO World Heritage Site|World Heritage Site]] on 5 July 2015, recognising it as \"an extraordinary and impressive milestone in bridge design and construction during the period when railways came to dominate long-distance land travel\". It is the sixth World Heritage Site to be inscribed in Scotland.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-edinburgh-east-fife-33397980 |title=Forth Bridge given world heritage status |publisher=BBC News |date=5 July 2015 |accessdate=5 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"UNESCO\" /> In 2016, a [[VisitScotland]] survey voted the Forth Bridge \"Scotland's greatest man-made wonder\", beating off competition from [[Stirling Castle]], the [[Caledonian Canal]], the [[Scott Monument]], [[Bell Rock Lighthouse]], and [[Melrose Abbey]].<ref name=\"bridgeIconic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/720896/Forth-railway-bridge-voted-scotlands-greatest-man-made-wonder|title=The Forth Railway Bridge is voted Scotland's 'greatest man-made wonder'|date=14 October 2016|website=Express.co.uk|publisher=Express Newspapers|last1=Ward|first1=Paul|accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Forth Bridge has appeared in representation on a 2004 [[One pound (British coin)|one pound coin]], issued by the [[Royal Mint]].<ref name=\"royalmint\">{{cite web|url=http://www.royalmint.com/Corporate/facts/coins/OnePoundCoin.aspx|title=The United Kingdom \u00a31 Coin|publisher=The Royal Mint|accessdate=21 June 2009|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/677vdSI6z?url=http://www.royalmint.com/discover/uk-coins/coin-design-and-specifications/one-pound-coin|archive-date=23 April 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Bridge has also featured on various [[banknotes of the pound sterling|banknotes]] including the 2007 series issued by the [[Bank of Scotland]], which depicts different bridges in Scotland as examples of Scottish engineering, and the \u00a320 note features the Forth Bridge.<ref name=\"scotbanks\">{{cite web |url=http://www.scotbanks.org.uk/banknote_design_bank_of_scotland_bridges.php |title=Banknote Design Features : Bank of Scotland Bridges Series |publisher=The Committee of Scottish Clearing Bankers |accessdate=29 October 2008}}</ref> In 2014 [[Clydesdale Bank]] announced the introduction of Britain's second [[polymer banknote]], a \u00a35 note featuring [[Sir William Arrol]] and the Forth Bridge (the first polymer banknote was [[Banknotes of Northern Ireland#Danske Bank/Northern Bank notes|issued by Northern Bank in 2000]]). It was introduced in 2015 to commemorate the 125th anniversary of the opening of the bridge, and its nomination to become a UNESCO World Heritage Site.<ref name=\"herscot\">{{cite news |title=UK's first plastic banknote introduced to commemorate Forth Bridge's UNESCO nomination |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/home-news/uks-first-polymer-note-introduced-to-commemorate-forth-bridges-unesco-nomination.1400751223 |newspaper=Herald Scotland |date=22 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Scotland}}\n* [[Banknotes of Scotland]] (featured on design)\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Blanc|first1=Alan|last2=McEvoy|first2=Michael|last3=Plank|first3=Roger|title=Architecture and Construction in Steel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Knmi0lzWd-0C|year=2003|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-135-82839-4}}\n<!--* {{cite book|last=Cole|first=Beverly|title=Trains|publisher=H.F.Ullmann|year=2011|isbn=978-3-8480-0516-1 |location=Potsdam, Germany |ref=harv }} unused-->\n* {{cite book |last1=Glen |first1=Ann |last2=Bowman |first2=Craig |last3=Andrew |first3=John |title=Forth Bridge: Restoring an Icon |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5qAoLgEACAAJ |year=2012 |publisher=Lily Publications |isbn=978-1-907945-19-9 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zlGErQK_qPoC |title=Bridge Management: Inspection, maintenance, assessment and repair |last1=Harding |first1=J. E. |last2=Gerard |first2=Parke |last3=Ryall |first3=M |year=2006 |publisher=CRC Press |isbn=978-0-203-97354-7 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=McKean |first=Charles |authorlink=Charles McKean |title=Battle for the North |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kUYfAQAAIAAJ |year=2006 |publisher=Granta Books |isbn=978-1-86207-852-9 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Nock |first=Oswald S. |title=The Railway Race to the North |year=1958 |publisher=Ian Allan |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=81rbAAAAMAAJ |title=100 Years of the Forth Bridge |first=Roland |last=Paxton |publisher=Thomas Telford |isbn=978-0-7277-1600-2 |year=1990 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2CD6-fz-raMC |title=Design Risk Management |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |year=2010 |isbn=978-1-4443-1890-6 |first=Stuart |last=Summerhayes |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title=The Forth Bridge |first=Wilhem |last=Westhofen |url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/The_Forth_Bridge |publisher=Offices of \"Engineering\" |year=1890 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Wills |first=Elspeth M. |title=The Briggers: The Story of the Men Who Built the Forth Bridge |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JY79PQAACAAJ |year=2009 |publisher=Birlinn |isbn=978-1-84158-761-5 |ref=harv}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite magazine |first=Peter |last=Kelly |title=A mountain of scrap for Serpell? |magazine=[[RAIL (magazine)|Rail Enthusiast]] |publisher=EMAP National Publications |date=April 1983 |pp=34\u201339 |oclc=49957965}}\n* {{cite book |last=MacKay |first=Sheila |title=The Forth Bridge: A Picture History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sdsVkgAACAAJ |year=2011 |publisher=Birlinn |isbn=978-1-84158-935-0}}\n* {{cite book | chapterurl=http://www.railwaywondersoftheworld.com/forth-bridge.html | chapter=The Forth Bridge| title=Railway Wonders of the World | year=1935 | pages=432\u2013441 | url=http://www.railwaywondersoftheworld.com/ |editor=Winchester, Clarence}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://digital.nls.uk/74570306 40 black-and-white photographs] of the construction of the Forth Bridge taken in 1886\u20131887 by Philip Phillips at [[National Library of Scotland]]\n* [http://www.forth-bridges.co.uk/forth-bridge.html Forth Bridge] at Forth Bridges Visitor Centre Trust\n* {{Structurae|id=20000024|title=Forth Rail Bridge}}\n* [http://www.scottishpoetrylibrary.org.uk/poetry/poems/construction-forth-railway-bridge-1882-1890 Scottish Poetry Library: Poetry Map of Scotland] (Firth of Forth): ''The Construction of the Forth Bridge, 1882\u20131890'', by Colin Donati\n\n{{Transport in Edinburgh}}\n{{World Heritage Sites in the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1890]]\n[[Category:Cantilever bridges]]\n[[Category:Category A listed buildings in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Category A listed buildings in Fife]]\n[[Category:Transport in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Railway bridges in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Railway bridges in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Listed bridges in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Historic Civil Engineering Landmarks]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Sites in Scotland]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Sites in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Fife]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Firth of Forth]]\n[[Category:South Queensferry]]\n[[Category:1890 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Cantilever railway bridge over the Firth of Forth in the east of Scotland}}\n{{distinguish|Fourth Bridge}}\n{{about|the railway bridge|the road bridge|Forth Road Bridge|other uses}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox bridge\n|bridge_name= Forth Bridge\n|image={{Css Image Crop|Image = Scotland-2016-Aerial-Edinburgh-Forth Bridge.jpg|bSize = 380|cWidth = 300|cHeight = 120|oTop = 30|oLeft = 38|Location = center}}\n|owner = [[Network Rail]]\n|carries =Rail traffic\n|crosses =[[Firth of Forth]]\n|locale =[[Edinburgh]], [[Inchgarvie]] and [[Fife]], Scotland\n|maint =[[Balfour Beatty]] under contract to Network Rail\n|designer = Sir [[Sir John Fowler, 1st Baronet|John Fowler]] and<br>Sir [[Benjamin Baker (engineer)|Benjamin Baker]]\n|design =[[Cantilever bridge]]\n|mainspan =Two of {{convert|1700|ft}}<ref name=nr>{{cite web|title=Forth Bridge|url=http://www.networkrail.co.uk/VirtualArchive/forth-bridge/|website=NetworkRail|publisher=Network Rail|accessdate=3 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150704235928/http://www.networkrail.co.uk/VirtualArchive/forth-bridge/|archive-date=4 July 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|length = {{convert|8094|ft}}<ref name=nr/>\n|width ={{convert|120|ft|abbr=on}} at piers<ref name=nr/><br />{{convert|32|ft|abbr=on}} at centre<ref name=nr/>\n|height ={{convert|361|ft|abbr=on}} above high water<ref name=nr/>\n|below ={{convert|150|ft|abbr=on}} to high water<ref name=nr/>\n|traffic =190\u2013200 trains per day\n|begin =1882\n|complete =December 1889\n|open=4 March 1890\n|coordinates = {{coord|56.0004|-3.3886|region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n|map_type = UK Scotland\n|extra =  {{Designation list\n  | embed                   = yes\n  | designation1            = World Heritage Site\n  | designation1_offname    = The Forth Bridge\n  | designation1_type       = cultural\n  | designation1_criteria   = i, iv\n  | designation1_date       = 2015\n  | delisted1_date          =\n  | designation1_number     = [https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1485 1485]\n  | designation2            = Category A Listed Building\n  | designation2_offname    = Forth Bridge\n  | designation2_type       =\n  | designation2_criteria   =\n  | designation2_date       = 18 June 1973\n  | delisted2_date          =\n  | designation2_number     = [http://portal.historicenvironment.scot/designation/LB40370 LB40370]\n}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Forth Bridge'''<ref name=\"bridgeName\">{{cite web|title=The Forth Bridge|url=http://www.forth-bridges.co.uk/forth-bridge.html|website=forth-bridges.co.uk|publisher=Forth Bridges Forum|accessdate=26 March 2017|date=2015|quote=Opened in 1890, The Forth Bridge is recognised the world over as the most famous of cantilever designs.}}</ref> is a [[cantilever bridge|cantilever]] [[rail transport|railway]] bridge across the [[Firth of Forth]] in the east of [[Scotland]], {{convert|9|mi|abbr=off}} west of central [[Edinburgh]]. It is considered as a symbol of Scotland (having been voted Scotland's greatest man-made wonder in 2016), and is a [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]]. It was designed by the English engineers [[Sir John Fowler, 1st Baronet|Sir John Fowler]] and [[Benjamin Baker (engineer)|Sir Benjamin Baker]]. It is sometimes referred to as the '''Forth Rail Bridge''' (to distinguish it from the adjacent [[Forth Road Bridge]]), although this has never been its official name.\n\nConstruction of the bridge began in 1882 and it was opened on 4 March 1890 by the [[Duke of Rothesay]], the future [[Edward VII]]. The bridge carries the [[Edinburgh\u2013Aberdeen line]] across the Forth between the villages of [[South Queensferry]] and [[North Queensferry]] and has a total length of {{convert|2467|m|order=flip}}. When it opened it had the [[list of longest cantilever bridge spans|longest single cantilever bridge span]] in the world, until 1919 when the [[Quebec Bridge]] in [[Canada]] was completed. It continues to be the world's second-longest single cantilever span, with a span of {{convert|521|m|order=flip}}.\n\nThe bridge and its associated railway infrastructure are owned by [[Network Rail]].\n\n==Background==\n[[File:The guts of the Forth Bridge - geograph.org.uk - 1318782.jpg|thumb|View of the structure]]\n\n===Earlier proposals===\n{{Main|History of the Forth Crossing}}\n\nBefore the construction of the bridge, [[Ferry|ferries]] were used to cross the Firth.<ref name=m58>{{harvnb|McKean|2006|p=58}}</ref> In 1806, a pair of tunnels, one for each direction, was proposed, and in 1818 [[James Anderson (civil engineer)|James Anderson]] produced a design for a three-span suspension bridge close to the site of the present one.<ref name=2006p2>{{harvnb|Harding|Gerard|Ryall|2006|p=2}}</ref> Calling for approximately {{convert|2500|t}} of iron, Wilhelm Westhofen said of it \"and this quantity [of iron] distributed over the length would have given it a very light and slender appearance, so light indeed that on a dull day it would hardly have been visible, and after a heavy gale probably no longer to be seen on a clear day either\".<ref name=w1>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=1}}</ref>\n\nFor the railway age, [[Thomas Bouch]] designed for the [[Edinburgh and Northern Railway]] a [[roll-on/roll-off]] [[Train ferry|ferry]] between [[Granton, Edinburgh|Granton]] and [[Burntisland]] that opened in 1850, which proved so successful that another was ordered for the Tay.<ref name=\"m58-59\">{{harvnb|McKean|2006|pp=58\u201359}}</ref> In late 1863, a joint project between the [[North British Railway]] and [[Edinburgh and Glasgow Railway]], which would merge in 1865, appointed Stephenson and Toner to design a bridge for the Forth, but the commission was given to Bouch around six months later.<ref name=m62>{{harvnb|McKean|2006|p=62}}</ref>\n\nIt had proven difficult to engineer a [[suspension bridge]] that was able to carry railway traffic, and Thomas Bouch, engineer to the [[North British Railway]] (NBR) and [[Edinburgh and Glasgow Railway]], was in 1863\u20131864 working on a [[Single-track railway|single-track]] [[girder bridge]] crossing the Forth near [[Charlestown, Fife|Charlestown]], where the river is around {{convert|2|mi|km}} wide, but mostly relatively shallow.<ref name=m62/><ref name=\"rp24-27\">{{harvnb|Paxton|1990|pp=24\u201327}}</ref> The promoters, however, were concerned about the ability to set foundations in the silty river bottom, as borings had gone as deep as {{convert|231|ft}} into the mud without finding any rock, but Bouch conducted experiments to demonstrate that it was possible for the silt to support considerable weight.<ref name=rp29>{{harvnb|Paxton|1990|p=29}}</ref> Experiments in late 1864 with weighted caissons achieved a pressure of {{convert|5|t/sqft|LT/sqft ST/sqft|abbr=on}} on the silt, encouraging Bouch to continue with the design.<ref name=rp29/> In August 1865, Richard Hodgson, chairman of the NBR, proposed that the company invest {{GBP|18000}} to try a different kind of foundation, as the weighted caissons had not been successful.<ref name=\"m73-74\">{{harvnb|McKean|2006|pp=73\u201374}}</ref> Bouch proposed using a large pine platform underneath the piers, {{convert|80|x|60|x|7|ft|m}} (the original design called for a {{convert|114|x|80|x|9|ft|m}} platform of green beech) weighed down with {{convert|10000|t}} of [[pig iron]] which would sink the wooden platform to the level of the silt.<ref name=rp29/> The platform was launched on 14 June 1866 after some difficulty in getting it to move down the greased planks it rested on, and then moored in the harbour for six weeks pending completion.<ref name=rp29/><ref name=m77>{{harvnb|McKean|2006|p=77}}</ref> The bridge project was aborted just before the platform was sunk as the NBR expected to lose \"through traffic\" following the amalgamation of the [[Caledonian Railway]] and the [[Scottish North Eastern Railway]].<ref name=rp29/> In September 1866, a committee of shareholders investigating rumours of financial difficulties found that accounts had been falsified, and the chairman and the entire board had resigned by November.<ref name=m78>{{harvnb|McKean|2006|p=78}}</ref> By mid-1867 the NBR was nearly bankrupt, and all work on the Forth and Tay bridges was stopped.<ref name=m81>{{harvnb|McKean|2006|p=81}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Forth Bridge (1890) Figs. 2 and 3, Page 4.png|thumb|upright=1.5<!--image represents multiple low aspect diagrams-->|Bouch's proposed bridge (top) along with other proposals on the same principle]]\n\nThe North British Railway took over the ferry at Queensferry in 1867, and completed a rail link from [[Ratho]] in 1868, establishing a contiguous link with Fife.<ref name=rp32>{{harvnb|Paxton|1990|p=32}}</ref> Interest in bridging the Forth increased again, and Bouch proposed a stiffened steel suspension bridge on roughly the line of the present rail bridge in 1871, and after careful verification, work started in 1878 on a pier at [[Inchgarvie]].<ref name=rp32/>\n\nAfter the [[Tay Bridge disaster|Tay Bridge collapsed]] in 1879, confidence in Bouch dried up and the work stopped.<ref name=rp32/> The public inquiry into the disaster, chaired by [[Henry Cadogan Rothery]], found the Tay Bridge to be \"badly designed, badly constructed and badly maintained\", with Bouch being \"mainly to blame\" for the defects in construction and maintenance and \"entirely responsible\" for the defects in design.<ref>{{harvnb|Summerhayes|2010|p=7}}</ref>\n\nAfter the disaster, which occurred in high winds for which Bouch had not properly accounted, the [[Board of Trade]] imposed a lateral wind allowance of {{convert|56|lb/sqft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"rp41-44\">{{harvnb|Paxton|1990|p=41}}</ref> Bouch's 1871 design had taken a much lower figure of {{convert|10|lb/sqft|abbr=on}} on the advice of the [[Astronomer Royal]], although contemporary analysis showed it would probably have stood, but the engineers making the analysis stated that \"we do not commit ourselves to an opinion that it is the best possible\" [design].<ref name=\"rp44-45\">{{harvnb|Paxton|1990|pp=44\u201345}}</ref> Bouch's design was formally abandoned on 13 January 1881, and [[Sir John Fowler, 1st Baronet|Sir John Fowler]], [[William Henry Barlow|W. H. Barlow]] and T. E. Harrison, consulting engineers to the project, were invited to give proposals for a bridge.<ref name=\"rp47-49\">{{harvnb|Paxton|1990|pp=47\u201349}}</ref><ref name=\"bridgeDesigners\">{{cite web|url=http://www.forth-bridges.co.uk/forth-bridge/history.html|title=History of the Forth Bridge|date=2015|website=forth-bridges.co.uk|publisher=Forth Bridges Forum|quote=the momentum for a crossing had grown and a new design, by John Fowler and Benjamin Baker, was submitted to the Forth Bridge Company in May 1881, with construction authorised by Parliament in July 1882.|accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Design==\n[[File:Forth Bridge (1890) Fig. 4, Page 5.png|thumb|upright=1.5<!--width for low aspect image-->|The original (above) and final (below) designs of the Forth Bridge]]\n\n===Dimensions===\nThe bridge spans the Forth between the villages of [[South Queensferry]] and [[North Queensferry]] and has a total length of {{convert|2467|m|order=flip}}<ref name=\"nr\" /> with the double track elevated {{convert|150|ft|m|2}} above the water level at high tide. It consists of two main spans of {{convert|1700|ft|m|2|}}, two side spans of {{convert|207.3|m|order=flip|abbr=on}}, and 15 approach spans of {{convert|51.2|m|ft|order=flip|abbr=on}}.<ref name=nr/><ref name=\"facts\">\"[http://www.forthbridges.org.uk/railbridgefacts.htm Forth Rail Bridge Facts & Figures] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121223015457/http://www.forthbridges.org.uk/railbridgefacts.htm |date=23 December 2012 }}\". Forth Bridges Visitors Centre Trust. Retrieved 21 April 2006.</ref> Each main span consists of two {{convert|207.3|m|ft|order=flip|abbr=on}} [[cantilever]] arms supporting a central {{convert|106.7|m|ft|order=flip}} span truss. The weight of the bridge superstructure was {{convert|50513|LT}}, including the 6.5&nbsp;million [[rivet]]s used.<ref name=\"facts\"/> The bridge also used {{convert|18122|m3|order=flip}} of [[granite]].<ref name=Gazetteer>{{cite web |url=http://www.scottish-places.info/features/featurefirst1053.html |title=Overview of Forth Bridge |work=The Gazetteer for Scotland |accessdate=21 April 2006}}</ref>\n\nThe three great four-tower cantilever structures are {{convert|361|ft|m|2}} tall,<ref name=nr/> each tower resting on a separate [[granite]] pier. These were constructed using {{convert|70|ft|m|abbr=on}} diameter [[caisson (engineering)|caissons]]; those for the north cantilever and two on the small uninhabited island of [[Inchgarvie]] acted as [[cofferdam]]s, while the remaining two on Inchgarvie and those for the south cantilever, where the river bed was {{convert|91|ft|m|abbr=on}} below high-water level, used compressed air to keep water out of the working chamber at the base.<ref name=\"Descriptionand1890\">{{cite news |title=Description and History of the Bridge |issue=32950 |page=13 |newspaper=The Times|location=London |date=4 March 1890 }}</ref>\n\n{{comparison_of_notable_bridges.svg}}\n\n===Engineering principles===\n[[File:Cantilever bridge human model.jpg|thumb|right|Illustration of the cantilever principle]]\nThe bridge is built on the principle of the [[cantilever bridge]], where a [[cantilever]] beam supports a light central girder, a principle that has been used for thousands of years in the construction of bridges.<ref name=w4>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=4}}</ref> In order to illustrate the use of tension and compression in the bridge, a demonstration in 1887 had the Japanese engineer [[Kaichi Watanabe]] supported between Fowler and Baker sitting in chairs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.universitystory.gla.ac.uk/biography/?id=WH17361&type=P |title=Kaichi Watanabe |publisher=University of Glasgow |accessdate=26 December 2014}}</ref> Fowler and Baker represent the cantilevers, with their arms in tension and the sticks under compression, and the bricks the cantilever end piers which are weighted with cast iron.<ref name=w6>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=6}}</ref>\n\n===Materials===\nThe bridge was the first major structure in Britain to be constructed of steel;<ref>{{harvnb|Blanc|McEvoy|Plank|2003|p=16}}</ref> its French contemporary, the [[Eiffel Tower]], was built of [[wrought iron]].<ref name=\"Hanser2006\">{{cite book |author=Hanser, David A. |title=Architecture of France |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zojzUU976h0C&pg=PA66 |year=2006 |publisher=Greenwood |isbn=978-0-313-31902-0 |page=66}}</ref>\nLarge amounts of steel became available after the invention of the [[Bessemer process]], patented in 1856.<ref>{{cite book |last=Wagner |first=Donald |title=Science and Civilisation in China: Vol. 5, Part 11: Ferrous Metallurgy |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FAud8CE5stsC&pg=PA361 |year=2008 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-87566-0 |page=361}}</ref><!-- The British [[Board of Trade]] had limited the use of steel in [[structural engineering]], as the produced steel was of unpredictable strength due to the production process. This limit was lifted in 1877 after the development of the [[Open hearth furnace|Siemens-Martin open-hearth process]] in 1875{{fact}}, which yielded steel of consistent quality.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}--> In 1859, the Board of Trade imposed a limit of {{convert|5|LTf/in2|N/mm2|2|abbr=on|lk=on|order=flip}} for the maximum design stress in railway bridges; this was revised as technology progressed.<ref name=\"historic-construction\">{{cite book|last1=D'Ayala |first1=Dina |last2=Fodde |first2=Enrico |title=Structural Analysis of Historic Construction: Preserving Safety and Significance, Two Volume Set: Proceedings of the VI International Conference on Structural Analysis of Historic Construction, SAHC08, 2\u20134 July 2008, Bath, United Kingdom |publisher=CRC Press |isbn=978-1-4398-2822-9 |page=209 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TVnRBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA209 |accessdate=30 April 2017|date=2 June 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe original design required {{convert|42000|t}} for the cantilevers only, of which {{convert|12000|t}} was to come from Siemens' steel works in [[Landore]], [[Wales]] and the remainder from the Steel Company of Scotland's works near Glasgow.<ref name=\"w36-37\">{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|pp=36\u201337}}</ref> When modifications to the design necessitated a further {{convert|16000|t}}, about half of this was supplied by the Steel Company of Scotland Ltd. and half by Dalzell's Iron and Steel Works in Motherwell.<ref name=w37>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=37}}</ref> About {{convert|4200|t}} of rivets came from the Clyde Rivet Company of Glasgow.<ref name=w37/> Around three or four thousand tons of steel was scrapped, some of which was used for temporary purposes, resulting in the discrepancy between the quantity delivered and the quantity erected.<ref name=w37/>\n\n===Approaches===\n[[File:Forth bridges 2005-06-17 06.jpg|thumb|The southern approach to the Forth Bridge, designed by [[James Carswell]]]]\nAfter [[Dalmeny railway station]], the track curves very slightly to the east before coming to the southern approach viaduct.<ref name=gmap>{{Google maps |url=https://www.google.co.uk/maps/@55.9996898,-3.3863626,14z |title=Forth Bridge |accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref> After the railway crosses the bridge, it passes through [[North Queensferry railway station]], before curving to the west, and then back to the east over the [[Jamestown Viaduct]].<ref name=gmap/>\n\nThe approaches were built under separate contract and were to the design of the engineer [[James Carswell]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scottisharchitects.org.uk/architect_full.php?id=100260 |title=James Carswell |website=Dictionary of Scottish Architects |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref> The supports of the approach viaducts are [[Entasis|tapered]] to prevent the impression of the columns widening as they approach the top, and an evaluation of the aesthetics of the Bridge in 2007, by A D Magee of the [[University of Bath]], identified that order was present throughout, and this included in the approach viaducts. Magee points out that the masonry was carefully planned, and has neat block work even in areas not immediately visible from the ground.<ref name=\"magee\" />{{rp|6}}\n\n==Construction==\n[[File:Forth Bridge - General view from back of Newhalls Inn, South Queensferry.jpg|left|thumb|The bridge under construction, viewed from South Queensferry]]\nThe Bill for the construction of the bridge was passed on 19 May 1882 after an eight-day enquiry, the only objections being from rival railway companies.<ref name=rp67>{{harvnb|Paxton|1990|p=67}}</ref> On 21 December, the contract was let to Sir Thomas Tancred, Mr. T. H. Falkiner and Mr. Joseph Philips, civil engineers and contractor, and [[Sir William Arrol & Co.]].<ref name=\"rp67-68\">{{harvnb|Paxton|1990|pp=67\u201368}}</ref> Arrol was a [[self-made man]], who had been apprenticed to a blacksmith at the age of thirteen before going on to have a highly successful business.<ref name=\"rp68-70\">{{harvnb|Paxton|1990|pp=68\u201370}}</ref> Tancred was a professional engineer who had worked with Arrol before, but he would leave the partnership during the course of construction.<ref name=rp70>{{harvnb|Paxton|1990|p=70}}</ref>\n\nThe steel was produced by Frederick and William Siemens (England) and Pierre and Emile Martin (France). Following advances in furnace design by the Siemens brothers and improvements by the Martin brothers, the process of manufacture enabled high quality steel to be produced very quickly.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.railway-technology.com/projects/forth-rail-bridge-firth-scotland/ |title=Forth Rail Bridge, Firth of Forth |work=Railway Technology |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://kids.britannica.com/comptons/article-202991/iron-and-steel-industry |title=iron and steel industry |publisher=Britannica |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.industrialmetalcastings.com/foundries_open_hearth.html|title=Open Hearth Furnace|website=www.industrialmetalcastings.com|access-date=30 April 2017|publisher=Industrialmetalcastings.com|date=2010}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Preparations===\n[[File:George Washington Wilson.jpg|thumb|The bridge under construction]]\nThe new works took possession of offices and stores erected by Arrol in connection with Bouch's bridge; these were expanded considerably over time.<ref name=w12>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=12}}</ref> Reginald Middleton took an accurate survey to establish the exact position of the bridge and allow the permanent construction work to commence.<ref name=\"w12-13\">{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|pp=12\u201313}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Triangulation & measurements at the Forth bridge |publisher=worldcat.org |oclc = 123250114}}</ref>\n\nThe old coastguard station at the Fife end had to be removed to make way for the north-east pier.<ref name=w13>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=13}}</ref> The rocky shore was levelled to a height of {{convert|7|ft}} above high water to make way for plant and materials, and huts and other facilities for workmen were set up further inland.<ref name=w13/>\n\nThe preparations at South Queensferry were much more substantial, and required the steep hillside to be terraced.<ref name=w13/> Wooden huts and shops for the workmen were put up, as well as more substantial brick houses for the foremen and tenements for leading hands and gangers.<ref name=w13/> Drill roads and workshops were built, as well as a [[Lofting|drawing loft]] {{convert|200|by|60|ft}} to allow full size drawings and templates to be laid out.<ref name=w13/> A cable was also laid across the Forth to allow telephone communication between the centres at South Queensferry, Inchgarvie, and North Queensferry, and girders from the collapsed [[Tay Rail Bridge|Tay Bridge]] were laid across the railway to the west in order to allow access to the ground there.<ref name=w13/> Near the shore a [[sawmill]] and cement store were erected, and a substantial jetty around {{convert|2100|ft}} long was started early in 1883, and extended as necessary, and [[Siding (rail)|sidings]] were built to bring railway vehicles among the shops, and cranes set up to allow the loading and movement of material delivered by rail.<ref name=w13/>\n\nIn April 1883, construction of a landing stage at [[Inchgarvie]] commenced.<ref name=w13/> Extant buildings, including fortifications built in the 15th century, were roofed over to increase the available space, and the rock at the west of the island was cut down to a level {{convert|7|ft}} above high water, and a seawall was built to protect against large waves.<ref name=w13/> In 1884 a [[compulsory purchase]] order was obtained for the island, as it was found that previously available area enclosed by the four piers of the bridge was insufficient for the storage of materials.<ref name=w13/> Iron staging reinforced wood in heavily used areas was put up over the island, eventually covering around {{convert|10000|sqyd}} and using over {{convert|1000|t}} of iron.<ref name=w14>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=14}}</ref>\n\n===Movement of materials===\n\nThe bridge uses {{convert|55000|t}} of [[steel]] and {{convert|140000|cuyd}} of masonry.<ref name=w14/> Many materials, including [[granite]] from [[Aberdeen]], [[Arbroath]] rubble, sand, timber, and sometimes coke and coal, could be taken straight to the centre where they were required.<ref name=w14/> Steel was delivered by train and prepared at the yard at [[South Queensferry]], painted with boiled [[linseed oil]], and was then taken to where it was needed by barge.<ref name=w14/> The cement used was [[Portland cement]] manufactured on the [[Medway]].<ref name=w17/> It required to be stored before it was able to be used, and up to {{convert|1200|t}} of [[cement]] could be kept in a barge, formerly called the ''[[Hougoumont (ship)|Hougoumont]]'' that was moored off South Queensferry.<ref name=w17>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=17}}</ref>\n\nFor a time a paddle steamer was hired for the movement of workers, but after a time it was replaced with one capable of carrying 450 men, and the barges were also used for people carrying.<ref name=w14/> Special trains were run from Edinburgh and Dunfermline, and a steamer ran to [[Leith]] in the summer.<ref name=w14/>\n\n===Circular piers===\n[[File:Forth Bridge (1890) Fig. 53, Page 30.png|thumb|right|upright|A completed caisson on Inchgarvie with the granite pier]]\nThe three towers of the cantilever are each seated on four circular piers. Since the foundations were required to be constructed at or below sea level, they were excavated with the assistance of [[caisson (engineering)|caissons]] and [[cofferdam]]s.<ref name=w17/> Caissons were used at locations that were either always under water, even at [[low tide]], or where the foundations were to be built on [[mud]] and [[clay]]. Cofferdams were used where rock was nearer to the surface, and it was possible to work in low tide.<ref name=\"magee\">{{cite conference |url=http://www.bath.ac.uk/ace/uploads/StudentProjects/Bridgeconference2007/conference/mainpage/Magee_Forth_Bridge.pdf |title=A Critical Analysis of the Forth Bridge |first=A D |last=Magee |author= |author-link= |date=27 April 2007 |conference=Bridge Engineering 2 Conference 2007 |conference-url=http://www.bath.ac.uk/ace/uploads/StudentProjects/Bridgeconference2007/index.html |volume=8  |publisher=University of Bath |access-date=30 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nSix caissons were excavated by the pneumatic process, by the French contractor L. Coisea.<ref name=w22>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=22}}</ref><ref name=w71/> This process used a positive air pressure inside a sealed caisson to allow dry working conditions at depths of up to {{convert|89|ft}}.<ref name=w71>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=71}}</ref><ref name=w27>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=27}}</ref>\n\nThese caissons were constructed and assembled in Glasgow by the Arrol Brothers, namesakes of but unconnected to W. Arrol, before being dismantled and transported to South Queensferry.<ref name=w22/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.glasgowwestaddress.co.uk/1888_Book/Arrol_Brothers.htm |title=Arrol Brothers |publisher=glasgowwestaddress.co.uk |accessdate=26 December 2014}}</ref> The caissons were then built up to a large extent before being floated to their final resting-places.<ref name=w23>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=23}}</ref> The first caisson, for the south-west pier at South Queensferry was launched on 26 May 1884, and the last caisson was launched on 29 May 1885 for the south-west pier at Inchgarvie.<ref name=w23/> When the caissons had been launched and moored, they were extended upwards with a temporary portion in order to keep water out and allow the granite pier to be built when in place.<ref name=w23/>\n\nAbove the foundations each of which is different to suit the different sites, is a tapered circular granite pier with a diameter of {{convert|55|ft}} at the bottom and a height of {{convert|36|ft}}.<ref name=w31>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=31}}</ref>\n\n====Inchgarvie====\nThe rock on which the two northern piers at Inchgarvie are located is submerged at high water, and of the other two piers, the site of eastern one is about half submerged and the western one three-quarters submerged.<ref name=w18>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=18}}</ref> This meant work initially had to be done at low tide.<ref name=w18/>\n\nThe southern piers on Inchgarvie are sited on solid rock with a slope of around 1 in 5, so the rock was prepared with concrete and sandbags to make a landing-spot for the caissons.<ref name=w26/><ref name=w20>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=20}}</ref> Excavation was carried out by [[drilling and blasting]], but no blasting was done within {{convert|1.5|ft|abbr=on}} of the caissons, and the remaining rock was quarried to within {{convert|6|in|abbr=on}}.<ref name=w18/>\n\n====North Queensferry====\nOnce the positions of the piers had been established, the first task at the Fife end was to level the site of the northernmost piers, a bedrock of whinstone rising to a level of {{convert|10|to|20|ft}} above high water, to a height of {{convert|7|ft}} above high water.<ref name=w17/> The south piers at North Queensferry are sited on rock sloping into the sea, and the site was prepared by [[diamond drilling]] holes for explosive charges and blasting the rock.<ref name=w18/>\n\n====South Queensferry====\n[[File:Forth Bridge (1890) Fig. 46, Page 26.png|thumb|left|The tilted caisson]]\n[[File:Forth Bridge (1890) Fig. 51, Page 28.png|thumb|left|The mode of sinking the South Queensferry caissons]]\n\nThe four South Queensferry caissons were all sunk by the pneumatic method, and are identical in design except for differences in height.<ref name=w22/> A '''T''' shaped jetty was built at the site of the South Queensferry piers, to allow one caisson to be attached to each corner, and when launched the caissons were attached to the jetty and permitted to rise and fall with the tide.<ref name=w23/><ref name=w21>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=21}}</ref> Excavation beneath the caissons was generally only carried out at high tide when the caisson was supported by buoyancy, and then when the tide fell the air pressure was reduced in order to allow the caisson to sink down, and digging would begin anew.<ref name=w27/>\n\nThe north-west caisson was towed into place in December 1884, but an exceptionally low tide on New Year's Day 1885 caused the caisson to sink into the mud of the river bed and adopt a slight tilt.<ref name=w26>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=26}}</ref> When the tide rose, it flooded over the lower edge, filling the caisson with water, and when the tide fell but the water did not drain from the caisson, its top-heaviness caused to tilt further.<ref name=w26/> Plates were bolted on by divers to raise the edge of the caisson above water level, and the caisson was reinforced with wooden struts as water was pumped out, but pumping took place too quickly and the water pressure tore a hole between {{convert|25|and|30|ft}} long.<ref name=w26/> It was decided to construct a \"barrel\" of large timbers inside the caisson to reinforce it, and it was ten months before the caisson could be pumped out and dug free.<ref name=w26/> The caisson was refloated on 19 October 1885, and then moved into position and sunk with suitable modifications.<ref name=w26/>\n\n===Approach viaducts===\nThe approach viaducts to the north and south had to be carried at {{convert|130|ft|6|in}} above the level of high water, and it was decided to build them at a lower level and then raise them in tandem with the construction of the masonry piers.<ref name=w32>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=32}}</ref> The two viaducts have fifteen spans between them, each one {{convert|168|ft}} long and weighing slightly over {{convert|200|t}}.<ref name=w32/> Two spans are attached together to make a continuous [[girder]], with an [[expansion joint]] between each pair of spans.<ref name=w32/> Due to the slope of the hill under the viaducts, the girders were assembled at different heights, and only joined when they had reached the same level.<ref name=w33>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=33}}</ref> Lifting was done using large [[hydraulic ram]]s, and took place in increments of around {{convert|3|ft|6|in}} every four days.<ref name=w33/>\n\n===Building the cantilevers===\nThe tubular members were constructed in the No. 2 workshop further up the hill at South Queensferry.<ref name=w38>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=38}}</ref> To bend plates into the required shape, they were first heated in a gas furnace, and then pressed into the correct curve.<ref name=w38/> The curved plates were then assembled on a [[mandrel]], and holes drilled for rivets, before they were marked individually and moved to the correct location to be added to the structure.<ref name=w38/> Lattice members and other parts were also assembled at South Queensferry, using cranes and highly efficient hydraulic rivetters.<ref name=w39>{{harvnb|Westhofen|1890|p=39}}</ref>\n<!--\n====Bedplates====\nAbove the twelve circular granite piers are the bedplates, some of which are constructed in such a way as to allow limited movement.<w39>\n\nThe bridge is bolted to the piers by holding-down bolts around {{convert|2.5|in}} thick and {{convert|25|ft}} long, with 48 bolts in each of the twelve piers.<w32> The bolts are angled slightly\n-->\n\n===Opening===\nThe bridge was completed in December 1889, and load testing of the completed bridge was carried out on 21 January 1890. Two trains, each consisting of three heavy locomotives and 50 wagons loaded with coal, totalling 1,880 tons in weight, were driven slowly from South Queensferry to the middle of the north cantilever, stopping frequently to measure the deflection of the bridge. This represented more than twice the design load of the bridge: the deflection under load was as expected.<ref name=\"Descriptionand1890\" /> A few days previously there had been a violent storm, producing the highest wind pressure recorded to date at Inchgarvie, and the deflection of the cantilevers had been less than 25&nbsp;mm (1&nbsp;in). The first complete crossing took place on 24 February, when a train consisting of two carriages carrying the chairmen of the various railway companies involved made several crossings. The bridge was opened on 4 March 1890 by the Duke of Rothesay, later King [[Edward VII of the United Kingdom|Edward VII]], who drove home the last rivet, which was gold plated and suitably inscribed.<ref name=Gazetteer/> The key for the official opening was made by Edinburgh silversmith John Finlayson Bain, commemorated in a plaque on the bridge. When it opened it had the [[list of longest cantilever bridge spans|longest single cantilever bridge span]] in the world,<ref name=\"UNESCO\">{{cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1485|title=The Forth Bridge|date=2015|publisher=UNESCO|quote=This railway bridge, crossing the Forth estuary in Scotland, had the world's longest spans (541&nbsp;m) when it opened in 1890. It remains one of the greatest cantilever trussed bridges and continues to carry passengers and freight.|last1=Centre|first1=UNESCO World Heritage|accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref> until 1919 when the [[Quebec Bridge]] in [[Canada]] was completed.<ref name=\"quebecBridge\">{{cite web|url=http://www.travelandleisure.com/slideshows/worlds-longest-bridges/14|title=Longest Cantilever Bridge Span: The Quebec Bridge, Quebec|date=2017|website=travelandleisure.com|publisher=Travel + Leisure|quote=Finally, in December 1919, the 94-foot-wide, 1,800-foot-long central span was jacked 150 feet into place, and it has remained the record-holder ever since.|accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref> It continues to be the world's second-longest single cantilever span, with a span of {{convert|521|m|order=flip}}.<ref name=\"spanLengths\">{{cite web|url=http://www.forth-bridges.co.uk/forth-bridge/facts-figures-rail.html|title=Key facts about the Forth Bridge|date=2015|website=forth-bridges.co.uk|publisher=Forth Bridges Forum|quote=The two main spans of 521m were for 28 years the longest and second longest bridge spans in the world|accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n{{main|Forth Bridge approach railways}}\nTo make the fullest use of the bridge, [[Forth Bridge approach railways|several new railway connections]] were built, bringing main line routes to the bridge. The construction of some of these lines was only completed on 2 June 1890, delaying the implementation of a full express train service over the bridge until that date. Even then, there was considerable congestion at Edinburgh Waverley station with remarshalling of the portions of the new, more intensive train service.<ref>''Aberdeen Weekly Journal'', 4 June 1890</ref>\n\n===Accidents and deaths===\nAt its peak, approximately 4,600 workers were employed in the bridge's construction. Wilhelm Westhofen recorded in 1890 that 57 lives were lost. In 2005 the Forth Bridge Memorial Committee was set up to erect a monument to those lost, and a team of local historians set out to name all those who died.<ref name=b82>{{harvnb|Wills|2009|p=82}}</ref> As of 2009, 73 deaths have been connected with the construction of the bridge and its immediate aftermath.<ref name=b86>{{harvnb|Wills|2009|p=86}}</ref> It is thought that the figure of 57 deaths excluded those who died working on the approaches to the bridge, as those parts were completed by a subcontractor, as well as those who died after the Sick and Accident Club stopped.<ref name=b86/> Of the 73 recorded deaths, 38 were as a result of falling, 9 of being crushed, 9 drowned, 8 struck by a falling object, 3 died in a fire in a [[bothy]], 1 of [[Decompression sickness|caisson disease]], and the cause of five deaths is unknown.<ref name=b90>{{harvnb|Wills|2009|p=90}}</ref>\n\nThe Sick and Accident Club was founded in 1883, and membership was compulsory for all contractors' employees.<ref name=rp136/> It would provide medical treatment to men and sometimes their families, and pay them if they were unable to work.<ref name=rp136/> The club also paid for funerals within certain limits, and would provide grants to the widows of men killed or the wives of those permanently disabled.<ref name=rp136>{{harvnb|Paxton|1990|p=136}}</ref> Eight men were saved from drowning by rowing boats positioned in the river under the working areas.<ref name=w14/>\n\n==Later history==\n\n===Race to the North===\nBefore the opening of the Forth Bridge, the railway journey from London to [[Aberdeen]] had taken about 13 hours running from {{stnlnk|Euston}} and using the [[London and North Western Railway]] and [[Caledonian Railway]] on a [[West Coast Main Line|west coast route]]. With competition opened up along the [[East Coast Main Line|east coast route]] from the [[Great Northern Railway (Great Britain)|Great Northern]], [[North Eastern Railway (UK)|North Eastern]] and [[North British Railway|North British]] railways and starting from [[London King's Cross railway station|King's Cross]], unofficial racing took place between the two consortia, reducing the journey time to about 8\u00bd hours on the overnight runs. This reached a climax in 1895 with sensational daily press reports about the \"[[Race to the North]]\". When race fever subsided the journey times became around 10\u00bd hours.<ref>{{harvnb|Nock|1958|pp=64,66}}</ref>\n\n===World wars===\n\n[[File:Are these \"just a few splashes\", Mr. Churchill?.jpg|thumb|A German photograph allegedly taken during the raid]]\nIn the [[First World War]] British sailors would time their departures or returns to the base at [[Rosyth]] by asking when they would pass under the bridge.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/stream/northseadiary00kingiala/northseadiary00kingiala_djvu.txt |title=A North Sea diary, 1914\u20131918 |author=King-Hall, Stephen |publisher=Newnes |date= |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref> <!--This practice continued at least up to the 1990s. In both wars the anchorage at Rosyth extended eastwards beyond the bridge.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}--> The first German air attack on Britain in the [[Second World War]] took place over the Forth Bridge, six weeks into the war, on 16 October 1939. Although known as the \"Forth Bridge Raid\", the bridge was not the target and not damaged. In all, 12 German [[Junkers Ju 88]] bombers led by two reconnaissance [[Heinkel He 111]]s from Westerland on the island of [[Sylt]], {{convert|460|mi|nmi km}} away, reached the Scottish coast in four waves of three.<ref>W. Simpson, ''Spitfires Over Scotland'', G C Books Ltd., 2010 {{ISBN|978-1-872350-44-8}}, p. 84</ref> The target of the attack was shipping from the [[Rosyth Dockyard|Rosyth naval base]] in the Forth, close to the bridge. The Germans were hoping to find {{HMS|Hood|51|6}}, the largest [[capital ship]] in the Royal Navy. ''[[Luftwaffe]]'' rules of engagement restricted action to targets on water and not in the dockyard. Although {{HMS|Repulse|1916|6}} was in Rosyth, the attack was concentrated on the cruisers {{HMS|Edinburgh|16|2}} and {{HMS|Southampton|83|2}}, the carrier {{HMS|Furious|47|2}} and the destroyer [[HMS Jervis|''Jervis'']].<ref>W. Simpson, ''Spitfires Over Scotland'', p. 92</ref> The destroyer ''Mohawk'' and the cruisers, ''Southampton'' and ''Edinburgh'' were damaged. Sixteen Royal Navy crew died and 44 were wounded, although this information was not made public at the time.<ref name=\"LTS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.educationscotland.gov.uk/scotlandshistory/20thand21stcenturies/worldwarii/airattack/index.asp|title=Air attack in the Firth of Forth|website=educationscotland.org.uk|publisher=[[Learning and Teaching Scotland]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150406135906/http://www.educationscotland.gov.uk/scotlandshistory/20thand21stcenturies/worldwarII/airattack/index.asp|archive-date=6 April 2015|url-status=dead|accessdate=25 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Spitfire]]s from [[No. 603 Squadron RAF|603 \"City of Edinburgh\" Squadron]] RAF intercepted the raiders and during the attack shot down the first German aircraft downed over Britain in the war.<ref name=\"LTS\" /> One bomber came down in the water off [[Port Seton]] on the East Lothian coast and another off [[Crail]] on the coast of Fife. After the War it was learned that a third bomber had come down in the Netherlands as a result of damage inflicted during the raid. Later in the month, a reconnaissance Heinkel 111 crashed near [[Humbie]] in [[East Lothian]] and photographs of this crashed plane were, and still are, used erroneously to illustrate the raid of 16 October, thus sowing confusion as to whether a third aircraft had been brought down.<ref>W. Simpson, ''Spitfires Over Scotland'', p. 108</ref> Members of the bomber crew at Port Seton were rescued and made prisoners-of-war. Two bodies were recovered from the Crail wreckage and after a full military funeral with firing party, were interred in [[Portobello, Edinburgh|Portobello]] cemetery, Edinburgh. The body of the gunner was never found.<ref>W. Simpson, ''Spitfires Over Scotland'', pp. 100, 109</ref> A wartime propaganda film, ''Squadron 992'', made by the [[GPO Film Unit]] after the raid, recreated it and conveyed the false impression that the main target was the bridge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/1364857/index.html |title=BFI Screenonline: Squadron 992 (1940) |website=Screen Online |accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Ownership===\n[[File:Forth Bridge RJD 129.jpg|right|thumb|upright|A 1913 [[Railway Clearing House]] Junction Diagram showing the Forth Bridge Railway (red) and neighbouring lines of the [[North British Railway]] (blue)]]\nBefore the opening of the bridge, the [[North British Railway]] (NBR) had lines on both sides of the Firth of Forth between which trains could not pass except by running at least as far west as {{stnlnk|Alloa}} and using the lines of a rival company. The only alternative route between Edinburgh and Fife involved the ferry at Queensferry, which was purchased by the NBR in 1867. Accordingly, the NBR sponsored the Forth Bridge project which would give them a direct link independent of the [[Caledonian Railway]].<ref name=Awdry132>{{cite book |last=Awdry |first=Christopher |authorlink=Christopher Awdry |title=Encyclopaedia of British Railway Companies |year=1990 |publisher=Guild Publishing |location=London |id=CN 8983 |page=132 |ref=harv }}</ref> A conference at York in 1881 set up the Forth Bridge Railway Committee, to which the NBR contributed 35% of the cost. The remaining money came from three English railways, which ran trains from London over NBR tracks. The [[Midland Railway]], which connected to the NBR at {{stnlnk|Carlisle}} and which owned the route to [[St Pancras railway station|London (St Pancras)]], contributed 30% and the remainder came equally from the [[North Eastern Railway (UK)|North Eastern Railway]] and the [[Great Northern Railway (Great Britain)|Great Northern Railway]], which between them owned the route between {{stnlnk|Berwick-upon-Tweed}} and [[London King's Cross railway station|London (King's Cross)]], via {{stnlnk|Doncaster}}. This body undertook to construct and maintain the bridge.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Thomas |first1=John |last2=Turnock |first2=David |editor1-last=Thomas |editor1-first=David St John |editor1-link=David St John Thomas |editor2-last=Patmore |editor2-first=J. Allan |title=A Regional History of the Railways of Great Britain: Volume XV&nbsp;\u2014 North of Scotland |year=1989 |publisher=[[David St John Thomas]] |location=Newton Abbot |isbn=0-946537-03-8 |page=71 |ref=harv }}</ref>\n\nIn 1882 the NBR were given powers to purchase the bridge, which it never exercised.<ref name=Awdry132 /> At the time of the [[1923 Grouping]], the bridge was still jointly owned by the same four railways,<ref>{{cite book |last=Conolly |first=W. Philip |title=British Railways Pre-Grouping Atlas and Gazetteer |edition=5th |date=January 1976 |publisher=[[Ian Allan Publishing|Ian Allan]] |location=Shepperton |isbn=0-7110-0320-3 |id=EX/0176 |page=49 |ref=harv }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Whitehouse |first1=Patrick |last2=Thomas |first2=David St John |authorlink2=David St John Thomas |title=LNER 150: The London and North Eastern Railway&nbsp;\u2013 A Century and a Half of Progress |year=1989 |publisher=[[David & Charles]] |location=Newton Abbot |isbn=0-7153-9332-4 |id=01LN01 |page=21 |ref=harv }}</ref> and so it became jointly owned by these companies' successors, the [[London Midland and Scottish Railway]] (30%) and the [[London and North Eastern Railway]] (70%).<ref>{{cite book |last=Hughes |first=Geoffrey |title=LNER |year=1987 |origyear=1986 |publisher=Guild Publishing/Book Club Associates |location=London |id=CN 1455 |pages=33\u201334 |ref=harv }}</ref> The Forth Bridge Railway Company was named in the [[Transport Act 1947]] as one of the bodies to be nationalised and so became part of [[British Railways]] on 1 January 1948.<ref>{{cite book |title=Transport Act 1947 (10 & 11 Geo. 6 ch. 49) |chapter-url=http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/documents/HMG_Act1947.pdf |date=6 August 1947 |author=His Majesty's Government |publisher=His Majesty's Stationery Office |location=London |chapter=Third Schedule |page=145 |accessdate=1 July 2011 |ref=ref1011Geo6c49 }}</ref> Under the Act, Forth Bridge shareholders would receive \u00a3109 of British Transport stock for each \u00a3100 of Forth Bridge Debenture stock; and \u00a3104-17-6d (\u00a3104.87\u00bd) of British Transport stock for each \u00a3100 of Forth Bridge Ordinary stock.<ref>[[#ref1011Geo6c49|Transport Act 1947]], fourth schedule, p. 148</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Bonavia |first=Michael R. |title=British Rail: The First 25 Years |year=1981 |publisher=[[David & Charles]] |location=Newton Abbot |isbn=0-7153-8002-8 |page=10 |ref=harv }}</ref>\n\nAs of April 2017, the bridge and its associated railway infrastructure are owned by [[Network Rail|Network Rail Infrastructure Limited]].<ref name=\"networkRail\">{{cite web|url=https://www.networkrail.co.uk/running-the-railway/our-routes/scotland/|title=Scotland \u2013 Network Rail|date=2017|website=www.networkrail.co.uk|publisher=Network Rail|quote=Network Rail Scotland looks after Scotland's railway infrastructure, including the world-famous Forth Bridge that connects passengers in Fife, north of Edinburgh, with Edinburgh and the Borders.|accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Operation==\n[[File:The Forth Bridge seen from Dalmeny Station.JPG|thumb|left|upright|The approach to the bridge from [[Dalmeny Station]]]]\n[[File:InsideTheForthRailBridge 19990822P0001.jpg|thumb|right|Inside the Forth Bridge as seen from a [[ScotRail (National Express)|ScotRail]] [[British Rail Class 158|class 158]]]]\n\n===Traffic===\nThe bridge has a speed limit of {{convert|50|mph}} for high-speed trains and [[diesel multiple unit]]s, {{convert|40|mph}} for ordinary passenger trains and {{convert|30|mph}} for freight trains.<ref name=bm11>{{harvnb|Harding|Gerard|Ryall|2006|p=11}}</ref><ref name=rp91>{{harvnb|Paxton|1990|p=91}}</ref> The [[route availability]] code is RA8, but freight trains above a certain size must not pass each other on the bridge.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.transportscotland.gov.uk/report/j8512a-05.htm |title=Forth Bridge and Associated Rail Network |publisher=Transport Scotland |accessdate=20 July 2014}}</ref> Up to 190\u2013200&nbsp;trains per day crossed the bridge in 2006.<ref>\"[http://www.forthbridges.org.uk/railbridgemain.htm The Forth Bridge] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080222183156/http://www.forthbridges.org.uk/railbridgemain.htm |date=22 February 2008 }}\". Forth Bridges Visitors Centre Trust. Retrieved 21 April 2006.</ref>\n\n===Maintenance===\n<!--The Forth Bridge needs constant maintenance and the ancillary works for the bridge include not only a maintenance workshop and yard but a railway \"colony\" of some fifty houses at [[Dalmeny railway station|Dalmeny Station]]. The track on the bridge is of \"[[waybeam]]\" construction: 12&nbsp;inch square baulks of timber 6 metres long are bolted into steel troughs in the bridge deck and the rails are fixed on top of these sleepers. Prior to 1992 the rails on the bridge were of a unique \"Forth Bridge\" section.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}-->\n\n{{Anchor|painting}}\"Painting the Forth Bridge\" is a colloquial expression for a never-ending task, coined on the erroneous belief that at one time in the history of the bridge repainting was required and commenced immediately upon completion of the previous repaint.<ref name=\"dict\">{{cite web |title=be like painting the Forth Bridge |url=http://idioms.thefreedictionary.com/be+like+painting+the+Forth+Bridge |publisher=theFreeDictionary.com |accessdate=23 November 2010}}</ref> Such a practice never existed, as weathered areas were given more attention, but there was a permanent maintenance crew.<ref name=rai15/> In 2011, the bridge was covered in a new coating designed to last for 25 years, bringing an end to having painters as a regular part of the maintenance crew. Colin Hardie, of [[Balfour Beatty Construction]], was reported as saying,<ref name=\"paintingEnd\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-edinburgh-east-fife-14789036|title=Forth Bridge painting 'is coming to an end'|date=5 September 2011 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |quote=The Forth Rail Bridge will be free of scaffolding and painters from 9 December|accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/jan/26/world/la-fg-scotland-bridge-20120127|title=Scotland can stop painting its Forth Rail Bridge|last=Chu|first=Henry|date=26 January 2012|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=13 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=For the first time in the bridge's history there will be no painters required on the bridge. Job done&nbsp;... |sign=Colin Hardie|source=[[BBC News]] article, 5 September 2011}}\n\n===Restoration===\nFloodlighting was installed in 1991, and the track was renewed between 1992 and 1995.<ref name=rai15>{{harvnb|Glen|Bowman|Andrew|2012|p=15}}</ref> The bridge was costing [[British Rail]] \u00a31&nbsp;million a year to maintain, and they announced that the schedule of painting would be interrupted to save money, and the following year, upon privatisation, [[Railtrack]] took over.<ref name=rai15/> A \u00a340&nbsp;million package of works commenced in 1998, and in 2002 the responsibility of the bridge was passed to [[Network Rail]].<ref name=rai15/>\n\nWork started in 2002 to repaint the bridge fully for the first time in its history, in a \u00a3130&nbsp;million contract awarded to [[Balfour Beatty]].<ref name=rai16>{{harvnb|Glen|Bowman|Andrew|2012|p=16.}}</ref><ref name=mos>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/men-of-steel-the-men-who-maintain-the-forth-rail-bridge-1-1976605 |title=Men of Steel: The men who maintain the Forth Rail Bridge |work=The Scotsman |date=22 November 2011}}</ref> Up to {{convert|4000|t}} of scaffolding was on the bridge at any time, and computer modelling was used to analyse the additional wind load on the structure.<ref name=rai18>{{harvnb|Glen|Bowman|Andrew|2012|p=18}}</ref> The bridge was encapsulated in a climate controlled membrane to give the proper conditions for the application of the paint.<ref name=rai19>{{harvnb|Glen|Bowman|Andrew|2012|p=19}}</ref> All previous layers of paint were removed using [[copper slag]] fired at up to {{convert|200|mph}}, exposing the steel and allowing repairs to be made.<ref name=rai19/><ref name=\"NCE\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nce.co.uk/painting-of-forth-bridge-to-end/754462.article |title=Painting of Forth bridge to end |last=McKenna |first=John |date=19 February 2008 |work=New Civil Engineer |accessdate=16 January 2010}}</ref> The paint, developed specifically for the bridge by [[Leigh Paints]], consisted of a system of three coats derived from that used in the North Sea oil industry.<ref name=rai19/> {{convert|240000|l}} of paint was applied to {{convert|255000|m2}} of the structure, and it is not expected to need repainting for at least 20 years.<ref name=mos/><ref name=rai19/> The top coat can be reapplied indefinitely, minimising future maintenance work.<ref name=rai20>{{harvnb|Glen|Bowman|Andrew|2012|p=20}}</ref>\n\n{{wide image|Forth rail bridge head-on-panorama josh-von-staudach.jpg|1320px|align-cap=center|Panoramic view of the Forth Bridge undergoing maintenance work in 2007}}\n\nIn a report produced by JE Jacobs, [[Grant Thornton]] and [[Faber Maunsell]] in 2007 which reviewed the alternative options for a second road crossing, it was stated that \"Network Rail has estimated the life of the bridge to be in excess of 100 years. However, this is dependant {{sic}} upon NR's inspection and refurbishment works programme for the bridge being carried out year on year\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.transport.gov.scot/report/j8512a-05.htm#43 |title=Forth Replacement Crossing \u2013 Report 1 \u2013 Assessment of Transport Network |publisher=Transport Scotland |archive-url=https://www.webarchive.org.uk/wayback/archive/20170106202624/http://www.transport.gov.scot/report/j8512a-05.htm#43 |archive-date=6 January 2017 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== In culture ==\n[[File:ForthRivet.JPG|thumb|Original [[rivet]] from the Forth Bridge]]\n\n===In the media===\nThe Forth Bridge has been featured in [[television program]]mes and films, including ''[[Carry On Regardless]]'', [[Alfred Hitchcock]]'s 1935 film ''[[The 39 Steps (1935 film)|The 39 Steps]]'', and its [[The 39 Steps (1959 film)|1959 remake]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lner.info/article/filmtv/filmtv.shtml|title=The LNER in Books, Film, and TV|accessdate=18 January 2014}}</ref> [[A.G. Barr]] used the bridge in posters advertising its soft drink [[Irn-Bru]], with the slogan: \"Made in Scotland, from [[girder]]s\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edinburgh-inspiringcapital.com/about/blog/forth_bridge_repaint.aspx|title=A Glow in the Dark Forth Bridge? Easy For Boats to Spot at Least!|accessdate=18 January 2014|archive-url=https://archive.is/20140118134624/http://www.edinburgh-inspiringcapital.com/about/blog/forth_bridge_repaint.aspx|archive-date=18 January 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2005, the [[BBC]] lit the Bridge in red for [[Comic Relief]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dunfermlineonline.net/news/index.php?ID=149&CATEGORY2=|title=Dunfermline.info The Historic City|accessdate=18 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824001731/http://dunfermlineonline.net/news/index.php?ID=149&CATEGORY2=|archive-date=24 August 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Also in 2005, [[Channel 4]] documentary ''[[Jump Britain]]'' showed [[S\u00e9bastien Foucan]], a French [[Free running|freerunner]], crawling along one of the highest points of the bridge without a harness.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bufvc.ac.uk/dvdfind/index.php/title/av38090|title=Jump Britain \u00b7 British Universities Film & Video Council|accessdate=18 January 2014}}</ref> The first episode of the UK television series ''Britain's Greatest Bridges'' featured the Forth Bridge and was aired on [[Spike (UK)|Spike UK]] on 12 January 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.channel5.com/show/britains-greatest-bridges/|title=Britain's Greatest Bridges|work=Channel 5|access-date=26 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== In general culture ===\nThe location of the Forth Bridge has seen it featured in other cultural forms. In the build up to the [[Millennium celebrations]] a countdown clock sponsored by the [[Royal Bank of Scotland]] was attached to the top of the Bridge in 1998.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/transport/forth-road-bridge-50th-year-ad-banner-plan-slammed-1-3054573|title=Forth Road Bridge 50th year ad banner plan slammed \u2013 The Scotsman|work=[[The Scotsman]]|accessdate=18 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.forth-bridges.co.uk/forth-bridge/history/growth-milestones.html|title=Growth and milestones|website=forth-bridges.co.uk|publisher=Forth Bridges Forum|access-date=29 April 2017}}</ref> [[Iain Banks]] wrote the novel ''[[The Bridge (novel)|The Bridge]]'', which is mainly set on a fictionalised version of the bridge, which links \"The City\" (Edinburgh) and \"The Kingdom\" ([[Fife]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arts.gla.ac.uk/scotlit/asls/Laverock-Iain_Banks.html|title=The Worlds of Iain Banks|last=MacGillivray|first=Alan|date=30 September 2013|website=arts.gla.ac.uk|publisher=The Association for Scottish Literary Studies|accessdate=18 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503134235/http://www.arts.gla.ac.uk/ScotLit/ASLS/Laverock-Iain_Banks.html|archive-date=3 May 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In [[Alan Turing]]'s most famous paper about [[artificial intelligence]], one of the challenges put to the subject of an imagined [[Turing test]] is \"Please write me a sonnet on the subject of the Forth Bridge.\" The test subject in Turing's paper answers, \"Count me out on this one. I never could write poetry.\"<ref>{{Turing 1950}}</ref> The bridge is included in the video game ''[[Grand Theft Auto: San Andreas]]'' by Edinburgh-based developer [[Rockstar North]]. Renamed the Kincaid Bridge, it serves as the main railway bridge of the fictional city of [[San Fierro]], and appears alongside a virtual Forth Road Bridge.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/gaming/grand-theft-auto-tour-of-scotland-as-councillors-of-hawick-disgusted-by-use-of-name-for-gta-vs-drug-district-8830390.html|title=Grand Theft Auto tour of Scotland as councillors of Hawick 'disgusted' by use of name for GTA V's drug district|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=18 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bison Skeleton.svg|thumb|[[D'Arcy Thompson]] used a figure of a [[bison]] skeleton when comparing it to the structural form of the Forth Bridge.<ref name=\"D'ArcyThompson\"/>]]\n\nIn his 1917 book ''[[On Growth and Form]]'', the mathematical biologist [[D'Arcy Thompson]] compares the structural form of the Forth Bridge with the cantilevered [[skeleton]] of an [[ox]], the piers corresponding to legs, the cantilevers to the [[vertebral column]]:<ref name=\"D'ArcyThompson\">{{cite book |last1=Thompson |first1=D'Arcy |authorlink1=D'Arcy Wentworth Thompson |editor1-last=Bonner |editor1-first=John Tyler |editor1-link=John Tyler Bonner |title=On Growth and Form |date=1961 |origyear=1917 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=0-521-09390-2 |pages=243\u2013246 |edition=Abridged}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|In a typical cantilever bridge, such as the Forth Bridge, a certain simplification is introduced. For each pier carries, in this case, its own double-armed cantilever, linked by a short connecting girder to the next, but so jointed to it that no weight is transmitted from one cantilever to another. The bridge in short is ''cut'' into separate sections, practically independent of one another&nbsp;... In the horse or the ox, it is obvious that the two piers of the bridge, that is to say the fore-legs and the hind-legs, do not bear (as they do in the Forth Bridge) separate and independent loads, but the whole system forms a continuous structure.<ref name=\"D'ArcyThompson\"/>}}\n\n===As heritage===\nNetwork Rail plans to add a visitor centre to the bridge, which would include a viewing platform on top of the North Queensferry side, or a bridge climbing experience to the South Queensferry side.<ref name=fs>{{cite web |title=The Forth Bridge Experience: An executive summary of its feasibility|publisher=Network Rail Infrastructure Limited|website=forthbridgeexperience.com|date=23 August 2013 |url=http://www.forthbridgeexperience.com/media/498/Network-Rail-Forth-Bridge-Feasibility-Study-LR.pdf |accessdate=20 July 2014}}</ref> In December 2014 it was announced Arup had been awarded the design contract for the project.<ref>{{cite web |title=Design For \u00a315m Forth Bridge Visitor Won by Arup |url=http://www.obas.com/blog/design-for-15m-forth-bridge-visitor-centre-won-by-arup/ | publisher=obas.com |date=15 December 2012}}</ref>\nUNESCO inscribed the bridge as a [[UNESCO World Heritage Site|World Heritage Site]] on 5 July 2015, recognising it as \"an extraordinary and impressive milestone in bridge design and construction during the period when railways came to dominate long-distance land travel\". It is the sixth World Heritage Site to be inscribed in Scotland.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-edinburgh-east-fife-33397980 |title=Forth Bridge given world heritage status |publisher=BBC News |date=5 July 2015 |accessdate=5 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"UNESCO\" /> In 2016, a [[VisitScotland]] survey voted the Forth Bridge \"Scotland's greatest man-made wonder\", beating off competition from [[Stirling Castle]], the [[Caledonian Canal]], the [[Scott Monument]], [[Bell Rock Lighthouse]], and [[Melrose Abbey]].<ref name=\"bridgeIconic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/720896/Forth-railway-bridge-voted-scotlands-greatest-man-made-wonder|title=The Forth Railway Bridge is voted Scotland's 'greatest man-made wonder'|date=14 October 2016|website=Express.co.uk|publisher=Express Newspapers|last1=Ward|first1=Paul|accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Forth Bridge has appeared in representation on a 2004 [[One pound (British coin)|one pound coin]], issued by the [[Royal Mint]].<ref name=\"royalmint\">{{cite web|url=http://www.royalmint.com/Corporate/facts/coins/OnePoundCoin.aspx|title=The United Kingdom \u00a31 Coin|publisher=The Royal Mint|accessdate=21 June 2009|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/677vdSI6z?url=http://www.royalmint.com/discover/uk-coins/coin-design-and-specifications/one-pound-coin|archive-date=23 April 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Bridge has also featured on various [[banknotes of the pound sterling|banknotes]] including the 2007 series issued by the [[Bank of Scotland]], which depicts different bridges in Scotland as examples of Scottish engineering, and the \u00a320 note features the Forth Bridge.<ref name=\"scotbanks\">{{cite web |url=http://www.scotbanks.org.uk/banknote_design_bank_of_scotland_bridges.php |title=Banknote Design Features : Bank of Scotland Bridges Series |publisher=The Committee of Scottish Clearing Bankers |accessdate=29 October 2008}}</ref> In 2014 [[Clydesdale Bank]] announced the introduction of Britain's second [[polymer banknote]], a \u00a35 note featuring [[Sir William Arrol]] and the Forth Bridge (the first polymer banknote was [[Banknotes of Northern Ireland#Danske Bank/Northern Bank notes|issued by Northern Bank in 2000]]). It was introduced in 2015 to commemorate the 125th anniversary of the opening of the bridge, and its nomination to become a UNESCO World Heritage Site.<ref name=\"herscot\">{{cite news |title=UK's first plastic banknote introduced to commemorate Forth Bridge's UNESCO nomination |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/home-news/uks-first-polymer-note-introduced-to-commemorate-forth-bridges-unesco-nomination.1400751223 |newspaper=Herald Scotland |date=22 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Scotland}}\n* [[Banknotes of Scotland]] (featured on design)\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Blanc|first1=Alan|last2=McEvoy|first2=Michael|last3=Plank|first3=Roger|title=Architecture and Construction in Steel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Knmi0lzWd-0C|year=2003|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-135-82839-4}}\n<!--* {{cite book|last=Cole|first=Beverly|title=Trains|publisher=H.F.Ullmann|year=2011|isbn=978-3-8480-0516-1 |location=Potsdam, Germany |ref=harv }} unused-->\n* {{cite book |last1=Glen |first1=Ann |last2=Bowman |first2=Craig |last3=Andrew |first3=John |title=Forth Bridge: Restoring an Icon |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5qAoLgEACAAJ |year=2012 |publisher=Lily Publications |isbn=978-1-907945-19-9 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zlGErQK_qPoC |title=Bridge Management: Inspection, maintenance, assessment and repair |last1=Harding |first1=J. E. |last2=Gerard |first2=Parke |last3=Ryall |first3=M |year=2006 |publisher=CRC Press |isbn=978-0-203-97354-7 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=McKean |first=Charles |authorlink=Charles McKean |title=Battle for the North |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kUYfAQAAIAAJ |year=2006 |publisher=Granta Books |isbn=978-1-86207-852-9 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Nock |first=Oswald S. |title=The Railway Race to the North |year=1958 |publisher=Ian Allan |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=81rbAAAAMAAJ |title=100 Years of the Forth Bridge |first=Roland |last=Paxton |publisher=Thomas Telford |isbn=978-0-7277-1600-2 |year=1990 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2CD6-fz-raMC |title=Design Risk Management |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |year=2010 |isbn=978-1-4443-1890-6 |first=Stuart |last=Summerhayes |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title=The Forth Bridge |first=Wilhem |last=Westhofen |url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/The_Forth_Bridge |publisher=Offices of \"Engineering\" |year=1890 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Wills |first=Elspeth M. |title=The Briggers: The Story of the Men Who Built the Forth Bridge |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JY79PQAACAAJ |year=2009 |publisher=Birlinn |isbn=978-1-84158-761-5 |ref=harv}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite magazine |first=Peter |last=Kelly |title=A mountain of scrap for Serpell? |magazine=[[RAIL (magazine)|Rail Enthusiast]] |publisher=EMAP National Publications |date=April 1983 |pp=34\u201339 |oclc=49957965}}\n* {{cite book |last=MacKay |first=Sheila |title=The Forth Bridge: A Picture History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sdsVkgAACAAJ |year=2011 |publisher=Birlinn |isbn=978-1-84158-935-0}}\n* {{cite book | chapterurl=http://www.railwaywondersoftheworld.com/forth-bridge.html | chapter=The Forth Bridge| title=Railway Wonders of the World | year=1935 | pages=432\u2013441 | url=http://www.railwaywondersoftheworld.com/ |editor=Winchester, Clarence}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://digital.nls.uk/74570306 40 black-and-white photographs] of the construction of the Forth Bridge taken in 1886\u20131887 by Philip Phillips at [[National Library of Scotland]]\n* [http://www.forth-bridges.co.uk/forth-bridge.html Forth Bridge] at Forth Bridges Visitor Centre Trust\n* {{Structurae|id=20000024|title=Forth Rail Bridge}}\n* [http://www.scottishpoetrylibrary.org.uk/poetry/poems/construction-forth-railway-bridge-1882-1890 Scottish Poetry Library: Poetry Map of Scotland] (Firth of Forth): ''The Construction of the Forth Bridge, 1882\u20131890'', by Colin Donati\n\n{{Transport in Edinburgh}}\n{{World Heritage Sites in the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1890]]\n[[Category:Cantilever bridges]]\n[[Category:Category A listed buildings in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Category A listed buildings in Fife]]\n[[Category:Transport in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Railway bridges in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Railway bridges in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Listed bridges in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Historic Civil Engineering Landmarks]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Sites in Scotland]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Sites in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Fife]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Firth of Forth]]\n[[Category:South Queensferry]]\n[[Category:1890 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "DocWatson42", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRestoration:Performed minor cleanup, in part perMOS:NUMNOTES.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forth_Bridge"}
